INSERT INTO `nodes` VALUES (2,NULL,1,'About','about','<p>This is an example of a Croogo page, you could edit this to put information about yourself or your site.</p>','',1,'',0,0,0,'/about','',0,1,2,'','page','2009-12-25 22:00:00','2009-12-25 22:00:00'),(3,NULL,1,'Sample Post','sample-post','<p><strong>Lorem Ipsum</strong> is simply dummy text of the printing and  typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry\'s standard dummy  text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of  type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not  only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting,  remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with  the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more  recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker  including versions of Lorem Ipsum.</p>\r\n<p>[Modified by WeatherphBehavior]</p>','',1,NULL,2,0,1,'/blog/sample-post',NULL,0,1,2,'','blog','2012-06-04 11:32:37','2012-06-04 11:25:00'),(4,NULL,1,'Intro to Typhoon Climatology','intro-to-typhoon-climatology','<p>Tropical Cyclones have been a part of Filipino culture since time immemorial, since the Philippines is located within the tropics, surrounded by large sea and ocean basins namely the Western Pacific Ocean, The Philippine and South China Seas. These bodies of water are breeding grounds of tropical cyclones.</p>\r\n<p>An average of 20 tropical cyclones enter the Philippine Area of Responsibility (PAR), where 10 cross the country (1948-2004 mean average &sbquo;based on PAGASA Statistics)&sbquo; bringing destruction to properties and loss of lives.</p>','',1,NULL,2,0,1,'/blog/intro-to-typhoon-climatology',NULL,0,3,4,'','blog','2012-06-04 13:58:01','2012-06-04 13:57:00'),(5,NULL,2,'WORST TYPHOONS OF THE PHILIPPINES (Spanish Period / 1617-1876)','worst-typhoons-of-the-philippines-spanish-period--1617-1876','<p>To thumb through the old logbooks containing the chronicles of past typhoons that had visited the Philippines is to re-live the vivid description of nature\'s fierce beauty from a safe distance.<br /><br />The storm documents covering a three-century span of history show that, for some strange reason, the then sparsely populated island of Samar was already the favorite haunt of the most destructive Titans from the Sea. Over this 300-year period, seven of the 13 mightiest storms smashed Samar. <br /><br />The Philippine Storm Logbook, 1617 to 1876 - in capsule, reads:<br /><br />OCTOBER 10-15, 1617 - Six large ships were reduced to floundering hulks by a mighty tidal-wave-generating sea churner off Marinduque.<br /><br />APRIL 28-MAY 5, 1866 - A rampaging whirlwind smashed the provinces of the Bicol Region, Southern Luzon, Masbate, Panay and Mindoro. In Manila, the barometer plummeted to a record low of 746.62 mm.<br /><br />MAY 4-5, 1870 - A devastating tempest battered Samar and Leyte islands, destroying 400 houses and 15 bridges as another smashing hurricane was dismantling 247 houses in Negros, sinking 13 fishing trawlers and five schooners as it stampeded over the Iloilo seacoasts.<br /><br />JUNE 24, 1871 - A cyclone of unusual fury hit Southern Luzon, Central Luzon and Samar. Big buildings were destroyed and several schooners were sunk or slammed against the shores.<br /><br />OCTOBER 12, 1872 - This one hammered Samar with a sustained ferocity for eight whole hours, crushing houses and drowning agricultural crops with its surging floodwaters before turning with the same great energy to topple towering trees and level down whole towns in southern Luzon.<br /><br />MARCH 4-5, 1874 - The first of this year\'s biggest churners scraped areas in Samar as it passed Panay Island; in one place, Laoang, only two houses remained standing, and as it hit Capiz province, even strong buildings and churches were severely damaged.<br /><br />DECEMBER 25, 1874 - What a terrible Christmas it was! A violent tropical tornado came howling over Misamis, Northern Mindanao and screaming onto Cebu; \"uprooting\" a stone church and mortar buildings; running a huge naval ship destroyer aground; dislodging massive stone docks of Cebu.<br /><br />JANUARY 1, 1875 - A raging tropical cyclone battered down bridges, destroyed roads in Samar completing its New Year\'s Day bash by raking towns on the far northern suburb of Manila.<br /><br />NOVEMBER 25-27, 1876 - A frightful hurricane-generating surging tidal waves rampaging rivers took a heavy toll in agricultural crops and livestock, sweeping away 2,500 houses in the then still sparsely populated areas of Mindanao and the Visayas.<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br />SOURCE: PAGASA; featured in the article \"Everything You\'ve Always Wanted to Know About Typhoons\". FILIPINO HERITAGE: The Making of a Nation by Lahing Pilipino Publishing Inc.,1977.</p>\r\n<p>[Modified by WeatherphBehavior]</p>','',1,NULL,2,1,1,'/blog/worst-typhoons-of-the-philippines-spanish-period--1617-1876',NULL,0,5,6,'','blog','2012-06-04 18:26:37','2012-06-04 14:42:00'),(15,NULL,1,'Zamboanga City','zamboanga','            <h3>Asia’s Latin City</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/zamboangaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Located at the southernmost tip of the Zamboanga Peninsula, Zamboanga City is bounded in the north by the provinces of Zamboanga Sibugay and Zamboanga del Norte, in the west by the Sulu Sea, in the east by Sibugay Bay, and in the south by the Basilan Strait.\r\n            </p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/zamboangaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h3>Zamboanga City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Discover Las Islas de Sta. Cruz. Composed of the Great and Little Islands, it lures foreign and domestic tourists with its pink coral sand (actually a creamy fine sand mixed with red pulverized coral). It takes only a 15-minute travel by speed- boat to get to these islands. The islands are likewise perfect for snorkeling and diving.\r\n                </li><li>2. Visit the city’s heritage zones which house the oldest historical structure in the city - the Fort Pilar Shrine dating back to 1635 and experience the calm and serenity witnessed by the local and visiting pilgrims. Adjacent to the Shrine is the National Museum showing the heritage and history of the city and its culture. One will not also miss the historical land- mark of the city – the City Hall. Constructed in 1905, it was completed and inaugurated in 1907 during the administra- tion of Brig. Gen. Tasker Bliss, the second governor of the Moro Province. Impressive architectural details surround and fill this remarkable building.\r\n                    Within the same vicinity, shop at Plaza del Pilar, Zamboanga’s Pasalubong Center, and dine at the People’s Park by the bay. Afterwards, dance the night away at Paseo del Mar.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit the Pasonanca Park. It was created by Gen. Pershing who fell in love with the natural terrain of the place. Situ- ated on an elevated area of some 500 feet above sea level overlooking by verdant mountains and rolling hills. The park consists of three swimming pools, a camp site, the famous Tree House built in the 1960s, an aviary, and, the Jardin Maria Clara Lobregat with its laminar shooting jet fountains, City Museum and the Butterfly Garden.\r\n                </li><li>4. Feast on a wide array of seafood cuisine such as the famous Curacha, the red-meaty crab found solely in the deep waters of Zamboanga. Try the Seafood Paella and other seafood cuisine such as crabs, prawns, shrimps and shells to complete your seafood fiesta. Do not miss Satti, a southern delicacy that comes in tamo (rice steamed in coconut leaves) and skewers of beef or chicken served in a bowl of Sambal (thick hot & spicy sauce). Satti is best eaten as breakfast, a perfect way to start your day in Zamboanga City.\r\n                </li><li>5. Trek to Merloquet Falls. With just fifteen-minute trek, discover the wondrous water falls in the highland sitio of Merlo- quet in Barangay Sibulao.\r\n                    From Manila, Zamboanga City’s accessibility by sea is made possible by an overnight trip with WG&A Superferry and Negros Navigation’s weekly schedule.\r\n                    Also, the City is connected to the Strong Republic Nautical Highway via the port of Puluan in Dapitan City. Thus, Zam- boanga City can be reached by land travel via the RO-RO facility at Puluan. The Ceres Liner provides bus travels to and from Manila to Zamboanga City.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Zamboanga City</p> <p>Population: 774,407 (2007)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Zamboanga is accessible by air, sea, and land. From Manila, there are daily flights of major airlines.</p>\r\n            <p>There are also flights to and from Zamboanga City to Cebu City. Cebu Pacific Air has seven flights a week from Zamboanga City to Cebu City while AirPhil Express has 14 flights from Zambo- anga City to Cebu City (January 2011 flight schedules).</p>\r\n            <p>Other places that have flight routes to Zamboanga City include Davao City (18 flights a week), Tawi-Tawi (seven flights a week) and Jolo (three flights a week). Just recently a low budget carrier, Aero Majestic Airways has opened air route to and from Zambo- anga City and Cagayan de Oro City. Zest Air will open its routes to Zamboanga City by December 2011.\r\n            </p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit\r\n            </h4><ol><li>1. October is the city’s busiest and the most dynamic when the City celebrates the Zamboanga Hermosa Festival, popularly called by the Zamboangueños as Fiesta Pilar, the biggest and grandest festivity. It starts on the first week of October and peaks on the 12th day, the Feast Day of the Nuestra Señora La Virgen del Pilar, the patroness of Zamboanga City.\r\n                    To make the celebration more vibrant, the city government orga- nizes events such as the famous Regatta, a traditional vinta race featuring the city’s colorful vinta sails, street dance and float parade, dance competition, art exhibit, dancesport competition, mascot de Zamboanga presentation, and competition WOW sardinas, and the prestigious Chabacano Song Festival.\r\n                </li><li>2. February 26 is the Dia de Zamboanga Festival. It is the celebration of the charter anniversary of the City. February 26 marks the day that the first set of city officials was installed into in office in 1937.\r\n                </li><li>3. Summertime is also the best time in Zamboanga as it sizzles up the summer heat with great outdoor and family-oriented activities which include the Festival de las Bellas y Flores - the City’s version of the Santacruzan.\r\n                </li><li>4. Pascua na Zamboanga Festival – the celebration of Christ- mas and the holiday season are made more meaningful with the conduct of the Christmas Festival dubbed Pascua na Zambo- anga. The City is famous for the lighted City Hall which annually draws more tourists not only from the region and other parts of the country but also from different parts of the world. The Pas- cua na Zamboanga culminates with a Grand Fireworks Display at the Paseo del Mar at the strike of 12:00 midnight to welcome the new year.</li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n                <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office, Sunken Garden, JS Alano Street, Zamboanga City with telephone nos. (062) 992-3007 or visit website at <a href=\"http://www.zamboanga.ph\">www.zamboanga.ph</a> or connect on facebook and multiply: ciuzamboanga@facebook.com or www.zamboangatourism@multiply.com\r\n            </p>\r\n','Located at the southernmost tip of the Zamboanga Peninsula, Zamboanga City is bounded in the north by the provinces of Zamboanga Sibugay and Zamboanga del Norte, in the west by the Sulu Sea, in the east by Sibugay Bay, and in the south by the Basilan Strait.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/zamboanga',NULL,0,1,2,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:07:32','2012-09-12 05:15:00'),(16,NULL,1,'Vigan City','vigan','<img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/viganCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Vigan is an island which used to be detached from the mainland by three rivers - the great Abra River, the Mestizo River and the Govantes River. It is unique among the Philippine towns because it is the country’s most extensive and only surviving historic city that dates back to the 16th century Spanish colonial period.</p>\r\n            <p>Vigan was an important coastal trading post in the pre-colonial times. Long before the Spanish galleons, Chinese junks sailing from the South China Sea came to Isla de Bigan through the Mestizo River that surrounded the island. On board were sea- faring merchants that came to barter exotic goods from Asian kingdoms in exchange for gold, beeswax and other mountain products brought down by natives from the Cordilleras. Vigan was also a vital trading post in the Spanish Colonial Period.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1572, Don Juan de Salcedo arrived in Vigan, established Villa Fernandina de Bigan and made it the capital of Ylokos covering most of Northern Luzon. In 1758, the seat of Nueva Segovia was transferred from Lallo, Cagayan to Vigan by a Spanish Royal Decree elevating Vigan into a city named Ciudad Fernandina de Bigan. For more than three centuries, the city was the center of political, religious and cultural activities in the North. Vigan was inscribed in the UNESCO World Heritage List of Sites and Monu- ments on December 2, 1999.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, Vigan is home to proud Bigueños who welcome everyone with warm smiles to the city where traditions blend with the demands of the times.</p>\r\n            <p>Images and sounds of modernity have established their pres- ence in the City, however, they are unable to drown the stillness and elegance of the Past. Vigan City opened itself to change but it has not sacrificed the wealth of its heritage. It is the ability of coping with the Present amidst the bounds set by centuries-old legacy that makes Vigan a living, historic city.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Vigan City Fiesta and Longganisa Festival (Jan. 19-30) – commemorating the Feast of the Conversion of Saint Paul (Jan. 25) and the anniversary of the Vigan’s Cityhood (Jan. 22) featuring the famed Longganisa Festival.\r\n                </li><li>2 .Viva Vigan Binatbatan Festival of the Arts (First week of May) – a week long Arts festivities in one of the biggest and most colorful attractions in the North celebrating the pride of Bigueños in their unique and historic city.\r\n                </li><li>3. World Heritage Cities Solidarity Week and Cultural Festi- val (First to second week of September) – A celebration of all UNESCO world heritage cities highlighted by significant events.\r\n                </li><li>4. Raniag: The Vigan Twilight Festival (First week of November) - Raniag means light, which connotes the light that Bigueños offer to the Lord in thanksgiving.\r\n                </li><li>5. Artes ita Pascua and Vigan Torch and Lantern Parade (Every December) - This festival features various arts trainings for Bigueños to continue strengthening cultural awareness and appreciation.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/viganCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Vigan City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Experience the Bigueño cuisine. Vigan is home to good restaurants where visitors can bask in authentic Ilocano food like bagnet, Vigan Longganisa, Sinanglao and other dishes. These restaurants are Los Majitos Street Dining, Café Leona, Uno Grille & Lilong and Lilang Café. The Empanadaan at Plaza Burgos serve the famous Vigan empanada and other delicacies.\r\n                </li><li>2. Explore the museums. Vigan has six museums/memorabilia where tourists can visit namely: Burgos National Museum, Museo Nueva Segovia, Museo San Pablo, Pres. Elpidio Quirino Memorabilia, Crisologo Museum and Buridek Childrens’ Museum. One may also visit the traditional industries of Vigan like Burnay (jar) making, Abel Handloom Weaving and the terracotta red clay industry where visitors can try their skills in these centuries old crafts.\r\n                </li><li>3. Travel back in time with Vigan Heritage River Cruise, a 45-minute river tour, where visitors can learn Vigan’s origin, his- torical background and other significant information while passing through five life-sized tableaus explaining the histori- cal timeline of Vigan. Or Ride the calesa, a horse drawn carriage and travel back in time while strolling at Calle Crisologo.\r\n                </li><li>4. Shop for souvenirs in Calle Crisologo, the best place to shop souvenir, antiques, and furniture.\r\n                </li><li>5. Learn best practices in local governance like heritage conservation, child friendly governance, environmental man- agement, disaster preparedness among others. Vigan City is one of the most awarded local government units in good governance.\r\n                </li></ol><h4>Profile</h4>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Vigan</p> <p>Population: 47,246 (Aug. 2007 census)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there\r\n            </h4><p>From Manila, Vigan can be reached by air (45 minutes) with domestic flights via SEA Air leaving Manila twice a week for Vigan City. Other domestic flights leave Manila daily for Laoag City in Ilocos Norte, which is an hour and a half ride by bus or arranged vehicles to Vigan.</p>\r\n            <p>By land, Manila to Vigan is a comfortable eight-hour ride along the scenic Manila-Ilocos Highway. Air-conditioned Partas Bus, Aniceto Bus, Dominion Bus Lines and Viron Tran- sit regularly ply Manila-Vigan route and vice versa.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol><li>1. January to May and November to December\r\n                </li></ol><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n                <p>Please contact the City Tourism & Investment Promotion Office at telephone nos. (077) 722-8776 and/or 722-8771- 75. Visit website at <a href=\"http://www.vigancity.gov.ph\">www.vigancity.gov.ph</a>. Email queries at admin@vigancity.gov.ph.</p>\r\n','Vigan is unique among the Philippine towns because it is the country’s most extensive and only surviving historic city that dates back to the 16th century Spanish colonial period.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/vigan',NULL,0,3,4,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:10:51','2012-09-12 06:08:00'),(17,NULL,1,'Victorias City','victorias','<img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/victoriasCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Victorias had been a settlement even before the coming of the Spaniards. The earliest inhabitants were Negritos, the aborigines of the place. When the Spaniards came, they called the place Malihaw because of the abundance of Malihaw trees situated at the mouth of the Malihaw River. It was in 1880 when the place was again renamed Victorias after a mysterious lady appeared who was believed to have repulsed marauders. The lady was known as Nuestra Señora de las Victorias. Literally, Victorias means victories.</p>\r\n            <p>Victorias City is considered as the sweetest city of sugarlandia that is Negros. It houses the sprawling Victorias Milling Com- pany (VMC), Asia’s largest integrated raw and refined sugar manufacturer. Within the VMC compound is the world’s famous “Angry Christ” mural painting at the St. Joseph the Worker Church; an antique steam locomotive engine, “iron dinosaur” and an 18-hole golf course classified as PAR 71.</p>\r\n            <p>The City has been a sports hub as the Philippine Basketball Asso- ciation holds often its games in the City Sports and Amusement Complex.</p>\r\n            <p>The City has been acclaimed as the home of PBA in the province of Negros Occidental. With its 8,000-seat capacity coliseum, four dug outs, galleries, four VIP rooms, 12-lane bowling center, food court, fitness gym, billiard hall and Olympic standard swimming pool, the City is truly fit for sports and recreation</p>\r\n            <p>The City is also naturally gifted with rich marine resources and forest that rest within the Northern Negros Natural Park, the last forest frontier of Negros Island and the largest watershed of the Province. Within its upland area nestles the Gawahon Eco-Park, famous for its scenic views, cool climate, primary growth forest and seven pristine waterfalls. The City’s true richness however, lies in its people, with fine taste, charm, hospitality, creativity and great vision.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Gawahon Eco-Park is considered as a haven to nature lovers with seven magnificent waterfalls, fresh, cool air and lush vegeta- tion in an elevation of about 800 meters above sea level topped by primary growth forest which is part of the Northern Negros Natural Park, the Province’s largest watershed.\r\n                </li><li>2. Kadalag-an Festival is held every March 21 in commemoration of Victorias’ Cityhood. Kadalag-an is a word adopted by Victorias City for its charter celebration. It means victory and symbolizes the triumph of a municipality turned into a city against the adversities and struggle for peace, progress and development and attainment of its vision\r\n                </li><li>3. Malihaw Festival is the annual fiesta of Victorias celebrated every April 26 in honor of the city’s patroness Nuestra Señora de las Victorias. This is highlighted by a fluvial parade of images of the Patroness along the shoreline of the City.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/victoriasCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Victorias City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Stay in Gawahon Eco-Park and experience what Victorias City’s nature has to offer. It has seven pristine waterfalls, a magnificent upland view of the City and a fresh cool breeze from the mountain top.\r\n                </li><li>2. See the “Angry Christ” mural, a world-famed liturgical art masterpiece done by Alfonso Ossorio, artist-son of VMC founder Don Miguel Ossorio. It is located inside the church of St. Joseph the Worker. The “Angry Christ” shows craggy- faced Christ in bold primary colors.\r\n                </li><li>3. Tour Victorias Milling Company’s huge agro-industrial complex which was established in 1919. It was the first sugar mill in the Philippines to earn ISO 9002 certification.\r\n                </li><li>4. Play at the VMC Golf and Country Club, an 18-hole golf course, which is a challenging place for golf aficionados. 5. Enjoy the City’s Malihaw Festival in April and Kadalag-an festivals in March.\r\n                </li></ol><h4>Profile</h4>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Victorias City</p> <p>Population: 88, 149\r\n            <p/><h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Victorias City is located 34 kilometers north of Bacolod City, Negros Occidental. It can be reached within 45 minutes by private or public utility vehicle.\r\n            </p><h4>Best time to visit\r\n            </h4><ol><li>1. March (City’s Charter Anniversary)\r\n                </li></ol><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the CCIO, Victorias City Hall at telephone nos. (034) 399-3627 or email at malihaw@yahoo.com</p>\r\n','Victorias had been a settlement even before the coming of the Spaniards. The earliest inhabitants were Negritos, the aborigines of the place.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/victorias',NULL,0,5,6,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:11:46','2012-09-12 06:11:00'),(18,NULL,1,'City of Valenzuela','valenzuela','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfValenzuela1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The City traces its long colorful history to the old town of Polo, then part of the province of Bulacan, which dated back from 1620s. It began as a tiny settlement of small fishermen along the coast of Manila Bay. Polo was later renamed Valenzuela, in honor of its most famous son, Dr. Pio Valenzuela, one of the triumvirates of the Katipunan.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1975, it formed part of the Metropolitan Manila after its creation. In 1998, it became a City. Valenzuela once a quaint provincial town during the colonial times, now stands as a mod- ern and bustling hub of wide array of industries.\r\n            </p><p>Valenzuela City is known as the northern gateway to Metro Ma- nila, a distinction which stems from having two major highways traversing the City, MacArthur Highway and the North Luzon Expressway. It is also regarded as one of the country’s top resi- dential, cultural and business destinations.\r\n            </p><h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Arkong Bato (Barangay Arkong Bato). This stone arch found along M.H. Del Pilar Street, was built by the Americans in 1910, and served as the boundary marker between Rizal and Bulacan provinces. Today, the Arkong Bato marks the boundary between Barangay Santulan in the City of Malabon and the arch’s name- sake, Barangay Arkong Bato in Valenzuela. The arch is a land- mark that witnessed the gradual transformation of the city.\r\n                </li><li>2. Bell Tower of San Diego De Alcala Church (Barangay Pobla- cion). The San Diego de Alcala Church at Barangay Poblacion, the center of the old town of Polo, was the first Parish of the city. The belfry, or bell tower, is a cultural and religious relic of the bygone Spanish era, a reminder of the 390 year-history of the town, now a bustling City.\r\n                </li><li>3. Residence of Dr. Pio Valenzuela (Barangay Pariancillo Villa). Dr. Pio Valenzuela was born in this house on July 11, 1869. Found along Velilla Street in Barangay Pariancillo Villa, this house serves as a silent witness to the life and times of the most prominent son of the City.\r\n                </li><li>4. Museo Valenzuela (Fatima Avenue, Barangay Marulas). Museo Valenzuela is one of the city’s main historical and cultural landmarks and houses a vast collection of artifacts and memora- bilia that traces Valenzuela’s rich culture and history.\r\n                </li><li>5. National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima (Fatima Avenue, Ba- rangay Marulas). Declared as the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima, it was also declared a tourist site in 1982 by the Depart- ment of Tourism. The Shrine houses the blessed pilgrim image of Our Lady of Fatima.\r\n                </li><li>6. Grand Marian Exhibit and Procession (Opens Every First Sunday of May). The Grand Marian Exhibit has been running for more than a decade. It is being participated by icon camareros or owners, not only from Valenzuela City, but from the neighbor- ing cities and provinces all over the country. On May 13 on the actual Feast of Our Lady of Fatima, a Grand Procession featuring some of the featured icons is held after a High Mass in honor of The Virgin.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfValenzuela2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of Valenzuela’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Win exciting prizes when you catch the biggest tilapia, bangus and cream dory fishes during the Mayor WIN Fun Fishing Tournament in April. Or spend time with family and friends while waiting for the next catch in Valenzuela City’s fishing havens.\r\n                </li><li>2. Pray for a “lover” during the Mano Po, San Roque: Sayawan sa Calle in May.\r\n                </li><li>3. Be solemnized by The Virgin’s grace while visiting the Grand Marian Exhibit in May.\r\n                </li><li>4. Attend the mass at the National Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima and See the image of The Virgin which blessed the People Power Revolution in 1986.\r\n                </li><li>5. Satisfy your palate with the sweet and succulent, the uniquely Valenzuela-owned rice cake, Putong Polo\r\n                </li></ol><h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Valenzuela\r\n            </p><p>Population: 623,695 (projected population, 2010)\r\n            </p><h4>How to get there\r\n            </h4><p>Valenzuela City is about 10 to 15 minutes from EDSA- Monumento via MacArthur Highway by jeepney or by bus, 10 to 15 minutes from Balintawak Clover Leaf via NLEX and Mindanao Avenue-NLEX by any mode of transportation.\r\n            </p><h4>For travel information\r\n            </h4><p>Please contact the Public Information Office at telephone nos. (02) 292-9168, (02)352-1000 local 1132/1102; and the City Cultural and Tourism Office (CATO)at telephone nos. (02) 293-8486, (02) 352-1000 local 1825. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"http://www.valenzuela.gov.ph\">www.valenzuela.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','The City traces its long colorful history to the old town of Polo, then part of the province of Bulacan, which dated back from 1620s. It began as a tiny settlement of small fishermen along the coast of Manila Bay.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/valenzuela',NULL,0,7,8,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:16:04','2012-09-12 06:15:00'),(19,NULL,1,'Urdaneta City','urdaneta','            <h3>The Gateway to the North</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/urdanetaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The City of Urdaneta is known as the Gateway to the North owing to its strategic location. All roads lead to the City when travelling to the cool pines of Baguio City, the historic sites of the Ilocos provinces, the beaches of Dagupan City, and the religious center that is Manaoag.</p>\r\n            <p>Urdaneta City is also home to the biggest livestock market and the largest fruits and vegetable trading center in the North. It is also home to the first community college in the Philippines. The city is also known as an investment center and a fast-emerging education capital.</p>\r\n            <p>Urdaneta was named after Fray Andres de Urdaneta, the Span- ish friar, cosmographer, and navigator. In 2010, the City was cited as the Cleanest, Greenest and Safest City in Region I by the Regional Development Council.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Urdaneta City Fiesta – December 1-8 2. City Charter Anniversary – March 21 3. Dumayo Festival – March 21\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/urdanetaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Urdaneta City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Join in the fun and festivities of the weeklong Urdaneta City Fiesta on December 1-8. Day and night activities include school-based cultural competitions, folk dancing and calisthenics, beauty pageants, sports exhibitions, street concert and an agro-industrial fair showcasing the best products of each barangay.\r\n                </li><li>2. Partake of the various cultures and cuisines of the different regional groups through the Dumayo Festival, the highlight of Urdaneta’s City Charter Anniversary every March 21. Launched in 2010, the Festival pays homage to the Batangue- nos, Igorots, Muslims, and other regional groups who have made Urdaneta their home and who have contributed to city’s economic and cultural development.\r\n                </li><li>3. Savor local delicacies such as tupig (glutinous rice and coconut mixture) and tinapa (smoked fish).\r\n                </li><li>4. Buy fruits, vegetables and spices at the Bagsakan Market, the biggest wholesale market in the North, at very afford- able prices. Buy in bulk for trading or by retail as pasalubong. Everything you need is in the 24/7 Bagsakan Market.\r\n                </li><li>5. Relax at the Lisland Rainforest, where age-old trees are in harmony with the resort ambiance, or dine at the famous Matutina’s Restaurant, home to the best seafoods and most sumptuous cuisines, or visit the Pasalubong Center where local products, delicacies and must-haves can be bought.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Urdaneta</p> <p>Population: 120,785 (2007)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there\r\n            </h4><p>From Manila, Urdaneta is 186 kilometers away or a four- hour bus ride or a three-hour ride by private vehicle.\r\n                Urdaneta City is 10 minutes away from Manaoag town, 45 minutes from Dagupan City, 1.5 hours from Baguio City, and four hours from the Ilocos provinces.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol><li>1. December 1-8 (City Fiesta in honor of its Patroness Saint the Immaculate Conception).\r\n                </li></ol><h4>For travel information\r\n            </h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office at telephone nos. (075) 568-3001 and (075) 568-3002. For further inquiries, please visit the city’s official website at <a href=\"http://www.urdaneta-city.com.ph\" >www.urdaneta-city.com.ph</a></p>\r\n','The City of Urdaneta is known as the Gateway to the North owing to its strategic location. All roads lead to the City when travelling to the cool pines of Baguio City, the historic sites of the Ilocos provinces, the beaches of Dagupan City, and the religious center that is Manaoag.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/urdaneta',NULL,0,9,10,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:17:09','2012-09-12 06:16:00'),(20,NULL,1,'Tuguegarao City','tuguegarao','<h3>The Premier Ybanag City</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tuguegaraoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Tuguegarao City is the main entry to the Province of Cagayan.</p>\r\n            <p>It was a small settlement in terms of population but was a big territory until the 1850s. It was governed as a barangay until the Spaniards gave it the status of mission-pueblo on May 09, 1604, making it one of the political units of the Province of Cagayan. It is politically subdivided into 49 barangays, 29 of which are urban. Centro 1 to 12 (Poblacion) comprise the city’s Central Business District.</p>\r\n            <p>Tuguegarao City’s economy has gradually shifted from agricul- tural to secondary/tertiary economic activities such as trading, commerce and services within the past three decades. The shift was ushered by Tuguegarao’s role as the Regional Government Center and the Center of Commerce in Northern Luzon. As a result, Tuguegarao City has been awarded as one of the Top 10 Most Competitive Cities in the Philippines by the Asian Institute of Management.</p>\r\n            <p>Furthermore, Tuguegarao City has developing tourist attractions. Its business services and social amenities coupled with its advanced infrastructure make the City an important regional tourism service center.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Every August, Tuguegarao City celebrates the Pavvurulun Fes- tival, which connotes togetherness or unity. Some of the lined-up activities are Pansit Eating Contest, Bangkarera (Boat Race) and Nuang (Carabao) and Kabayu (Horse) Karera (Race)\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tuguegaraoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Tuguegarao City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Taste the famous “Pansit Batil-Patung” (egg on top of the pansit)\r\n                </li><li>2. Visit Sts. Peter and Paul Cathedral and Ermita de San Jacinto.\r\n                </li><li>3. Try the delicious longganisa.\r\n                </li><li>4. Buy the cacao balls, baked peanuts, carabao milk candy and other local products.\r\n                </li></ol><h4>Profile</h4>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Tuguegarao City</p> <p>Population: 157, 219 (2007)</p>\r\n            <h3>How to get there</h3>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Tuguegarao City is approximately 483 kilo- meters, about 65 minutes by air travel and about 10 hours by land, through the Maharlika Highway. Buses are ample available both ordinary and air-conditioned.</p>\r\n            <p>Air Philippines and Cebu Pacific have daily flights from Ma- nila to Tuguegarao City.\r\n            </p><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Office of the Tuguegarao City Mayor’s Office at tel. nos. (078) 844-2894 loc. 882 or 883. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"http://www.tuguegaraocity.gov.ph\" >www.tuguegaraocity.gov.ph</a>.\r\n            </p>\r\n','Tuguegarao City is the main entry to the Province of Cagayan.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/tuguegarao',NULL,0,11,12,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:19:10','2012-09-12 06:17:00'),(21,NULL,1,'Toledo City','toledo','            <h3>The Premier and Liveable City in the West Coast of Cebu\r\n            </h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/toledoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Toledo City lies on Tañon strait across Negros Island and the City of San Carlos, Negros Occidental. It is home to the Philippines’ largest copper mine, owned by Atlas Consolidated Mining and Development Corporation.</p>\r\n            <p>Toledo City is connected with Cebu City, the provincial capital, by two stretches off road crossing the rugged spine of the island: the Naga-Uling Road and the alternate Manipis Road. A ferry also runs between San Carlos and Toledo. During the harvest season, migrant sugar workers travel from Toledo to San Carlos to work in the sugar fields of Negros. The city’s small seaport provides Toledo with commercial inter-island service. Between 1980-1990, the population grew by 31 percent, more than the national growth rate of 26%.</p>\r\n            <p>The city was chartered in 1960.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Toledo City Annual Fiesta</li>\r\n                <li>2. Hinulawan Festival</li>\r\n                <li>3. Sinulog Festival</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/toledoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Toledo City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Request for a mine tour at the Carmen Copper Corporation, one of the major industries in the city.\r\n                </li><li>2. Take the short lake cruise at the Malubog dam, a man-made lake in Barangay Gen. Climaco, Toledo City.\r\n                </li><li>3. Visit the Unity Park in Barangay Poblacion and try out Toledo City’s own version of the famous ‘Lartian barbecues’ of Cebu City.\r\n                </li><li>4. Take a night stroll at the Espinosa Boulevard in Barangay Poblacion and enjoy the relaxing view of the City at night time over a cup of coffee at Café Royale\r\n                </li><li>5. Visit the Parish Church of St. John of Sahagun, which has been declared a Shrine by Cardinal Ricardo Vidal, Archbishop of Cebu\r\n                </li></ol><h4>Tourism Profile</h4>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Toledo City</p> <p>Population: 157,000</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Toledo is located at the South of Cebu, an hour and a half drive from Cebu City. The V-hire vans and public buses are available as modes of transportation at the City Link and South Bus Terminals. Nearest route from Cebu City to Toledo is via the Naga-Uling Road.</p>\r\n','Toledo City lies on Tañon strait across Negros Island and the City of San Carlos, Negros Occidental. It is home to the Philippines’ largest copper mine, owned by Atlas Consolidated Mining and Development Corporation.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/toledo',NULL,0,13,14,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:20:33','2012-09-12 06:19:00'),(22,NULL,1,'Tangub City','tangub','<h3>Christmas Symbols Capitals of the Philippines\r\n            </h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tangubCity1.png\"alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Tangub City is hidden within at the southern curve of the D- shaped province of Misamis Occidental. It is bounded on the north by Mt. Malindang Range, on the south by Panguil Bay, on the east by Ozamiz City and on the west by the municipality of Bonifacio. It is composed of 55 barangays, 23 are urban and 32 are rural.\r\n                The ultimate goal of the City is the improvement of quality of life and its constituents through total human development and where people have equal access to the benefits, opportunities and resources.</p>\r\n            <p>The city’s vision is to become the agribusiness and learning center for skills and technology in Northwestern Mindanao. Its mission is to optimally develop and utilize the city’s human resources by integrating people-centered development to all sectors within the framework of good governance, ecological balance, sound moral values, sustainability and socio-economic development.\r\n            </p><h4>Best time to visit\r\n            </h4><ol><li>1. February – Charter anniversary and inter-collegiate games - A twin event held annually in celebration of the city’s charter day every last week of the month.\r\n                </li><li>2. September 29 – Dalit Festival – a thanksgiving festival to the City’s Patron Saint Michael the Archangel participated by different schools of the city.\r\n                </li><li>3. December – The first day of December is the start of the Christmas Symbols Festival. The festival is a month-long celebration featuring giant Christmas symbols, Christmas arches, giant Christmas lanterns (parols) displayed in the city from November to January. It is an exhibition of Tangubanon ingenuity and creativity.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tangubCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Tangub City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Prepare for an exciting adventure such as Malindang trail trekking, boating, swimming and zipline. Points of interest include Hoyohoy Highland Park found at the foot of Mt. Malindang Range where one can have the panoramic view of Panguil Bay, the cities of Ozamiz and Tangub and the neighboring places of Zamboanga del Sur, Lanao del Norte, and Iligan City.\r\n                </li><li>2. Dance with the Sinanduloy Cultural Troupe. It is an award winning cultural troupe managed by local government of Tangub\r\n                </li><li>3. Eat luscious evergreen Tangub mangoes, tasty mudcrabs and shrimps, exotic seafood like igud, ubod, and tamban- gongo.\r\n                </li><li>4. Buy any salted mussels/sisi at Centennial Rest Area grounds, galletas from Obut bakery at barangay Sta. Maria, souve- nir and novelty items at City Café 1 and City Café 2 and evergreen mangoes, mudcrabs, prawns, and shrimps from Agora Public Market.\r\n                </li><li>5. Spend a worry-free vacation with the laidback character of the city\r\n                </li></ol><h3>Tourism Profile</h3>\r\n                <p>Official Name: Tangub City </p>\r\n                <p>Population: 56, 644</p>\r\n                <h4>How to get there\r\n            </h4><p>\r\n                From Cagayan De Oro City, take the bus (Rural Transit or Super 5 Bus) from Cagayan De Oro west bound Bus Terminal bound for Dipolog or Ozamiz City. Upon reaching Mukas, La- nao Del Norte, there is a 10-15 minutes barge ride to reach Ozamiz City port, then a jeepney or bus to Tangub City.</p>\r\n            <p>By sea, from Cebu City, an overnight boat trip to the port of Ozamiz City then a jeepney or bus bound to Tangub City. From Manila, a two-night boat trip to the port of Ozamiz City then a jeepney or bus bound for Tangub City.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information\r\n            </h4><p>Please contact the City Tourism Office at telephone nos. (088) 354-1591 or email at tangub_tourism@yahoo.com\r\n                There are no direct flights to Tangub City. However, flights from Manila and Cebu have routes to Cagayan De Oro City, Dipolog City, Ozamiz City, and Pagadian City from where Tangub can be reached by land.</p>\r\n            <p>From Ozamiz City, take the Rural Bus or Suscir Bus located at the Integrated Bus and Jeepney Terminal (IBJT/Agora Terminal) for a roughly 20-minute ride.</p>\r\n            <p>From Pagadian City, take an air-conditioned, deluxe, or stationary bus of Rural Transit, or Super 5 Bus Company that is bound for either Dipolog or Ozamiz. These buses have stopovers in Tangub City.</p>\r\n','Tangub City is hidden within at the southern curve of the D- shaped province of Misamis Occidental. It is bounded on the north by Mt. Malindang Range, on the south by Panguil Bay, on the east by Ozamiz City and on the west by the municipality of Bonifacio. It is composed of 55 barangays, 23 are urban and 32 are rural.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/tangub',NULL,0,15,16,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:22:43','2012-09-12 06:21:00'),(23,NULL,1,'Tagum City','tagum','\r\n            <h3>The Palm City of the Philippines, A Destination for Learning\r\n            </h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tagumCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The socio-economic dynamics of Tagum City is atypical com- pared with other medium-sized cities in Mindanao, or for that matter, the rest of the country. The City has been accorded as one of the Most Competitive Medium-Sized Cities in the Philip- pines and one of the Seven Most Viable and Most Competitive Business Sites in the country.</p>\r\n            <p>Moreover, the City has been successful in augmenting its locally generated revenues from its locally managed economic enter- prise projects reaching to as high as Php 48.9 million pesos in 2007. The revenues from the city economic enterprise have increased to Php 74.4 million pesos in 2010 or almost 24.2% of the total local income of the city which registered at 439.4 mil- lion pesos in the same year.\r\n            </p><p>The development interventions in the City are decisively the product of a forward-looking and result-oriented leadership. In fact, the Honorable Mayor Rey T. Uy is the first elected public official to receive the prestigious Gawad Pag-asa Award from the Civil Service Commission.\r\n                Over and above the tangible evidence of economic growth, the City of Tagum is renowned as a favorite destination for Lakbay- Aral (or educational tour) by officials and functionaries of various local government units from all over the country. Truly, the City of Tagum has prevailed as a “Destination for Learning”.\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Musikahan sa Tagum Festival (February 21-27) – The longest running and inclusive music festival that is participated by Filipino and foreign artists.\r\n                </li><li>2. Durian Festival (During the Durian Fruiting Season in August to September) – Savor the King of the Fruit during the Mindan- ao’s culinary Olympics and be enthralled by the uniqueness and singularity of Durian based culinary showcases.\r\n                </li><li>3. Tagum City River Cruise (Whole year round) – An excur- sion into the “wetlands-in-a-city” to witness the successes of the Mangrove Development and Rehabilitation Program and Community-based Tourism initiatives.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tagumCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Tagum City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Embark on the Tagum City River Cruise and revisit the significance of the “wetlands-in-the-city” and encounter the rich- ness of the cultural traditions of the local community.\r\n                </li><li>2. Experience the Tagum City Night Market and indulge in the best food trip.\r\n                </li><li>3. Embrace the Landmarks of the Tagum, the “Home of Festivals” – including historical, architectural and natural land- marks as well as its tourism products and the treasured Emerald Durian delicacies.\r\n                </li><li>4. Esteem the Sustainability of the City’s Economic Enterprise Projects and the timely delivery of engineering support services.\r\n                </li><li>5. Explore the engaging and successful Reef-to-Ridge Environmental Conservation Program. Learn on several conservation programs like coastal resource management, partnerships in watershed conservation, marine life sanctuary, barangay-based solid-waste management and the successes of the City’s Urban Greening interventions.\r\n                </li></ol><h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Tagum\r\n            </p><h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Located in the Southeastern part of Mindanao, Tagum City can be reached about an hour drive by land from Davao International Airport or from the Sasa Wharf in Davao City. It is about four hours from Butuan City by bus, and about two hours from Mati.\r\n            </p><h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol><li>1. February - Musikahan sa Tagum Festival\r\n                </li><li>2. April to May - Summer Sports Festival and Flores de Tagumenyo</li>\r\n                <li>3. September - Savor the King of the Fruits during the Durian Festival\r\n                </li><li>4. October - Indigenous People’s Festival\r\n                </li><li>5. November to January - Dive the Marine Sanctuary\r\n                </li></ol><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n                <p>Please contact the City Tourism Operations Office, Beach Volleydrome, Rotary Park, Tagum City with telephone nos. (084) 216-2965 and (084) 370-1424 or email at tourism. tagum@gmail.com or tagumcity_tourism@yahoo.com. Visit <a href=\"http://www.musikahansatagum.com\" >www.musikahansatagum.com</a>.\r\n            </p>\r\n','The socio-economic dynamics of Tagum City is atypical com- pared with other medium-sized cities in Mindanao, or for that matter, the rest of the country.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/tagum',NULL,0,17,18,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:23:30','2012-09-12 06:22:00'),(24,NULL,1,'Tacurong City','tacurong','<h3>The City of Goodwill</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tacurongCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Situated at the crossroads of Central Mindanao, the City of Tacurong serves as the gateway to four major cities: General Santos, Cotabato, Davao and Cagayan de Oro.\r\n            <p>Regarded as the educational, financial, and commercial hub of the province of Sultan Kudarat, Tacurong likewise boasts of having a large expanse of agricultural land devoted to major crops, primarily rice; hence the presence of the imposing National Food Authority-Southern Philippines Grains Complex silo, one of the largest in Southeast Asia.</p>\r\n            <p>Since becoming a component city of the Province in 2000, Tacurong City has continued to live up to its vision of becoming a politically mature and economically dynamic city. Peace and security is given paramount importance by the local leadership in attaining its vision.</p>\r\n            <p>The Materials Recovery Facility and Sanitary Landfill of Tacurong, the first to be established in Mindanao, is a testament to the City’s continued quest of protecting the environment. The Baras Bird Sanctuary, home to more than 20,000 herons and egrets, has reinforced the City’s desire of attaining an ecologically balanced community.</p>\r\n            <p>   The Talakudong Festival every September speaks of the splendor of the City’s culture. Performed in exhilarating street dances and field demonstration accompanied with exotic and native sounds of bamboo drums, the festival showcases the City’s unique culture that emphasizes multi-ornamented headgears or hats. Tacurong, which is derived from Talakudong, means a head- covering material.</p>\r\n                <p>    Highlighted by the spectacular fireworks display, the Inugyunay Festival every December is a Christmas celebration of Tacurong- nons as well as homecoming revelry for the balikbayans.\r\n            </p><h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Talakudong Festival (3rd week of September and culminates on September 18 with the street-dancing and field demonstra- tion).\r\n                </li><li>2. The Inugyunay Festival (3rd week of December and culmi- nates on December 23 with fireworks display)\r\n                </li><li>3. Baras Bird Sanctuary (any day and any time of the year)\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/tacurongCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Tacurong City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Visit to the Baras Bird Sanctuary and take a much closer look at the thousands of black-crowned night herons and cattle egrets.\r\n                </li><li>2. See the largest oil palm plantation in the province. Do not miss to pass by the various plantations of African oil palm lined up in perfect symmetry. You also need to see the NFA-SPGC silo, one of the largest rice storage facilities in Southeast Asia, a testa- ment to why Tacurong is still considered a major rice granary in the region.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Satiate your appetite in a wide array selection of native foods offered by many restaurants. Go to VE-JR Aqua Farm and enjoy the deep-fried/sinugba/adobong hito (catfish), kinilaw/chicharon tilapia, the tinolang native na manok cooked in a clay pot, and many others, while at the same time taking pleasure in the soft wind blowing from the surrounding farm.\r\n                </li><li>4. Buy souvenir items and check out the Demi Moores and Patrick Swayzes in the outskirts of the City who keep themselves busy shaping potteries. Our corn husk and water hyacinth byproduct makers are experts in their trades too. You can also see in Barangay San Emmanuel how muscovado (unrefined sugar) is being processed.\r\n                </li><li>5. Visit the City Hall and experience firsthand the warmth and friendliness of city employees. The City is one of the only six local governments to be awarded the Seal of Excellence in Local Governance by the Civil Service Commission (2010) and the Seal of Good Housekeeping by the Department of Interior and Local Government (2011). Also in 2011, the City is the most child-friendly in the Region.\r\n                </li></ol><h4>Place to Visit</h4>\r\n            <p>Notre Dame of Tacurong College National Highway\r\n                (064) 200-3631\r\n            </p><h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Tacurong</p> <p>Population: 479,794 (PDMS 2010 Survey)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there\r\n            </h4><p>Tacurong is located at the center of Central Mindanao. It is 92 kilometers from General Santos city, 96 kilometers from Cotabato City, 178 kilometers from Davao City, and 314 kilometers from Cagayan de Oro City.</p>\r\n            <p>From Manila, one takes a flight to General Santos, the near- est entry point, and make a land trip for two-three hours.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit\r\n            </h4><ol><li>1. September (Talakudong Festival) and December (Inugyunay Festival)</li>\r\n            </ol><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office at telephone nos. (064) 384-2139 or the City Information Office at telephone nos at (064) 384 2628. For further queries, visit the website, at <a href=\"http://www.tacurong.gov.ph\" >www.tacurong.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','Situated at the crossroads of Central Mindanao, the City of Tacurong serves as the gateway to four major cities: General Santos, Cotabato, Davao and Cagayan de Oro.\r\n',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/tacurong',NULL,0,19,20,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:24:14','2012-09-12 06:23:00'),(25,NULL,1,'Sorsogon City','sorsogon','<h3>Sararo, Sarabay sa Progreso\r\n            </h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/sorsogonCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Sorsogon is the capital city of the province of Sorsogon, located at the southernmost tip of Luzon. The City was formed by merging the Bacon and Sorsogon municipalities. It is dubbed as a gateway to Southern Philippines and it serves as the transshipment point from the Visayas and Mindanao provinces.</p>\r\n            <p>Sorsogon is well on its way to urbanization. Currently less than five percent of its land area is built up, with the rest being utilized as agricultural, forest, reservation, and open spaces available for future development.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/sorsogonCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h3>Sorsogon City’s Must Do List\r\n            </h3><ol><li>1. Visit Bato Cave and the Napaga Limestone cave, a site of pre-historic civilization. Burial jars believed to be more than 3,000 years old were unearthed by archaeologist Dr. Robert Fox here.\r\n                </li><li>2. Stroll in the Capitol Building and Park, Old Pandayan and Simbahan ng Bacon, a heritage structure built during the 18th century.\r\n                </li><li>3. Explore the City’s ecologically preserved destinations like the Botong Twin Falls, Inang Maharang, Sulfuric Lake and Sanctuary of Large Flying Foxes (biggest bats in the world).\r\n                </li><li>4. Stroll along the Bacon Beach, a long stretch that covers 15 barangays starting from the black sand Libanon (big waves and fine-black sand, ideal for skim boarding) to the basin-like Paguiriran island (uninhabited islet with endemic flora and a lagoon within). In between are Tolongapo/ Halabang Baybay/ Pagol beaches offering gentle sea breeze and white sand with available amenities.\r\n                </li><li>5. Savor the City’s culinary taste. Try tilmok, a fresh-water shrimp cooked with young coconut and fresh herbs (Yerba Buena), hinagom (freshly harvested rice toasted and ground with fresh buko and muscovado sugar) and Pili Conserva sa Dahon (pili nuts coated with muscovado sugar enclosed in leaf).\r\n                </li></ol><h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Sorsogon City</p> <p>Population: 151,454 (2007 Census)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, the City can be reached by plane via Manila- Legazpi City route. From Legazpi, Sorsogon is a one-hour ride. By land, travel by bus is approximately 12 hours.</p>\r\n            <p>Coming from Cebu, one can reach Sorsogon City by plane via Legazpi. From other cities in the South, one may take a bus or ferry passing the Allen, Samar or Masbate route.\r\n            </p><h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. April-May (Summer, Lent, and Fiestas)\r\n                </li><li>2. October (Kasanggayan Festival/ Festival of the Province) 3. December (Sorsogon Festival)\r\n                </li></ol><h4>For travel information\r\n            </h4><p>Please contact the Sorsogon City Tourism Office at tele- phone nos. (056) 211-2899 or (0917) 75132847 or email at sorcitytourism@yahoo.com</p>\r\n','Sorsogon is the capital city of the province of Sorsogon, located at the southernmost tip of Luzon. The City was formed by merging the Bacon and Sorsogon municipalities.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/sorsogon',NULL,0,21,22,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:24:58','2012-09-12 06:24:00'),(26,NULL,1,'Silay City','silay','<h3>The Sweet Life</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/silayCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The City of Silay is “the Seat of Arts, Culture and Eco-tourism in Western Visayas” with its rich history and heritage, flourishing arts and culture reflected from its ancestral mansions on its music and dances, breath-taking natural wonders, timeless delicacies, the endless opportunities for development and of course, the naturally friendly citizenry. Indeed one of the most unique destinations in the region, Silay welcomes everyone seeking either the pleasures of adventure or the mysteries of the past about to unfold.</p>\r\n            <p>Founded in 1760, Silay was at the forefront of sugar production at the turn of the 20th century. This golden age ushered in an era of prosperity, where dances, opera, theatre and carnivals were a common occurrence.\r\n            <p>In fact, the revolution that ended more than three centuries of Spanish rule in Negros was planned in the guise of Silay’s lav- ish parties. Silay was also famous for its imports of artists and cultural shows. European performers would share the stage with local talents. Thus, Silay was made known by chroniclers as “the Paris of the Orient”.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, Silay is embracing a modern-day renaissance as it again plays its role as the commercial and cultural hub of the province of Negros Occidental by being host to the Province’s first airport of international standards and by being a haven for arts and heritage appreciation</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Hugyaw kay Kansilay Festival and Charter Day Celebration (June 6 – 12)\r\n                </li><li>2. Commemoration of the Cinco de Noviembre Revolution and Fiesta de San Diego (November 5 -13)\r\n                </li><li>3. Silay Christmas Village and Festival (December 6 – January 6)\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/silayCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Silay City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. Eat. Drop by El Ideal Bakery, the oldest in the City and savor the best delicacies Silay has to offer or visit the home of Emma Lacson and sample her bestseller Fresh Lumpia de Silay and pili squares. The feast of gastronomic delights continues in the lore of the manug-libod or street vendor, selling Silay’s traditional delicacies passed down from generation to generation. Or better yet, catch up and feast at the early morning barter-trade at the side of the public market for a truly Silaynon experience.\r\n                    If you want to have a quick escape from the bustle of the city, there is the seaside Barangay Balaring. Its sought after shoreline restaurants offer the freshest seafood. Find time to see the Balaring Mangrove Rehabilitation Project, a canopy of mangrove tree species accessed by bamboo bridges that culminates in a tower, providing breathtaking views of the Guimaras Strait.\r\n                </li><li>2. Pray. Designed by Italian architect Lucio Bernasconi in 1920, the San Diego cathedral’s silver-colored Byzantium dome was inspired by St. Peter’s Basilica in Rome. Its architectural grandeur and treasury of religious art are testaments to the people of Silay’s deep faith and religiosity. The ruins of the old church whose foundations date back to 1776, is located at the back of the present church and is now an adoration chapel.\r\n                </li><li>3. Love. Thirty two kilometers from the City proper is Barangay Patag. An adventurer’s complete getaway, this eco -tourism destination has a lot to offer. From over a hundred waterfalls noteworthy are Pulang Tubig and Dumalabdab that will bring you to the brim of excitement. For the more adventurous, a long trek to enchanted Tinagong Dagat, an open space in the middle of lush forests and high peaks will surely test the spirit. But it is not all endurance and thrills in Patag, for the less adventurous, a quite dip in the pool fed by spring water or a picnic will always be the perfect time to bond with family and friends.\r\n                </li><li>4. Observe and Imagine as the past comes alive in the fine craftsmanship of Silay City’s 29 surviving ancestral homes, all recog- nized by the National Historical Commission. A confluence of foreign and local ingenuity, these palatial dwellings tell the tale of an era made sweeter by the sugar produced and the colorful life lived. It is sugar that made Silay one of the richest towns in the country and the hacienderos spared no expense in the construction and furnishing of their homes.\r\n                </li><li>5. Peek into three of Silay’s most loved ancestral homes - The Balay Negrense (Don Victor Ancestral House), Don Bernardino Jalandoni Ancestral House and the Manuel Hofilena Heritage House - which were all converted into museums, providing us glimpses to a once glorious past – a past worth revisiting.\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Silay</p> <p>Population: 120, 365 (2007)\r\n            </p><h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Silay is 50 minutes and from Cebu, 30 minutes by plane. Three airline companies fly daily (10 flights) from Manila and Cebu.\r\n                Silay is also accessible via Bacolod from Manila (18 hours) and by fast craft from Iloilo (50 min.)\r\n                From Bacolod, Silay City can be reached within 10 minutes. There are taxis and public transportations available. By land via “Roll-on, Roll-off” from Cebu, Silay is approximately six to eight hours away.\r\n            </p><h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. Summer (March-May, best time for walking tours around the historic city center)\r\n            </p><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Silay City Tourism Office, Negros Occidental, Philippines at telephone nos. (034) 495-5553\r\n                and fax at telephone nos (034) 495-0848. Email at silaycity_tourism@yahoo.com. Like Silay City in Facebook, search for (Silay City).\r\n            </p>\r\n','The City of Silay is “the Seat of Arts, Culture and Eco-tourism in Western Visayas” with its rich history and heritage, flourishing arts and culture reflected from its ancestral mansions on its music and dances, breath-taking natural wonders, timeless delicacies, the endless opportunities for development and of course, the naturally friendly citizenry.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/silay',NULL,0,23,24,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:27:02','2012-09-12 06:26:00'),(27,NULL,1,'Santiago City','santiago','            <h3>Investment Hub of the North</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/santiagoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Santiago City is situated in the Province of Isabela at about 79 kilometers south of Ilagan, the Provincial Capital of Isabela, and is located at about 326 kilometers North of Manila. It is a six hour drive from Manila.</p>\r\n            <p>By public vehicle, Santiago City is available 24 hours in Baliwag Transit, Victory Liner, Florida Bus Line, and Nelbusco Bus Compa- nies in Manila.</p>\r\n            <p>Likewise, Dalin, Royal Eagle and Dagupan Bus Line going to the City of Tuguegarao pass through the City of Santiago. It is an eight hour drive.</p>\r\n            <p>By Air, Cebu Pacific, Zest Airline, and Air Philippines are available flying Manila to Tuguegarao. Bus companies such as Baliwag Transit, Victory Liner, Florida Bus Line, Nelbusco, Dalin, Royal Eagle, and Dagupan Bus are available in Tuguegarao City bound for Santiago. Van for hire is also available.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/santiagoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Santiago City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Climb the Calvary Hills and the Chapel of Transfiguration. Located at Dariuk Hills in Barangay Balintocatoc, the place offers a pilgrimage venue for the Holy Week where life-sized Stations of the Cross are presented from the foot of the hill going up to the top where the Chapel of Transfiguration is located. Found also at the top of the hill is the tallest image of the Our Lady of La Salette facing the City proper.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Visit the Balay na Santiago. The museum showcases a collection of the ethno-linguistic lifestyle of those who made Santiago City the melting pot of culture that is today. It shows a glimpse of the past customs and traditions that have united the multi-race Santiagueños. Balay na Santiago is located at the heart of the city along Turingan and Melegrito Streets in Barangay Calao West, Santiago City.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Participate in the Pattaraday Festival. Santiago City’s founding anniversary festivity is celebrated every May 1-5 of the year through Pattaradday Festival. Pattaradday, an Ybanag term means unity. Ybanags are said to be the first settlers of the locality. The festival has already won Hall of Fame in the Search for Best Tourism Event in the Philippines conducted by the Association of Tourism Officers of the Philippines.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Celebrate with Santiagueños on the Feast of St. James the Apostle. Celebrated every July 25 of the year, it features the life history of the patron saint as it saves the Christians against the Moros through Sarswela and the Grand Batalla of the Moro-Moro, a dance choreography depicting the battle.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Have a patupat, Santiago City’s native delicacy. It is a native rice cake cooked by soaking malagkit (sticky rice) wrapped in coconut leaves in a boiling juice of sugarcane for hours. Other sugar cane products such as molasses or puliti- pot, muscovado sugar, sinaklob, and sugarcane vinegar and wine are readily available.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Santiago</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 126,244 (NSO Census)</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For more travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Office of the City Mayor with telephone nos. (078) 682-8110 or (062)- 8455.</p>\r\n','Santiago City is situated in the Province of Isabela at about 79 kilometers south of Ilagan, the Provincial Capital of Isabela, and is located at about 326 kilometers North of Manila. It is a six hour drive from Manila.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/santiago',NULL,0,25,26,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:28:12','2012-09-12 06:27:00'),(28,NULL,1,'City of Santa Rosa','santa-rosa','            <h3>The Lion City of South Luzon</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfSantaRosa1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n            <p>Santa Rosa is named from the first patron saint of South America, Santa Rosa de Lima of Peru. It became a municipality on January 18, 1792 from a mere barrio of Biñan called Barrio Bukol. During the revolutionary period, Santa Rosa signed the Act of Independence from Spain on June 12, 1898. The local leaders fought alongside General Emilio Aguinaldo during the Filipino-American War. After a brief occupation by the Japanese forces during the Second World War, the town was liberated on February 5, 1945.</p>\r\n            <p>During the post war era, Santa Rosa’s local economy was depen- dent on farming, fishing, livestock and small backyard industry. Industrialization came in the 1980’s with the entry of foreign multinational companies in economic zones and industrial estates.</p>\r\n            <p>From a fourth-class municipality in 1986, Santa Rosa became a first-class town in 1993, and officially became the 101st city in the Philippines on July 10, 2004.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, the City of Santa Rosa is living up to its symbol – the lion. Its economy is vibrant and booming, and so to speak, roaring like a lion.</p>\r\n            <p>As The Lion City of South Luzon, Santa Rosa is the headquarters to some of the major corporations in the Philippines. These include the largest bottling plant of Coca-Cola in the Far East and the manufacturing plant of food giant Monde Nissin Corp.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol><li>1. The major festival is the Sikhayan Festival, which is celebrated every January 18, coinciding with Santa Rosa’s founding anniversary as a separate and independent town in the Laguna Province.\r\n                    Short for SikapKabuhayan, Sikhayan is a celebration of life, a tribute to the people’s unrelenting and resolute effort, to their profound sense of community, to their deeply rooted cultural heritage, and to their enterprising spirit.\r\n                </li><li>2. The City’s major destinations include: Enchanted Kingdom (the Philippines’ first and only world-class theme park), Cuartel de Santo Domingo (a Spanish-era fort, the city’s version of Intramuros), Nuvali-Solenad (One of the city’s most modern, eco-friendly business, and commercial complex) and Paseo de Santa Rosa (A shopper’s haven, night time is the best time to visit) and City Proper (See the city’s rich cultural heritage)\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfSantaRosa2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h4>City of Santa Rosa’s Must Do List\r\n            </h4><ol><li>1. Acquaint yourself with the City by taking a walking tour in the City proper, where the old and the new converge. In the City proper, visitors are welcomed by the Santa Rosa Arch that leads to the modern and visitor-friendly City Hall. Fronting the City Hall is the City Plaza where one can take a trip down memory lane by visiting the newly-refurbished Museo de Santa Rosa, the Santa Rosa de Lima Parish Church, and some of the well-preserved Hispanic ancestral homes in the City Square.\r\n                </li><li>2. Relax with some of the amenities the city has to offer. Bring your family and enjoy the rides at Enchanted Kingdom. Relax and unwind at the 18-hole golf course of world-class Santa Elena Golf and Country Club. Spend nightlife with friends and colleagues at Paseo de Santa Rosa where food is great and music is at its best.\r\n                </li><li>3. Indulge yourself in many shopping malls spread around the City.\r\n                </li><li>4. Stay in one of the City’s best hotels like the Paseo Premier Hotel, the Laguna Technopark Hotel or El Cielito Inn. Relax in some of the best resorts like the Southpick Resort and Rosalinda’s Garden.\r\n                </li><li>5. Eat in one or two of the 199 restaurants and foodshops in the City. From local kitchenettes to fine-dining restaurants, the city boasts of a wide-range of variety.\r\n                </li></ol><h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Santa Rosa</p> <p>Population: 266, 943</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>The City of Sta. Rosa is 40 kilometers south of Metro Manila and just 40 minutes away from Makati City. It is one and a half hours from the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.\r\n                Depending on where one wants to go, the City of Santa Rosa is accessible via the South Luzon Expressway through three exits –Greenfield City (Mamplasan), Santa Rosa, and Eton City. The Balibago Complex is the City’s central transport terminal where one rides to go to their destination in and out of the City.\r\n            </p><h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Olongapo City Tourism Office, G/F Olongapo City Convention Center, Old Hospital Road, East Tapinac, Olongapo City with telephone nos. (047) 224-1471. Visit the City’s website at <a href=\"http://www.olongapocity.gov.ph\" >www.olongapocity.gov.ph</a>\r\n','Santa Rosa is named from the first patron saint of South America, Santa Rosa de Lima of Peru. It became a municipality on January 18, 1792 from a mere barrio of Biñan called Barrio Bukol.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/santa-rosa',NULL,0,27,28,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:29:59','2012-09-12 06:28:00'),(29,NULL,1,'San Fernando City, La Union','san-fernando-la-union','<h3>The Prime Capital of Ilocandia</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/sanFernandoCity_LaUnion1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>San Fernando City is the regional capital of the Ilocos Region and the capital province of the Province of La Union.</p>\r\n            <p>The City envisions itself as the premier capital city for trade, tourism, and governance - a liveable, progressive, business- friendly and environmentally-sensitive urban center, home to God-loving, enlightened and empowered citizens and leaders.</p>\r\n            <p>The main goal of the City Government is to enhance the quality of life of its people through an efficient and effective provision of public service and facilities, creation of livelihood opportu- nities, and promotion of a safe and clean environment that adheres to sustainable development.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>La Union Botanical Garden - Located 8 kilometers east of the City is a forested mountain and a great spot that is probably one of its kind in the country. It is a display of different themed garde with their scientific names and a sanctuary of varieties of wild animals.</li>\r\n                <li>La Union Botanical Garden - Located 8 kilometers east of the City is a forested mountain and a great spot that is probably one of its kind in the country. It is a display of different themed garde with their scientific names and a sanctuary of varieties of wild animals.</li>\r\n                <li>La Union Science Centrum and Museum - First interactive hands on science center in the North that was launched in May 2003 as a response to the Science and Technology Master Plan for socio-economic development and the Science for Masses Program of the Department of Education.</li>\r\n                <li>Ma-tzu Festival - In Macao and Fujian (China), Taiwan and the Ma-Tzu temples in La Union and Batangas, the goddesses of Ma-Cha is believed to be one and the same as the Our Lady of Caysasay. Today, Filipino-Chinese communities of Northern Luzon come and visit on an annual pilgrimage to Taal in her ‘mother’ shrine, bringing along the image of Mama Ma-cha of the Ma-Tzu temple.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/sanFernandoCity_LaUnion2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>San Fernando City, La Union’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>La Union Botanical Garden (LUBG) located 8 kilometers east of the City at baran- gay Cadacion. A must see garden. For an unforgettable experience for all ages, visit the La Union Science Centrum and Museum located near the LUBG at barangay Cada- clan.</li>\r\n                <li>See the historical seven hills including the Bacsil Ridge that are part of the World War II history.</li>\r\n                <li>Experience the past as one goes around the City on a Historical and Cultural tour.</li>\r\n                <li>Enjoy the splendid beaches that adorn the city’s coastline where one can skin and scuba dive, snorkel, surf, and swim or just soak in waters.</li>\r\n                <li>Be educated with the City’s best practices on environmental conservation and pres- ervation with the city-based government programs such as the engineered sanitary landfill, the ecological sanitation dry technology toilet, wastewater treatment facility, materials recovery facility, and the ongoing construction of the Septage and Sewerage Management Facility for human wastes.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Where to Stay</h4>\r\n            <p>Thunderbird Resorts</p>\r\n            <p>Poro Point Freeport Zone (072) 888-777 <a href=\"http://www.thunderbird-asia.com\">www.thunderbird-asia.com</a>  </p>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p> Official Name: San Fernando City </p>\r\n            <p>Population: 114, 398</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>The City is about 270 kms north-northwest of Metro Manila and only 60 kilometers northwest of Baguio City. By land, it is about six to eight hour drive from Manila through public utility buses and five to six hours through private cars plying the National Highway.</p>\r\n            <p>By air, it is about 30 minutes through the Zest Air passenger plane which is available every Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays landing in the San Fernando City Airport.</p>\r\n            <p>Although the City can be reached by sea, the International Seaport caters national and international cargo vessels only to Northern Luzon and East Asian region.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    February 1-10 for the annual City Fiesta which is continu- ing up until March of which the Foundation Anniversary of the Province and Cityhood Foundation Anniversary are be- ing celebrated on March 2nd and 20th respectively.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    September for The Feast of Our Lady of Caysasay, the Pa- troness of Filipino-Chinese enshrined at the Ma-Cha Temple.\r\n                </li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Office of the City Mayor, 2nd Floor, City Hall, City of San Fernando, La Union with telephone nos. (072)-888-6906 and (072) 888-6901 (trunkline) to 04 local 120 or email at csflu@sflu.com. Visit the City’s website at <a href=\"http://www.sanfernandocity.gov.ph\" >www.sanfernandocity.gov.ph</a>.</p>\r\n','San Fernando City is the regional capital of the Ilocos Region and the capital province of the Province of La Union. The City envisions itself as the premier capital city for trade, tourism, and governance.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/san-fernando-la-union',NULL,0,29,30,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:30:41','2012-09-12 06:30:00'),(30,NULL,1,'City of San Fernando','san-fernando','<h3>Christmas Capital of the Philippines</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfSanFernando1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Fernandinos (natives of the city) are known for their creativity and craftsmanship especially in lantern making hence San Fernando is referred to as the Christmas Capital of the Philippines.</p>\r\n            <p>San Fernando has been the choice industrial location of business establishments. As of December 2010, the City of San Fernando has a total of 7,524 registered business establishments which include two big shopping malls, 152 banks and financial institu- tions, four major bottling companies, and several manufacturing companies. The City is one area in the country where all large banking and financial institutions can be found. There are a total of 76 banking institutions located in the City that serves the banking requirements of the business community.</p>\r\n            <p>The City also takes pride for its very competitive meat processing industry. It has earned the title as the food center of the prov- ince of Pampanga with around 83 restaurants abound becoming a culinary haven for food enthusiasts.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is also an education center with 66 elementary, 25 secondary, 35 tertiary schools including one university and 12 colleges and 49 day care centers. The City serves as the provin- cial capital and site of most regional government agencies of Central Luzon. There are 10 hospitals, 67 clinics, and five rural health units operating in the City of San Fernando.</p>\r\n            <p>The City of San Fernando prides itself as the home of numerous personages in Philippine history, among who include socialist leader and assemblyman Pedro Abad Santos, war hero and former chief justice Jose Abad Santos, revolutionary heroine Nicolasa P. Dayrit, poet and legislator Zoilo S. Hilario, senator and father of the concrete pavement Sotero J. Baluyut, revolutionary governor Tiburcio T. Hilario and celebrated pre-war journalist Amando G. Dayrit.</p>\r\n            <p>San Fernando is considered as the birthplace of the labor move- ment in the Philippines. The first organized strike was said to have been staged in 1872 by a gremio of printers from govern- ment press located in the town, in protest against the abuses of the plant foreman. The first labor union was also established in San Fernando in the printing plant of La Independencia, edited by General Antonio Luna.</p>\r\n            <p>On June 27, 1892 national hero, Dr. Jose P. Rizal, visited the town as part of his mission to recruit members into his group, La Liga Filipina.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Holy week (Good Friday to Easter Sunday “Maleldo”) - The cultural clash between folk beliefs and elegant religious ceremonies is most evident in the City where once a year, every Good Friday, several penitents, driven by strong faith, reenact the crucifixion of Jesus Christ by having themselves nailed to the cross.</li>\r\n                <li>2. On or before May 30 (Weeklong celebration for the feast day St. Ferdinand) - The city honors its town patron San Fernando.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>3. On or before the third week of December (Giant Lantern Festival “Ligligan Parul”) -The Giant Lantern Festival is a city-wide competition participated by different barangays..</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfSanFernando2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of San Fernando’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the San Fernando Heritage District and take a kalesa ride around the district. Visit the Capitol Park & Heroes Park to know famous Kapampangan Heroes. Land- marks include the San Fernando Train Station where the Death March ended.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Dine at the famous restaurants in the City. Our distinct cuisine is one of the Ka- pampangans’ Pride. Visit some of the more famous restaurants (Bale Kapampangan, Everybody’s Café, Holliday Land, Fishermans Grill, Jun-Jun’s BBQ and many more) and have a taste of the best Kapampangan cuisine - kamaru(crickets), lichun bulaklak, sisig babi, betuteng tugak(stuffed frog), tocino, buru keng mustasa (fermented rice in mustard), pako salad and many more.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Take home a Parul Sampernandu (San Fernando lantern). It is one of the more fa- mous products of the city and well known not only nationally but also internationally. It has different variations like made of vinyl plastic, handmade paper, capiz, and fiber glass.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Visit the festivals of the City. Drop by and witness the four major cultural attrac- tions of the city - Maleldo (Holy Week), the Pyetang Fernandino during last week of May, the Pyestang Tugak (Frog festival) every October and the famous Giant Lantern Festival every third Saturday of December.\r\n                </li><li>5. Enjoy Shopping. San Fernando is a haven for shoppers. Boasting of having the longest mall in the country (SM City Pampanga) and a premium outlet destination (Robinsons, Starmills and Walter Mart). Soon to open is SM City of San Fernando and S&R Membership Shopping.\r\n                </li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>Where to Stay</h4>\r\n\r\n            <p>Miyabe Court Lazatin Avenue, Villa Victoria (045) 961-6059 alan_david04@hotmail.com</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of San Fernando Population: 298,936</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>The City of San Fernando is strategically located at the heart of Central Luzon. It is 67 kilometers North of Metro Manila.</p>\r\n            <p>From Manila, all bus lines (i.e. Victory Liner, Bataan Transit, Genesis, Saulog, and Five Star) linking Manila with Baguio, Pangasinan, and Ilocos pass through Pampanga. Provincial liners bound for Zambales, Bataan and Baguio City stop over at San Fernando.</p>\r\n            <p>San Fernando City is adjacent to two International Airports – Diosdado Macapagal International Airport (DMIA) which is located at Clark Freeport Zone and the Ninoy Aquino International Airport (NAIA) located at Metro Manila.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Mayor’s Office, City Hall Building, A. Consunji St., Poblacion, Sto. Rosario, City of San Fernando, Pampanga with telephone nos. (045) 961-5022 and the City Tourism Office with telephone nos. (045) 961-5684.\r\n            <p>Visit the website at <a href=\"http://www.cityofsanfernando.gov.ph\" >www.cityofsanfernando.gov.ph</a> or email us at sanfernandotourism@yahoo.com. Like the City on Facebook, like www.facebook.com/sanfernadotourism@ yahoo.com</p>\r\n','Fernandinos (natives of the city) are known for their creativity and craftsmanship especially in lantern making hence San Fernando is referred to as the Christmas Capital of the Philippines.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/san-fernando',NULL,0,31,32,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:31:33','2012-09-12 06:31:00'),(31,NULL,1,'Island Garden City of Samal','samal','            <h3>The Urban Center in a Garden Setting</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/islandGardenCityOfSamal1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>An enchanting paradise - an island, a garden, and a city. Located at the heart of Davao Gulf of southern Philippines, the Island Garden City of Samal (IGACOS) teems with rich flora and fauna bedecked in captivating waterfalls, challenging ridges, fascinating cave systems, and picturesque underwater gardens.</p>\r\n            <p>With all these ingredients combined, Samal has unsurprisingly emerged as ‘Regional Hub for Recreation and Amity in Southern Philippines’, a haven for wellness tourism, outdoor adventure, aquasports, cultural and eco-tourism - a rare destination with almost has it all.</p>\r\n            <p>No wonder that the Island has become a favorite gateway of all types of tourists - a hidden nook for discriminating jetsetters, a refuge for nature trippers, a preferred lair for family excursionists, and as a playground for outdoor adventurists wanting to burn their adrenalins.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is an Island, a cluster of nine islands at the heart of Davao Gulf with scenic seacaspes pristine coastlines, and turquoise marine waters, a 118-kilometer of fine, white, sandy coastlines, home to more than 50 commercial resorts and hundreds of private getaways.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is a Garden. Laidback urban landscape in a garden set- ting, numerous scenic natural parks and open spaces, balanced ecosystems (intact natural endowment), more pedestrians, bicycle and tree lanes, and green oriented neigborhoods.</p>\r\n            <p>IGACOS is an urbanizing community of dignified constituents, equipped with good urban amenities living in an atmosphere of good governance.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/islandGardenCityOfSamalCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>IGACOS’ Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Close encounters with millions of fruit bats at the Monfort Bat Sanctuary and Conservation Park. Declared in 2009 by Guinness World Record as home of the world’s biggest colony of Geoffrey’s Rousette Fruit Bats numbering approximate- ly 1.8-2.5 million as validated by the Bats Conservation International.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Cliff hanging at Bito Depression and Plunging at the Hagimat Falls. Burn adrenalin in rappelling 273-feet natural limestone walls, then commune with nature as you go in a picnic beneath the shadow of coconut grooves, or spread your tents in the midst of lush vegetation.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Island cruise and bask in any of our numerous resorts. Cruise around the island and lay idle at the numerous commercial resorts and private getaways along the 118-kilometer stretch of coastlines.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Scuba diving. Diving into the depths of Talikud or in Liguid Islands and many other dive spots will reveal dazzling coral gardens and colorful underwater vistas with jaw dropping tropical marine life.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Celebrate during festivals. Celebrate with Samalenos on their founding anniversary every March 07. The weeklong festivity highlights sand sculputure competition (Pag-Ukit sa Pantad), fluvial parade of colorful boats (Bigiw Regatta), banca race (bangkarera). The merry making is accentuated with the colorful stitlts (karang) and Mascot Competition.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. IGACOS Festival - This week-long festivity in celebration of the founding anniversary of the City starts on March 1 and culminates on March 07.</li>\r\n                <li>2. KABASAN Festival. “Kabasan” (literally means seashells) celebrates the rich and colorful ‘bounties of the seas’ culminating on May 28, the founding anniversary of the old municipality of Babak. The festival showcases ala Mardigras street-dancing, street parties, and concerts, bikini open, fireworks, among others.</li>\r\n                <li>3. White Nights Festival - Owing to its moniker to the white sandy beachline of celebration venue which is Kaputian (white) Poblacion, the event is a festival of history, culture and arts in commemoration of the founding anniversary of the old municipality of Kaputian.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: The Island Garden City of Samal Population: 90,291</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, IGACOS is an hour and a half flight bound to Davao City, the gateway to the Island City. The jump off point to Samal is a 7-minute taxi ride from the Davao International Airport to Km-11, Sasa, located behind the Sasa Public Market IGACOS is just about 10-minutes across the Pakiputan Strait.</p>\r\n            <p>By RORO or launches, one may board the ferryboard with or without your vehicle. One may also opt to take the passenger launches at Km-11 for only 10 minutes.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Anytime of the year is the best time to go to Samal though tourists flock during summer and long holidays.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the IGACOS Tourist Information Center, Ferry Boat Landing, Km. 11, Sasa, Davao City.</p>\r\n            <p>IGACOS Tourist Information Center, Villarica Wharf, Babak, Island Garden City of Samal</p>\r\n            <p>City Tourism Office, City Hall Compound, Penaplata, Island Garden City of Samal.</p>\r\n            <p>Visit <a href=\"http://www.samalcity.gov.ph\" >www.samalcity.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','An enchanting paradise - an island, a garden, and a city. Located at the heart of Davao Gulf of southern Philippines, the Island Garden City of Samal (IGACOS) teems with rich flora and fauna bedecked in captivating waterfalls, challenging ridges, fascinating cave systems, and picturesque underwater gardens.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/samal',NULL,0,33,34,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:32:19','2012-09-12 06:31:00'),(32,NULL,1,'Puerto Princesa City','puerto-princesa','            <h3>The City in a Forest</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/puertoPrincesaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Exotic islands, unspoiled beaches, world-class dive sites, lush virgin forests, endemic flora and fauna, waterfalls, hot springs and rivers and many more abound in this place we call the City in a Forest, Puerto Princesa&#46; It lies in the center of the island province of Palawan&#46; Considered as the largest city in the country, it sprawls across 253,982 hectares of land and stretches 106 kilometers long.</p>\r\n            <p>What more of its blessedness, being a typhoon free city and not being within the earthquake fault, the City is endowed with the longest navigable underground river in the world&#46; The Puerto Princesa Underground River, home of a 20 million year old fossilized &ldquo;Serenia&rdquo; and is now a Finalist to the New 7 Wonders of Nature.</p>\r\n            <p>It is no wonder that Puerto Princesa City is among the National Geographic&rsquo;s &ldquo;Top 20 New Destinations&rdquo; to watch for 2011 all over the world&#46;</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities&#46;</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li> Balayong Festival (March)</li>\r\n                <li> City Fiesta (December 8)</li>\r\n                <li> Tandikan Festival (September)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/puertoPrincesaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Puerto Princesa City&rsquo;s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li> Puerto Princesa Underground River Tour</li>\r\n                <li> Island Hopping Tour</li>\r\n                <li> City Tour</li>\r\n                <li> Dolphin and Firefly Watching Tour</li>\r\n                <li> Souvenir Shopping</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3> Profile </h3>\r\n            <p> Official Name: Puerto Princesa City</p>\r\n            <h4> How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Puerto Princesa takes less than an hour. Flights are available nine times daily by Philippine Airlines, Cebu Pa- cific, Airphil Express and ZestAir. There are also flights from Cebu three times a week.</p>\r\n            <p>By sea, Puerto Princesa is accessible by boat from Manila once a week by Superferry, with stopover at Coron. Boat trips from Puerto Princesa to Cuyo and Iloilo aboard MV Milagrosa and Montenegro are also available thrice weekly.</p>\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>During summer season, the weather is fine and all activities can be done.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office, 2F Right Wing, City Coliseum, Brgy. San Pedro Puerto Princesa City at (048) 433- 2983 or (048) 434-4211. Email at puertoturismo@yahoo.com.</p>\r\n','Exotic islands, unspoiled beaches, world-class dive sites, lush virgin forests, endemic flora and fauna, waterfalls, hot springs and rivers and many more abound in this place we call the City in a Forest, Puerto Princesa.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/puerto-princesa-city',NULL,0,35,36,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:32:55','2012-09-12 06:32:00'),(33,NULL,1,'Pasay City','pasay','            <h3>The International Gateway</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/pasayCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>After four decades of rapid urbanization in Metropolitan Manila, Pasay City has transformed into an important local corridor between major urban centers. Its southwestern portion provides access between the City of Manila in the north with cities and municipalities like Parañaque, Las Piñas as well as the nearby municipalities of Cavite in the south. Likewise, its southeastern portion links Parañaque, Muntinlupa and Laguna with the cities of Manila, Makati, Mandaluyong as well as Quezon City.</p>\r\n            <p>Pasay City becomes the facilitator of trade among its neighboring local government units. The City also serves as an international gateway not just to Metro Manila but the whole Philip- pines with the existence of both the domestic and international airports within its jurisdiction.</p>\r\n            <p>Another feature that could work to its advantage is its western coastline that could be expanded through reclamation. In fact, a large portion of the City is already made up of reclaimed lands where prominent landmarks and national government offices are now established.</p>\r\n            <p>As a whole, Pasay City has the basic fundamentals that can sus- tain its economic machinery. It has highly educated and skilled manpower as well as managers; adequate supply of electricity and water; excellent access provided by light rail transit systems, excellent communication facilities, road networks and airports; and some land for expansion.</p>\r\n            <p>Pasay City has a key role in the Philippine tourism industry, as it hosts the Ninoy Aquino International Airport 1, 2 and 3 and thus serves as the country’s international gateway. It also supports the tourism industry in Metro Manila and the nearby provinces in Southern Luzon as it has 23 hotels that accommodate foreign and local tourists.</p>\r\n            <p>The ferry terminal beside the Tanghalang Francisco Balagtas also serves as the jump-off point to the historical island of Corregidor. And if somebody wants to roam around Metro Manila, the LRT and MRT terminals are just around the corner located at EDSA-Taft Avenue and Pasay-Rotonda.</p>\r\n            <p>Cultural attractions include the numerous venues for shows at the Cultural Center of the Philippines (CCP) Complex, Folk Arts Theater (Tanghalang Francisco Balagtas), Philippine International Convention Center (PICC), Philippine World Trade Center, Philippine Training Center, Sofitel Hotel (formerly Philippine Plaza Hotel), Coconut Palace, SMX Convention Center, The Shrine of St. Therese of the Child Jesus, Chinese temple, SM Mall Of Asia and SM MOA Skating Rink (the biggest mall in Asia and big- gest indoor skating rink in the Philippines, Resorts World Manila, Maxim and Marriot Hotel.</p>\r\n            <p>The reclamation area is also home to Star City, which is the favorite recreational destination by people during the Christmas season.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/pasayCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Pasay City</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. April is the best time of the year to go to Pasay because of Aliwan Festival, “The Mother of All Fiestas” that features the famous cultural festivals that can be found in the Philippines. Aliwan is a Tagalog word for entertainment or amusement. It is a battle between the best Philippine festivals as the participants dance in a parade with float competitions as well.</li></ol>\r\n            <h4>How to get there:</h4>\r\n            <p>Jeepneys are usually the cheapest and fastest way to get around the city with a trip costing not less than 7-8 Pesos. Taxis are affordable, comfortable and one can get where ever one wants at any time, flag down rates cost P40.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Resorts World. The fun never stops at Pasay City where the Resorts World Manila is located, with world-class entertainment happening throughout the day, seven days a week.</li>\r\n                <li>2. SM Mall of Asia. The Christmas Sale at SM Mall of Asia (MOA) is attracting international and local tourists. SM Mall of Asia is the 3rd largest shopping mall in Asia and the 4th according to Forbes’ World’s 10 Largest Shopping Malls) largest shopping mall in the world. Every Friday and Saturday at 7pm, a pyromusical event is held in this place. It is a fantastic fireworks display held to music at the SM by the bay behind the mall. In here you can be taken away by the dazzling lights and festive atmo- sphere. Soak in the thrills as you dine and relax in any of the restaurants by the seaside.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n','After four decades of rapid urbanization in Metropolitan Manila, Pasay City has transformed into an important local corridor between major urban centers. Its southwestern portion provides access between the City of Manila in the north with cities and municipalities like Parañaque, Las Piñas as well as the nearby municipalities of Cavite in the south.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/pasay',NULL,0,37,38,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:33:59','2012-09-12 06:33:00'),(34,NULL,1,'Olongapo City','olongapo','            <h3>The Freeport City</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/olongapoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Olongapo City is a highly urbanized city located in the province of Zambales. Other than the City proper which is located on tidal flatland, it is characterized by rugged and mountainous terrain.</p>\r\n            <p>From being a barrio of Subic, Zambales under the United States Naval Reservation Administration, Olongapo was transformed into a municipality on December 7, 1959, then into a chartered city on June 1, 1966.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, Olongapo City is a haven for business opportunities and a topnotch tourist destination. Moreover, remarkable initiatives and outstanding practices in local governance make Olongapo a template for other cities’ growth and advancement.</p>\r\n            <p>In 2007, The City was awarded as one of the Philippines’ Most Competitive Cities (medium sized category) by the Asian Institute of Management (AIM) Policy Center under the Philippine Cities Competitiveness Ranking Project.</p>\r\n            <p>True to its vision of becoming the First Freeport City in the country, the City has become the center of trade and commerce in West Central Luzon. Olongapo City‘s economic activities are primarily based on trade and services. It has been a convenient trading post between Luzon merchants and wholesalers in the northern and southern municipalities of Zambales and nearby provinces.</p>\r\n            <p>Most of major tourism events in the City are held in the beaches, which are major attractions. Every summer, the Sibit-Sibit Festival features an array of beach activities such as boat racing, beach sports competition, beach parade and others.</p>\r\n            <p>Celebrated on October is the Mardi Gras which is known for its wild and unique festival experience during the US Navy days and the only kind of festival in Asia during those times.</p>\r\n            <p>At the end of the year, the City’s Grand Fiesta is being celebrated. The climax of the event is the grand parade and the coronation night of the year‘s City Fiesta Queen.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Olongapo City Museum – In the modern edifice of the Museum are the rich and significant reminders of the past chroni- cling the events that have shaped Olongapo into what it has become today.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Mardigras (October) – Dubbed before as the Music Capital of the Philippines, Olongapo City is reliving the famous Mardigras event to celebrate music, dances, and entertainment on the stretch of Ramon Magsaysay drive.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Sibit Sibit Festival (April-May) – Sibit-Sibit is a word derived from the erstwhile saga of Ulo ng Apo which connotes a small paddle banca used for fishing. During the olden fiestas, fisher- men held banca races using sibit-sibit driven by human strength in the quest to win races. Today, the traditional Sibit-Sibit Fiesta is transformed into a colorful and enthralling event bringing together Olongapo’s past, its thriving present, and a promising future.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/olongapoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Olongapo City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Night life at Ramon Magsaysay Drive.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Visit the City Museum</li>\r\n                <li>3. Avail of the audio visual presentations of the different city’s programs like the HELPS (Health and Housing, Educa- tion and Environment, Livelihood and Labor, Peace and Order and Social Welfare and Sports), Solid Waste Management System, Color Coding of Public Transportation, and Child Friendly City among others.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Take pleasure in swimming in the pristine beaches of Olongapo</li>\r\n                <li>5. Enjoy shopping for souvenir items in shops located at Olongapo City Public Market and the Gawang Gapo Product Exhibit at the lobby area of Olongapo City Hall.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Olongapo City Population: 227,270</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Olongapo City lies 127 kilometers north of Manila, a three- hour drive on the average along the North Luzon Express- way (NLEX) and Subic-\r\n                Clark Tarlac Expressway (SCTEX). The City is located in the southwestern portion of Zambales province. </p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. Summer season (April-May) – Olongapo is rich in natural water resources such as pristine beaches.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Olongapo City Tourism Office, G/F Olongapo City Convention Center, Old Hospital Road, East Tapinac, Olongapo City with telephone nos. (047) 224-1471. Visit the City’s website at <a href=\"http://www.olongapocity.gov.ph\">www.olongapocity.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','Olongapo City is a highly urbanized city located in the province of Zambales. Other than the City proper which is located on tidal flatland, it is characterized by rugged and mountainous terrain.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/olongapo',NULL,0,39,40,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:35:17','2012-09-12 06:34:00'),(35,NULL,1,'City of Muntinlupa','muntinlupa','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfMuntinlupa1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Once considered as a haven for prisoners, the City of Muntinlupa now proudly stands as a premier business location. Muntin- lupa, which literally means ‘little land’ is small in size but big in business as the City is now one of the fastest growing business centers in the country.</p>\r\n            <p>Muntinlupa City is a Hall of Famer in the annual search for the Most Business Friendly City in the Philippines by the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry, winning the award for three years.</p>\r\n            <p>As one progressive city, Muntinlupa is nonetheless tied to its roots that run deep. For its people, tradition and progress are expressions of the city’s visage - enamored with nature, beauty, community and possibility. These are the ties that bind Muntin- lupa and its people as evidently shown by the vivid celebrations and festivities in the City that illustrate a culture of pagmamahal sa pamilya, pagkakaisa and pakikipagkapwa-tao, spirituality and religiosity.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is also well known for its leading hospitals as well as health and wellness centers which offer the best in medical care and technology. The City is also a top shopping destination with its characteristic atmosphere that gives mall goers a vibrant universality, bridging mass appeal with upscale flair.</p>\r\n            <p>Finally, Muntinlupa is your home-away-from-home. If you are a traveler looking for a cool respite from the hustle and bustle of urban living, the warm Filipino hospitality of hotels in Muntinlupa City will surely chase your cares away.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. The Bureau of Correction and Administration Building – Built in 1941, this prison facade houses the offices of the prison administration. The maximum security compound, consisting of 12 buildings called brigades, is located at the western side of the structure.</li>\r\n                <li>2. The Jamboree Lake – Known as the country’s smallest natural lake, it is surrounded by natural terrain reminiscent of the rice terraces of Ifugao, Mountain Province.</li>\r\n                <li>3. The Memorial Hill – This small hill in the New Bilibid Prison reservation compound cradles a World War II vintage Japanese canon.</li>\r\n                <li>4. The Director’s Quarters – The structure manifests the influence of pre-war architecture. Built simultaneously with the Ad- ministration Building in 1941, it serves as the official residence of the Director of the Bureau of Corrections.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Japanese Cemetery – This is the burial place of Yamashita, the Japanese general who became famous during the Japanese occupation of the country.</li>\r\n                <li>6. Visitors from near and afar flock to Muntinlupa to watch the spectacle of Banhayan in Barangay Cupang (September 10), Dinagsa and Serenata in Barangay Poblacion (February), Sa- mahang Batya in Barangay Alabang (January 1), Bulaklakan in Barangay Bayanan (May), the Senakulo (April), and the Grand Santacruzan (May).</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfMuntinlupa2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of Muntinlupa’s Must Do</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the city’s historical sites like The Bureau of Correction and Administration Building, The Memorial Hill, and The Director’s Quarters.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Experience fun and leisure. Shop, Dine, Watch a Movie, and Bar Hop in the City’s numerous malls.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit the National Shrine of Our Lady of Miraculous Medal and the Diocesan Shrine of Our Lady of the Abandoned 4. Choose among the health and wellness centers in the City.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Bring reusable bags, such as cloth or paper bags, whenever one shops in the City. A local ordinance (10-109) prohibiting the sale and use of plastic bags and styrofoam or polyethylene containers in the City is strictly observed especially in commercial establishments.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Muntinlupa Population: 452,943</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Muntinlupa City is the southernmost city in the National Capital Region (Metro Manila). The City can be reached easily via public and private transport through the Southern Luzon Expressway or the Metro Skyway in 30 minutes. It is also a short drive from the Ninoy Aquino International Air- port which is only 13 kilometers from Alabang, Muntinlupa’s premier commercial business district.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. All year round. In Muntinlupa, one can find the perfect mix of modern comfort and leisure, commerce, trade, and nature that satisfies the senses without the wearying effect of overload. The lingering pastoral appeal of the City’s green landscape blending with shopping malls, first-class restaurants, high-rise corporate and condominium buildings, and five-star hotels is a welcome breather - a distinctive characteristic that sets Muntinlupa apart from other urban centers in Metro Manila.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Cultural and Tourism Development Office, 4/L Annex Building, Muntinlupa City Hall, National Road, Barangay Putatan, Muntinlupa City 1770 with telephone nos. 862-6454. Visit official website at <a href=\"http://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph\" >www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','Once considered as a haven for prisoners, the City of Muntinlupa now proudly stands as a premier business location. Muntin- lupa, which literally means ‘little land’ is small in size but big in business as the City is now one of the fastest growing business centers in the country.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/muntinlupa',NULL,0,41,42,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:35:54','2012-09-12 06:35:00'),(36,NULL,1,'City of Masbate','masbate','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfMasbate1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>From the chronicles of the early years of Spanish colonization, reports about Masbate first appeared in July 1569 when Fray Martin de Rada wrote to the Viceroy of New Spain (Mexico), Marquis de Falces. He mentioned that in a place called Masbat there were plenty of gold and mines. Other later documents such as those of Artieda’s Ralacion (1573) and Andres de Mirandaola’s letter (1574) reported of a place called Masbat or Masbad.</p>\r\n            <p>The name variation is understandable as Spaniards spoke in an aspirated manner. Masbad must have been pronounced Masbat by the Spanish tongue. In 1582, Miguel de Lorca reported about a place called Masbate. This was the first time the name was used in place of Masbad or Masbat.</p>\r\n            <p>On September 30, 2000, Republic Act 8807 officially proclaimed the conversion of the Municipality of Masbate into a component city.</p>\r\n            <p>Masbate is the capital of the Masbate province. The city’s total land area is 187.892811 square kilometers. It has 30 barangays, 11 of which are urban located in the Poblacion.</p>\r\n            <p>Masbate is fulfilling its vision to become the country’s Marine Sanctuary by 2020.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfMasbate2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Lapay Bantigue Festival – It is celebrated on September 29 annually during the City’s founding anniversary.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Pagdayao Festival – It is celebrated every June 13 in honor of the City’s patron, Saint Anthony of Padua.</li>\r\n                <li>3. The Masbate City’s Coastal Resource Management Inter- pretive Center (CRMIC) – It is designed to showcase and pro- mote Masbate’s rich coastal environment and heritage. One can plan and begin a journey of discovery and explore the amazing and diverse natural and cultural wonders of the province and its more than 50 islands and islets.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Rodeo Festival – It is celebrated every second Monday of April. It showcases ten competitive rodeo events such as cattle wrestling, lassoing, and bull riding among others.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Masbate Population: 81,855</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>In Araneta Center Cubao, there is daily roll-on roll-off (Roro) trip which leaves Manila at 1:00 PM. The Mega Bus and Elavil Bus have daily trips from Manila to Masbate via Pilar port.</p>\r\n            <p>From Cebu, a Roro bus leaves at 7:30 PM in Bogo every Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays. Via Trans Asia, Cebu- Masbate route is every Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays. Masbate can also be reached through the sea onboard luxury shipping lines like the Shuttle Roro (Batangas-Mas- bate every Tuesdays, 3:00 PM; Cebu-Masbate, every Sun- days, 5:00 AM) and MV Mary the Queen (Masbate-Manila- Masbate every Tuesday, 10:00 AM)</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the CRMIC office, Old City Hall Bldg, City Hall Compound, Masbate City with telephone nos. (056) 588- 1120 or (056) 333-5608. Email queries at aksyonpadayon@yahoo.com. Visit the website at <a href=\"http://www.masbatecity.gov.ph\" >www.masbatecity.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','From the chronicles of the early years of Spanish colonization, reports about Masbate first appeared in July 1569 when Fray Martin de Rada wrote to the Viceroy of New Spain (Mexico), Marquis de Falces.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/masbate',NULL,0,43,44,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:36:29','2012-09-12 06:36:00'),(37,NULL,1,'Alaminos City','alaminos','          <h3>Home of the Hundred Islands</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/alaminos1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n            <p>\r\n                Alaminos City is the heart of Western Pangasinan. It is rich in natural and man-made attractions like the world famous Hun- dred Islands National Park, making tourism a flourishing indus- try. The Hundred Islands boasts of pristine beauty, white sand beaches and cool, clear waters. Other spots in the City are the Baleyadaan Ruins — the seat of Alaminos during the Spanish era, now the site of church ruins - and the Pag-Asinan, featuring the salt-making industry which Pangasinan is known for.\r\n            </p>\r\n            <p>\r\n                The City of Alaminos lies along the shore of the historical Lingayen Gulf. It is bounded on the north by the Lingayen Gulf where the Hundred Islands can be found; on the east by the Municipality of Sual; on the south by the Municipality of Mabini; and on the west by the Municipality of Bani.\r\n            </p>\r\n            <p>\r\n                Some highly sought foods in the City include the boneless bangus (milkfish), goat meat, parad (spareribs) and longganisa (sau- sage).\r\n            </p>\r\n            <p>\r\n                Alaminians pay homage to its patron saint, St. Joseph, every third week of March through a colorful celebration called Gali-La Hundred Islands Festival.\r\n            </p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    1. The City fiesta in honor of Patron Saint Joseph and the Gali-La Hundred Islands Festival (third week of March, actual fiesta is March 19) – This festival is the most anticipated event in Alaminos City showcasing a range of activities from different arts and performance competitions, various fun-filled activities such as concerts of famous artists and a city-wide street party and agri-trade fair.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    2. Village fiestas – All the 39 barangays (villages) of Alaminos City celebrate their own fiesta to honor their individual patron saints. Each home in the barangay serves sumptuous food to friends and guests. Barangay fiesta starts as early as first week of December (in Brgy. Pangapisan) and runs up to May (in Brgy. Maawi). Moro-Moro or Zarzuela, the traditional musical play, is often presented during barangay fiestas.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    3. The Gali-Langoy Eco-Adventure Race – This is celebrated every Labor Day (May 1) where the City hosts swimming, parao racing, kayaking and other water sports competition. The most unique feature is the island-to-island race. It is a growing popu- lar attraction in the City.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>4. The Ban-oitan Ed Alaminos – This sport fishing competition is held every September 29. It is one of the highlights of the celebration of the turnover of the Hundred Island National Park from the Philippine Tourism Authority to Alaminos City. The competition promotes the hook and line fishing which is legal, safe and environment-friendly. Competitors vie for the biggest fish catch and heaviest fish, among others.</li>\r\n                <li>5. The Underwater Weddings – Experience Valentine’s Day (February 14) with an extraordinary underwater wedding or watch hundreds of couples exchange “I Do\'s” every February 14 in either one of these romantic locations — Bolo Beach, Lucap Wharf, or the Hundred Islands.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/alaminos2.png\" alt=\"Alaminos City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of Alaminos’ Must Do List</h3>\r\n\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    1. Go on a Hundred Islands adventure. Explore and see what works for you from a host of island activities. Check out the giant clams or go snorkeling, cliff diving, island hopping, spelunking, fun-fishing, parasailing, jet skiing, kayaking, scuba diving, banana boat riding, birdwatching, or simply sun bathing anywhere in the 123 islands of your choice. If you are lucky enough, you might just get a rare peek of visiting whales and dolphins.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    2. Savor the Alaminos longganisa. One distinct feature of this variant of Philippine sausage (chorizo) is that its ends are sealed with little sticks. But what stands out is its garlicky and slightly salty taste. It is best when charbroiled and dipped in a spicy condiment.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    3. Check out Camantiles Island Eco-Trail Park and explore its flora and fauna. It is the only island that can be reached by hiking. An island, is it? Years and years of wave movement created a sandbar that connected it to the mainland. Trails leading into the island’s deep forest recesses have been created—a nature lover’s dream. Or as an alternative, try the Bued Mangrove Park.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    4. Buy a shellcraft at the Lucap Wharf. These expertly crafted mementos speak of the artistry and patience of the Ala- minos shellcraft makers. Some are great adornments to grace a living room or add a touch of the sea in a veranda or a cabana.\r\n                </li>\r\n                <li>\r\n                    5. Discover Alaminos City’s best practices. Visit the Maria Valdez Cornelia Techno-Demo Farm located in the village of Tangcarang and check out its hybrid and organic agricultural products. One may also drop by Tangcarang Elementary School, one of the 45 schools in the city that is connected through the city’s innovative WINGS project (also known as Wireless Internet-based Governance System). Immerse in any of the schools and learn about the city’s Bright Child, an integrated program that targets education, social welfare and development, health and nutrition, and sports and cultural awareness.\r\n                </li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Alaminos</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 79,788 (2007 Census)</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>\r\n                In Manila, Victory Liner, Five Star and Philippine Rabbit bus lines have daily trips bound for Alaminos City which traverse the provinces of Bulacan, Pampanga and Tarlac. The esti- mated travel time is five to six hours.\r\n            </p>\r\n            <p>\r\n                From Baguio City, there are trips that go straight to Ala- minos or one can take a bus to Dagupan City and easily transfer to one that is bound Alaminos. The estimated travel time is two to three hours. There is also a domestic airport in San Fernando City, La Union and public buses have trips to Alaminos via Dagupan City. The estimated travel time from Dagupan to Alaminos is one to two hours.\r\n            </p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>\r\n                April and May are the best months to spend time in Alaminos City and in the Hundred Islands. There is less chance of rain and visitors are assured of hot summer days and balmy nights.\r\n            </p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>\r\n                Contact the the City Tourism Office at (075) 551-2145 or the Hundred Islands National Park (HINP) Welcome Center at (075) 551-2505.\r\n            </p>\r\n            <p>\r\n                Visit <a href=\"www.alaminoscity.gov.ph\">www.alaminoscity.gov.ph</a> and <a href=\"www.hundredislands.ph\">www.hundredislands.ph</a> or like Alaminos City on Facebook, search facebook/galila.alaminians\r\n            </p>\r\n','Alaminos City is the heart of Western Pangasinan. It is rich in natural and man-made attractions like the world famous Hun- dred Islands National Park, making tourism a flourishing industry.',1,NULL,1,0,0,'/visit/alaminos',NULL,0,1,2,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:09:43','2012-09-12 05:38:00'),(38,NULL,1,'Angeles City','angeles','            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/angelesCity1.png\" alt=\"Angeles City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Angeles City is a highly urbanized city located in the province of Pampanga. Economic growth for this City was initially perceived as an offshoot of the presence of the adjacent Clark Air Base but the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo in 1991 and the subsequent evacuation of the Americans proved this wrong. The resilience of the Angelenos, however, rose above this tragedy.</p>\r\n            <p>Tourism in the City has become a flourishing industry with the influx of travelers comprising mostly of long staying guests. Life- style comforts are within reach but the City maintains a relaxed atmosphere that is usually enjoyed in the countryside.</p>\r\n            <p>With its growing number of foreign residents who have brought their culture with them, the City pulsates with a cosmopolitan vibe.</p>\r\n            <p>Angelenos are recognized for their skills, knowledge and appreciation of excellent food. Angeles City is a melting pot of cultures where one can enjoy the best of Kapampangan cooking along- side high quality international cuisine.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Tigtigan Terakan Keng Dalan Festival is Kapampangan for music and dancing in the streets. Every year on the last Friday and Saturday nights of October, the City holds the biggest street party that can last until the break of dawn. Started in 1991, it was conceptualized to uplift the spirit of the city residents from the devastated impact of Mt. Pinatubo. Now on its 20th year, the event lives on to commemorate Angeleno resilience and celebrate life after the tragedy of the Mt. Pinatubo eruption.</li>\r\n                <li>2. La Naval Fiesta, the first of Angeles City’s twin fiesta in October, is held every second Sunday in commemoration of the Virgin of the Holy Rosary, whose intercession saw the victory of the Spanish fleet over the Dutch invaders. The City celebrates fiesta with traditional religious programs while homes display the finest traditions of hospitality by entertaining guests with their best cooking and most extravagant food spread.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Piyesta ning Apung Mamacalulu or the Feast of Our Lord of Mercy, the second of the twin fiesta, is celebrated on the last Friday of October. Devotees from all over Pampanga flock to the Apu shrine every Friday to venerate the miraculous image of Jesus Christ lying in the sepulcher.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Philippine Independence Day Re-Enactment at the Old Pamintuan Mansion is performed on June 12 every year. In 1899, a year after the independence of the Philippines under Spanish rule, President Emilio Aguinaldo moved the seat of government to Angeles City during the Filipino-American War. A passionate re-enactment of the first and only Independence Day anniversary celebration is held yearly complete with the actual speech of Aguinaldo translated into Filipino.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Limbun is a Good Friday procession featuring circa 1830 religious carriages and iconic floats. Since the early 1800s, this Lenten tradition is attended by devotees and visitors including men who wear traditional costumes while pulling the carros which adds color to the serene proceedings.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/angelesCity2.png\" alt=\"Angeles City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Angeles City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Take a heritage and historical tour. At the center of Sto. Heritage District is the Holy Rosary Parish Church, Angeles City’s most famous landmark. Kapampangans are a proud group and one can learn more about them at the Center for Kapampangan Studies at Holy Angel University. Visit the Museo ning Angeles housed at the old municipio building and find out how Angeles City came to be -- from its beginnings, the aftermath of the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo to the makings of an emerging cosmopolitan city. A guided package tour can be arranged at the Museo ning Angeles.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Eat Kapampangan. Angeles City is located in Pampanga, known as the Culinary Capital of the Philippines. The City is the birthplace of the sizzling sisig. For the adventurous, try famous exoticas such as betute, frogs stuffed with ground pork meat and local herbs, and camaru (mole crickets) cooked dry adobo-style.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Indulge in international cuisine in the City’s gastronomic belt. Spoil yourself on a staggering array of international restau- rants in the city’s entertainment center. Stretching from the Balibago Strip to Fields District, Don Juico Avenue and all the way to Fil-Am Friendship Highway just outside Clark Freeport Zone, Angeles City’s gastronomic belt is home to the best of world cuisine. A melting pot of culinary cultures, Angeles City is also the birthplace of Panizza, a thin-crust panini cum pizza rolled with arugula and alfalfa sprouts. This culinary invention by a Swiss national turned Angeleno has been making waves in the national scene and replicated in many restaurants in and out of the city.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Pamper yourself at the Puning Hot Springs. Enjoy a healing trip at Angeles City’s nature’s spa located in Barangay Sapang Bato complete with beauty treatments, lunch, a round trip 4x4 ride from the Garden Restaurant to the hot springs, use of facilities, sand steam where you will be covered up to your neck with volcanic sand, body mud pack, and a foot massage. One attraction is a steaming hot waterfall.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Bask in the glow of city night life. Chill out and enjoy the laidback atmosphere at the Balibago’s entertainment district. Enjoy live weekend music with your date, friends or family at Cioccolo Bistro, located within the plush Grand Palazzo Royale Estate. There are over a hundred night establishments in Angeles City – many are within walking or short driving distance from each other. Activities range from the international standard night clubs, Japanese and Chinese-style karaoke bars, to hi- tech discothèques. Feeling lucky? Your fortune could just turn for the better inside the Casino Filipino Angeles along McArthur Highway in Balibago, just outside of Clark.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Angeles City</p>\r\n\r\n            <p>Population: 343,844 (2007 Census)</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Angeles City is located at the heart of the Pampanga province in Central Luzon.\r\n                From Manila, it is 83 kilometers, a 45-minute drive via the North Luzon Expressway. Motorists coming from Metro Manila are advised to exit at the Angeles – Magalang toll plaza to proceed to the City proper.\r\n                The Diosdado Macapagal International Airport offers regular flights to Manila and Caticlan via Seair, Inc. and Cebu via Cebu Pacific. International flights to Malaysia (Kuala Lumpur and Kota Kinabalu), Singapore, Macau, Thailand (Bangkok), Taiwan (Taipei) Hong Kong and South Korea are also available.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. Angeles City is a year-round destination but the celebration of its twin fiesta in October offers a host of exciting activities ranging from cultural, culinary, community and sports events.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact Angeles City Tourism Office, Angeles City Hall, Pulung Maragul, Angeles City with telephone nos. (045) 322-0507. Email at ilikeangeles at gmail.com. Visit website at <a href=\"http://angelescitytourism.com.ph\">angelescitytourism.com.ph</a></p>\r\n','Angeles City is a highly urbanized city located in the province of Pampanga.',1,NULL,1,0,0,'/visit/angeles',NULL,0,3,4,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:09:27','2012-09-12 05:46:00'),(39,NULL,1,'Antipolo City','antipolo','            <h3>The Pilgrimage City</h3>\r\n            <hr>\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/antipoloCity1.png\" alt=\"Antipolo City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Antipolo is an urban area in a rural setting. It is the home of the famed Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage which is declared a National Shrine. All throughout the year, thousands of devotees from all walks of life visit this famed Patroness because of the numerous miracles believed she has performed for the City.</p>\r\n            <p>Agro-industrial, commercial and tourism are prime movers of its economic development. The City also boasts of its cool climate, rugged terrains, panoramic views, and vast natural resources.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. First week of May. Ang Tipulo Festival. The City of Antipolo found her name from a tree called Tipulo where folklore tells that whenever the image of the Blessed Virgin disappears in the altars of the parishes, she was always found on top of the Tipulo tree that made her enshrined permanently in Antipolo. From this tree came the official name of the festival celebrated during the opening of Maytime Festivities of the City of Antipolo within the first week of May. The event, previously called “The SUMAKAH Festival” for Suman, Mangga, Kasoy and Hamakah, is a celebra- tion of the history of the city mostly attributed to Nuestra Se- ñora dela Paz y Buen Viaje. The official song, the famous “Tayo Na Sa Antipolo”, must always be included in the music used for the street dancing competition of the 16 barangays of Antipolo City.</li>\r\n                <li>2. May to July. The Pilgrimage Season of Antipolo City in hon- or of Nuestra Señora dela Paz y Buen Viaje is the longest in the country which runs for 63 days consisting of seven Novenas.</li>\r\n                <li>3. December 07. Bisperas ng Fiesta For the Feast of the Im- maculate Conception Grand Parade. A grand parade, spear- headed by the city government, is held within the City proper a day before the City Fiesta celebrating the Feast Day of the Immaculate Conception, the Patroness of the parish.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/antipoloCity2.png\" alt=\"Antipolo City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Antipolo City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Pay homage to the Virgin of Antipolo enshrined at the National Shrine of Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Have a moment of reflection at Via Dolorosa at the Pinagmisahan Hill or at the Old Boso-Boso Church.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Bring home some of favorite pasalubongs: adobong kasuy, suman, latik, mangga at kalamay.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Dine in any of the restaurants or hotels at “The Overlooking” along Sumulong Highway.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Take a dip in any of the City’s affordable resorts, get a soothing massage in any of the spas, enjoy outdoor activities in all-natural camping sites, gain from team building activities in conference centers and exhibit one’s prowess in playing golf in world-class golf courses.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Antipolo City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 633,971</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Antipolo is located in the northern part of Rizal province. The City proper is 29.3 kilometers away from Metro Ma- nila. Antipolo can be accessed from Marikina City via the Sumulong Highway which extends to the Poblacion from Cubao, Quezon City via the Marcos Highway which extends eastward to Quezon Province through the Marikina-Infanta Road; and from Cainta/Taytay via Ortigas Extension.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>The whole month of May. This is the pilgrimage season where pilgrims from other parts of the country as well as for- eigners pay homage to the National Shrine of Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage. Visitors also go to the Hinulugan Taktak and other resorts within the City.</p>\r\n','Antipolo is an urban area in a rural setting. It is the home of the famed Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage which is declared a National Shrine.',1,NULL,1,0,0,'/visit/antipolo',NULL,0,5,6,'','visit','2012-09-12 05:52:16','2012-09-12 05:50:00'),(40,NULL,1,'Baguio City','baguio','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/baguioCity1.png\" alt=\"Baguio City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Baguio City remains a prime tourist destination area in North Luzon because of its cool climate, fresh, green and peaceful environment. This makes it a favorite destination especially for those who like to relax and stay away from the excessive heat of the lowlands and also a favorite venue of seminars and conferences.</p>\r\n            <p>Baguio is the midway to the wonders of Northern Luzon. The calm beaches of La Union; the fabled Hundred Islands; the ancient churches, Spanish-influenced houses, historical, and cul- tural relics of Ilocos Sur and Ilocos Norte and is also the gateway to the Cordilleras where you can find the world-famous Banaue Rice Terraces in Ifugao; the Kabayan mummy caves of Benguet; and the distinct culture and colorful traditions of the tribes of Benguet, Mountain Province, Ifugao, Kalinga Apayao, and Abra.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Kennon Road and its builder – Named after Col. Lyman W. Kennon, who was the final builder of the famous Benguet road, with the help of industrious Cordilleras and foreign workers. Kennon Road is the shortest and most scenic highway linking Baguio and the lowlands. The Lion’s head can be found along the way. Final construction of this road was finished in 1903. Col. L. Kennon was ascended to Baguio City in 1905. Of the original workers, the Igorots and the Japanese were admired for their trustworthiness and willingness to work.</li>\r\n                <li>2. The Presidential Mansion – The Philippine President’s summer residence. This imposing and majestic Baguio man- sion house has a long list of Filipino presidents and American governor-generals. It has an elegantly structured building and guesthouse. Its gate is patterned after that of London’s Buck- ingham Palace.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Asin Hot Spring – Located 16 kilometers northwest of Baguio. The resort’s main feature is a swimming pool surrounded by thermal springs, lush vegetation and several hanging bridges.\r\n                    It has an ideal respite. This is now eyed to be redeveloped into\r\n                    a tourism resort along with the adjoining tourist attractions of Tuba and Baguio.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Burnham Park- It is the oldest of all Baguio parks. One can unwind from the tension of the day to day bustle of biking, skat- ing, or simply reflecting on the day’s experiences amid a sooth- ing garden backdrop of colorful flowers. It is thickly wooded and is a great place to have a picnics and concerts.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Baguio Flower Festival – Panagbenga – Focuses on the Ba- guio as the Flower Garden City of the North. Highlights include the street dancing competition, flower exhibits, lectures, garden tours, floral contest and a parade of floats.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/baguioCity2.png\" alt=\"Baguio City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Baguio City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the numerous parks and family-oriented facility in the City</li>\r\n                <li>2. Go bargain-hunting at numerous curio and novelty ships located at the central business district</li>\r\n                <li>3. Immerse yourself in the culture and the arts by visiting the various museums and exhibits that dot the City</li>\r\n                <li>4. Participate in the all-year round and events-based activities offered by the City and private sector.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Simply curl up and stay toasty in bed while taking pleasure of the cool climate of the City</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n\r\n            <p>Official Name: Baguio City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 393,696 (2010 Census)</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Travel time to reach Baguio City by bus with an average of seven hours from Manila. The three main access roads leading to Baguio from the lowlands are Kennon Road, Aspiras-Palispis Highway (formerly Marcos Highway), and the Naguilian Road, also known as the Quirino Highway.</p>\r\n            <p>Another access to Baguio from Aritao in the province of Nueva Vizcaya passing through Itogon, Benguet. Another route, Hanselma Highway leads North through mountainous portion of the Cordillera Autonomous Region.</p>\r\n            <p>By air, Loakan Airport is the only airport serving the general area of Baguio City. The airport is classified as a trunkline airport or a major commercial domestic airport.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. February is the best time since most visitors can witness the annual Panagbenga Festival towards the summer break and Holy Week.</p>\r\n            <p>2. The period starting the academic break in October to- wards the month of December where Christmas becomes a favored time for most vacationers.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact, Baguio City Tourism Office, Baguio Conven- tion Center with telephone nos. (074)- 442-1007. Visit the City’s website at <a href=\"www.baguio.gov.ph\">www.baguio.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','Baguio City remains a prime tourist destination area in North Luzon because of its cool climate, fresh, green and peaceful environment.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/baguio',NULL,0,7,8,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:08:49','2012-09-12 05:53:00'),(41,NULL,1,'Bais City','bais','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/baisCity1.png\" alt=\"Bais City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Bais got its name from an elongated eel-like fish that used to abound in the locality’s streams and rivers. Legend has it that when a group of Spanish engineers and surveyors asked the natives of the name of the place, they answered Bais, thinking that then foreigners were asking the name of the fish they were catching.</p>\r\n            <p>Bais was once a barrio of the Municipality of Manjuyod when the village headman and his followers pledged loyalty to the Alcalde of the municipality. When the Americans put an end to the Spanish regime in the Philippines, Negros Oriental became a province with the late Demetrio Larena of Bais holding the distinction as its first governor.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1901, Bais was recognized as a town. Since then, Bais contin- ued to move forward with remarkable persistence towards being a City and center of progress and development.</p>\r\n            <p>The City of Bais came into being on September 1, 1968. Former President Ferdinand E. Marcos personally proclaimed Bais as a City on September 9, 1968.</p>\r\n            <p>At present, the City of Bais is known for its eco-tourism develop- ment highlighting its rich and highly diverse coastal and marine eco-system as well as its pristine beaches and other well-con- served natural resources.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. March to October - Best time for dolphin and whale watching</li>\r\n                <li>2. Fiesta Season – First week of September - Lots of week-long fun and merry making</li>\r\n                <li>3. Christmas Season – month-long Christmas festival</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Dolphin and whale watching eco-tour package during March\r\n                    to October.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Sipong sa Bais Festival every September 07.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Pasko sa Bais Festival every first week of December up to second week of January.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Agro-Industrial and Seafood Fair/ Salawaki and Seafoods Festival during the first week of September.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Tour to Central Azucarera de Bais through the Tourism Op- erations Division of Bais City.</li>\r\n                <li>6. An educational tour to the Bais City Waste Management Center that can be arranged through the City Environment and Natural Resources Office (City ENRO)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/baisCity2.png\" alt=\"Bais City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Bais City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Enjoy dolphin watching and eco-tour. One should experience dolphin watching off the coast of Tañon Strait between the islands of Negros and Cebu where one can get a one-of-a kind experience with the sea’s very friendly, lovable, and intelligent creatures. There are 11 out of the 24 cetaceans in the Philippines that are found in Tañon Strait. Included the tour package is a visit to the seven-kilometer white sand bar where sun lovers can enjoy sun bathing, beach volleyball, and other recreational activities during low tide.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Savor the seafood feast. The delicious salawaki or sea urchin (tripneutis gratilla) is a must-to-enjoy-and-eat which is believed to have an aphrodisiac effect. The eating of the salawaki is one of highlights during the Salawaki and Seafoods Festival held every first week of September. Other seafood/fishery products such as squids, tilapia, bangus, kitong, oysters, crabs and shellfishes shared the Festival’s limelight either cooked or eaten raw.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Be thrilled with the Christmas Fair. The Pasko sa Bais Festival, held at the City’s ball field, is an annual Christmas celebration featuring a 20-meter gigantic Christmas tree and decors around the City Plaza. The Christmas Festival has continually drawn domestic and foreign tourists over the years.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Join the fun in the Street dancing and merry making. Enjoy and watch the Sipong sa Bais Festival, a street dancing competition showcasing the social and cultural heritage of the City. Sipong was a practice on the City’s ancestors as a thanksgiving after a good and bountiful harvest. It also depicted a bountiful harvest of sugarcane, various crops and sea products, coming from the thirty five (35) barangays of the city.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Best to dine at our local restaurants such as La Planta Hotel and Restaurant, Fuyma Restaurant, Jacob’s Barbecue House and Wonka Restaurant where good food is served by friendly and accommodating staff. For native chicken and pork lovers, Bais Tocino Country for a cook-out of grilled native chicken and pork paired with the native “puso” (rice indi- vidually wrapped in coconut leaves and steam-cooked).</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Bais</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 80,759</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Bais City is one of the five cities of the Province of Negros Oriental in the Central Visayas Region (Region 7) occupying the eastern portion of Negros Island.</p>\r\n            <p>Bais City is easily and conveniently accessible by land travel from the nearest ports of entry. Bais City is 43 kilometers north of the Commercial Airport of Dumaguete, the pro- vincial capital, and 45 kilometers from the Dumaguete Sea Port.</p>\r\n            <p>Travel time by land from Dumaguete City is less than an hour while travel time by land from the Occidental side (Bacolod City) is four hours via Mabinay and six hours via San Carlos City.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact Bais City Tourism Office with telephone nos. at (035) 402-8338, (035) 402-8257 or (035) 402-6629 (for reservations on the dolphin and whale watching tour pack- age). Visit the City’s website at http://baiscity.gov.ph</p>','Bais got its name from an elongated eel-like fish that used to abound in the locality’s streams and rivers.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/bais',NULL,0,9,10,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:08:36','2012-09-12 05:54:00'),(42,NULL,1,'Balanga City','balanga','            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/balangaCity1.png\" alt=\"Balanga City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The City of Balanga, capital of Bataan province, was formerly a visita of Abucay before it was established as a mission of the Dominican Order in the Provincial Charter of April 21, 1714, and later declared as a vicariate on April 18, 1739, under the patron- age of Saint Joseph. Upon the establishment of Bataan as a separate province in 1754, Balanga was made its capital by Gen. Pedro Manuel Arandia due to its favorable location at the heart of the new territorial jurisdiction.</p>\r\n            <p>The word Balanga originated from the Tagalog word banga (clay pot), which the town used to produce and which was known to be among the best that could be found in the\r\n                country.</p>\r\n            <p>On December 30, 2000, Balanga became a Component City by virtue of Republic Act No. 8984. During this period, Balanga was established as a Tech City.\r\n                Today, being the center of excellence in education, Balanga is a fast-developing city. It keeps on striving and working for the re- alization of its vision. The City aspires to become “A World Class University Town by the year 2020, acknowledged as the center of political, economic, social and cultural interaction in the region.” Its mission is to “provide strong academic atmosphere that will ensure sustainable development for the City.”</p>\r\n            <p>In terms of economic progress, the City is an investment haven. It is considered as the centre of entrepreneurship in the prov- ince. Investors acknowledge the City which is empowering entrepreneurs to succeed in their business ventures. Several big establishments are also starting their businesses like the soon-to- rise Galeria Victoria,\r\n                a five-storey commercial building located at the heart of the City that is expected to boost employment, generate additional jobs, and create new work opportunities for local residents.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major Destinations and Festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Balanga City Wetland and Nature Park - The newest tourism destination in the City that serves as the first park in the Philip- pines that uses nature as an outdoor recreational museum and teaching aid for the City residents and visitors. Located in Baran- gay Tortugas, it serves as a haven for wildlife creatures.</li>\r\n                <li>2. World Class City Public Market - A modern facility that pro- vides a memorable marketing experience to local consumers and tourists alike located in Barangay San Jose.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Saint Joseph Cathedral l - During the Japanese invasion, the Cathedral was used as an artillery emplacement to bombard Mt. Samat where Filipino-American troops staged their last defense. It was later renovated by the first bishop of the Diocese, Bishop Celso Guevarra DD, and made its patron saint, Saint Joseph.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Surrender Site - Located in Balanga Elementary School ground, this site was used as a command post by Lt. Gen. Homma at the time of Bataan’s Surrender wherein Major Gen. King and his party signed the documents for the surrender of the USAFFE forces in the Philippines under a mango tree on April 9, 1942.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/balangaCity2.png\" alt=\"Balanga City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Balanga City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the City Wetland & Nature Park for a migratory bird-watching experience. This is the newest addition to bird- watching or birding sites being promoted by the Department of Tourism (DOT), the Philippine Convention & Visitors Corporation (PCVC) and the Wild Bird Club of the Philippines (WBCP).</li>\r\n                <li>2. Dine and experience the culinary treats with homegrown restaurants like J2 Fastfood Nook, Joyous Fishpond Resort, Lou-is Resort & Restaurant, Tangway Grill, etc. Try also the best palabok and kalamay at Aling Edios and Estrella’s’ Eater- ies, both located in Barangay Cupang North, Balanga City.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Attend the month-long Pista Balangueno (April) and Paskong Balangueno (December) celebrations and feel the warmth hospitality of Balanguenos.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Buy pasalubong at the New City of Balanga Public Market and bring home a piece of Balanga through export-quality products like boneless tinapa (smoked processed fish), bagoong (Shrimp paste), tuyo (dried fish) and Araro Cookies;</li>\r\n                <li>5. Spend the night at local hotels such as Crown Royale Hotel, GAP Plaza Hotel and Hillside Garden Mansions or try an adrenaline-rushed adventure at La Vista Resort Inland Resort\r\n                </li></ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Balanga</p>\r\n            <li>Population: 91,059 (as of December 2010)</li>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, the city is 124 kilometers and can be reached by land within two to three hours. The City can also be reached via a ferry boat service from Pasay City to Limay port with 45 minutes travel time and a 20-minute ride by jeep or bus going to the City proper</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. April – For the month-long celebration of the City fiesta; 2. December – For the month-long celebration of Paskong Balangueno\r\n                For travel information</p>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office at telephone nos. (047) 791-4008; City Mayor’s Office at telephone nos. (047) 237-2969, (047) 791-2099. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"www.cityofbalanga.gov.ph\">www.cityofbalanga.gov.ph</a></p>','The City of Balanga, capital of Bataan province, was formerly a visita of Abucay before it was established as a mission of the Dominican Order in the Provincial Charter of April 21, 1714, and later declared as a vicariate on April 18, 1739, under the patron- age of Saint Joseph.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/balanga',NULL,0,11,12,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:08:21','2012-09-12 05:55:00'),(43,NULL,1,'Batangas City','batangas','           <h3>Industrial Port City of Calabarzon</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/batangasCity1.png\" alt=\"Batangas City\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Batangas City is discovered by Spanish missionaries in 1572. It was named Batangan due to numerous big logs or batang that abound the Calumpang River. Located 112 kilometers south of Manila, it has a total land area of 28,541 hectares divided into 105 barangays. It was proclaimed a City on July 23, 1969. From the day of its found- ing, the City has transformed from a budding city to a booming metropolis. It is now one of the major centers of commerce and industry south of Manila.</p>\r\n            <p>The City’s international port, a vital link in the nautical highway, serves hundreds of thousands of passenger and tons of volume of domestic and foreign cargo.</p>\r\n            <p>From a mere Php 40 million annual budget in 1988, the City has a current annual budget of Php 1.2 billion.</p>\r\n            <p>Business and technology have drastically altered the City’s land- scape. Batangas City is the site of the biggest oil refineries in Asia, the Pilipinas Shell Petroleum Corporation, JG Summit Petro- chemical Corporation and the three natural gas combined cycle power plants – Sta. Rita, San Lorenzo of First Gas Power Plant Corporation, and Ilijan power plant of Korean Electric Company. This has a total generative capacity of 2,700 megawatts supply- ing 70% of the power requirements of the Luzon grid.</p>\r\n            <p>Fueling the local economy are 47 banking institutions, three public markets, and 3,000 small and medium business establish- ments.</p>\r\n            <p>Although the City has been identified as an industrializing city, the emphasis on agriculture production goes hand in hand with industrialization to realize its growth targets. The City produces 75% of livestock that is supplied to Manila and 25% for local consumption.</p>\r\n            <p>Education is also an equal priority. The City government runs 116 daycare centers and one tertiary school. Environmental protection is another priority program in the City. The passage of the Batangas City Environment Code and the establishment of a Materials Recovery Facility in every barangay to sustain the ecological management of solid wastes is a reiteration of the City’s assertive campaign to make cleaning and waste segregation as a way of life. This is Batangas City today, a fast urbanizing city in harmony with ecological balance.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/batangasCity2.png\" alt=\"Batangas City\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Batangas City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Spend time in Plaza Mabini. The people’s park was designed by the world renowned urban planner, Palafox and Associates. It can be found at the heart of the City just across the City Hall and the Basilica Church.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Pray at the Basilica Minor of Infant Jesus and Immaculate Concepcion. It was built in 1500s and considered as one of the oldest architectural treasures of the city. In the restored Sacristy of the Basilica is the Yatco Museum which show- cases priceless Catholic artifacts.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Marvel the old past at the Pastor-Acosta Ancestral House. One of the several ancestral houses in the City where the original structure and furnishings of old are maintained and preserved.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Learn the City’s history in Museo Puntong Batangan It showcases various artifacts and historical accounts of Batan- gas City dating to the pre-Spanish period.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Dive at Isla Verde. Its dive spots are one of the best in the region. It is part of the center of the center of the world’s marine biodiversity. The whale-shaped island also boasts of long white sand at Mahabang Buhangin with crystal blue waters and thick forested slopes.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Batangas City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 317,559</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, it is 112 kilometers with a travel time of two and a half hours. All routes within and outside the city are serviced by bus lines like the ALPS Express, JAM Trans, Supreme Trans, Liner Inc., DLTB Co., Pong and Oning Trans, N. Dela Rosa, Batangas Star Express, RRCG, and Ceres Trans. The city is one and half hours away from the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.</p>\r\n            <p>Ferry boats and other water crafts connect the city to Mind- oro, Romblon, and other nearby ports/islands</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. January – The City Fiesta (January 7-16). A week-long celebration starting on January 7 with a fluvial procession where the icon of Sto. Nino, the city’s patron saint, is pa- raded on a decorated banca in Calumpang River.</p>\r\n            <p>2. July – The Sublian Festival (July 12-23). A two-week cel- ebration which features the revival of Batangueño traditions and culminates with the Sublian competition on July 23, the city’s founding anniversary.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Planning and Development Coordi- nator Office at telephone nos. (043) 723-1832 and/or (043) 723-4108. Email at jbgcpdo@mozcom.com.</p>\r\n','Batangas City is discovered by Spanish missionaries in 1572. It was named Batangan due to numerous big logs or batang that abound the Calumpang River.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/batangas',NULL,0,13,14,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:07:58','2012-09-12 05:58:00'),(44,NULL,1,'Bayawan City','bayawan','\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/bayawanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>On December 23, 2000, Bayawan City became a Component City in the third district of Negros Oriental. It has 28 barangays with a total land area of 69,908 hectares, the largest in the Province. It has a population growth rate of 2.59%. Bayawan City is also a key transport and trading hub in the south of Negros Island.</p>\r\n            <p>Since the Cityhood, Bayawan City has been recognized for best practices and a learning site on ecological wastes management, food security program, community health care initiatives and cooperative partnerships.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is one of the most competitive small-sized cities in the country. It has a continuous drive for public governance excel- lence. It envisions itself to be a self reliant community with a sustainable, diversified agricultural economy such that appropri- ate public services are provided to improve the quality of life of the Bayawanon, and make Bayawan a competitive and highly- livable City.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>How to get there</h3>\r\n            <p>From Manila, it is an hour flight bound for Dumaguete City and another two-hour drive for 101 kilometers down south before ar- riving at the City proper. </p>\r\n            <p>From Cebu, via plane, it is 30 minutes.</p>\r\n            <p>From Cebu City, one can also take a bus with direct land trip which takes about six to eight hours. From Dumaguete City, van- for-hires leave for Bayawan in hourly intervals, while buses leave in 20 minutes afterwards</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <p>1. February is the fiesta month of Bayawan. There is the Tawo- Tawo Festival which is a celebration of the bounty of the harvest season.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Tawo-Tawo Festival (February 17)</li>\r\n                <li>2. Pasko sa Bayawan (December)</li>\r\n                <li>3. Habhaban Cave Spelunking (Summer)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/bayawanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Bayawan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Witness the Tawo Tawo Festival in February</li>\r\n                <li>2. Al-Fresco Dining while Sunset Watching by the Boulevard</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit and learn from City Environmental Governance Projects such as A.) City Ecological Waste Manage- ment Center, Brgy. Maninihon B.) GK Fisherman’s Village and Constructed Wetland Waste Water Treatment Facility, Brgy. Villareal C.) Danapa Watershed Eco-Park, Barangay Nangka</li>\r\n                <li>4. Spelunking at the Habhaban Cave, Barangay Malabugas</li>\r\n                <li>5. Take home ‘baye-baye,’ a Bayawan’s delicacy. Just grab it either from Ivon’s or Morgados Rice Grinder along CM Recto.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For more travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Information Office located at the Integrated Business Center, Barangay Villareal, Bayawan City at telephone nos. (035)-531-0883 or (035)-430-0117. Visit the City’s website at <a href=\"www.bayawancity.gov.ph\">www.bayawancity.gov.ph</a>.</p>\r\n','On December 23, 2000, Bayawan City became a Component City in the third district of Negros Oriental.',1,NULL,1,0,0,'/visit/bayawan',NULL,0,15,16,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:07:45','2012-09-12 05:59:00'),(45,NULL,1,'Caloocan City','caloocan','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Makasaysayang Lungsod ng Caloocan</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/caloocanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Philippine history will never be complete without mentioning the name of Caloocan. It is rich with cultural and historical heritage. Once a sitio, the City had an important role during the outbreak of the Philippine Revolution, events of which were summarily captured and highlighted in a bronze monument, which serves as the City’s most famous landmark and what is now commonly known as the Andres Bonifacio Monument.</p>\r\n            <p>Despite the rapid urbanization, the City still enjoys the beauty and bounty of Mother Nature, more specifically in North Caloo- can. Among the resorts that feature and maintain the richness of nature are Villa Celedonia Valley Resort, Gubat sa Ciudad Resort, the Grogun Health Resort among others. These are located on areas with rolling terrain, abundant with old-age tall trees and equipped with recreational facilities such as swimming pools, pavilions and cottages.</p>\r\n            <p>The South Caloocan meanwhile is the entry point of travelers coming from North Luzon towards Metro Manila. It is a suitable place for lodging-inns.</p>\r\n            <p>Due to its notable potentials and development, Bagong Barrio area is being developed as the Rest and Recreation District of Caloocan City. The area is within the Central Business District. Its accessibility, availability of different modes of transportation, existence of difference communication facilities and its strategic location are considered as the areas’ plus factors.</p>\r\n            <p>Also considered as visitor’s destination in the City are the food chains and restaurants. The Boy Ching Woo Restaurant is the oldest restaurant in the City since 1939 and still being patron-\r\n                ized even by non-city residents. Most of the City’s famous res- taurants are concentrated in the A. Bonifacio Ave., De Los Santos Avenue, Rizal Avenue Extension, 10th Avenue and McArthur Highway.</p>\r\n            <p>Cultural activities depicting Filipino customs and traditions are conducted throughout the year. The newest event is the Pajotan Festival which is being celebrated every last Sunday of January in the streets of Maypajo.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural activities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Bonifacio Monument</li>\r\n                <li>2. San Roque Cathedral</li>\r\n                <li>3. Pajotan Festival</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/caloocanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Caloocan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the Bonifacio Monument</li>\r\n                <li>2. Visit San Roque Cathedral</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit PNR Horace Higgins Hall</li>\r\n                <li>4. Eat at Mabini Home Bakeshop</li>\r\n                <li>5. Watch the Pajotan Festival</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Caloocan City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 1,474,040</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Caloocan City is accessible via all modes of transports: jeepneys, buses, taxis and the Light Railway Transit. ‘Monu- mento’ is a famous landmark where all the public utility vehicles pass by.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>February when the city is celebrating its founding anniver- sary.</p>\r\n            <h4>For more travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Cultural Affairs Travel and Tourism Office with telephone nos. (02) 323-5173. Visit www.caloocancity. gov.ph for more details.</p>\r\n','Philippine history will never be complete without mentioning the name of Caloocan. It is rich with cultural and historical heritage.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/caloocan',NULL,0,23,24,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:12:55','2012-09-12 06:12:00'),(46,NULL,1,'Cadiz City','cadiz',' \r\n            <h3>City of Whales</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cadizCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Cadiz City traces its beginning to a trading settlement in a place near the bank of a river called Hitalon. History tells that in 1861, the Spaniards came and named the settlement Cadiz because they were reminded of a seaport named Cadiz in Spain.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1878, Cadiz became a municipality. It became a city on July 4, 1967 with the approval of Republic Act 4998 on June 1967. The City of Cadiz is composed of 22 barangays, 11 coastal barangays including six in the poblacion while the rest are lo- cated upland. The urbanized area of the City is composed of 10 barangays.</p>\r\n            <p>Cadiz City is a coastal city in Northern Negros Occidental, 65 kilometers north of Bacolod City. Bounded to the north by the Visayas Sea and to the south by the Northern foothills; To the West by Silay City and Municipality of Manapla and to the East by the City of Sagay.</p>\r\n            <p>Cadiz is a one hour drive from Bacolod City, a 45 minute drive from the Bacolod-Silay airport and an hour and a half drive from San Carlos City.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Cadiz City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 150,750</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Third week of January is the best time to visit Cadiz. Cadiz is celebrating its week-long Dinagsa sa Cadiz Festival in honor of its Patron Saint, Santo Niño de Cadiz.</li>\r\n                <li>2. April and May. It is best months to go to Lakawon Island Resort and other beaches of Cadiz City.</li>\r\n                <li>3. December. It is best time to witness Pamaskwa Sa Cadiznon.</li>\r\n                <li>4. July 4. The best time to participate in the City’s charter day celebration.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cadizCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Cadiz City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit Lakawon Island Resort and other beaches in the City.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Buy the City’s famous dried fish and fishcharon delicacy (awarded as best delicacy 2011 in the Pana-ad sa Negros Festival) for pasalubong.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Commune with nature at Balay Alibangbang Farm Resort, Green Lagoon, and Little Jungle Resort.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Try the exotic Buriring</li>\r\n                <li>5. Go trekking at Pacol falls. Cadiz City hosts a number of waterfalls.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Tourism and Cultural Division, 2nd floor, New SGE Bldg., Cabahug Street, Cadiz City with telephone nos. (034) 493-1611. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"www.cadizcity.gov.ph\">www.cadizcity.gov.ph</a>.</p>\r\n','Cadiz City traces its beginning to a trading settlement in a place near the bank of a river called Hitalon.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/cadiz',NULL,0,17,18,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:07:34','2012-09-12 06:02:00'),(47,NULL,1,'Cagayan De Oro City','cagayan-de-oro','            <h3>City of Golden Friendship</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cagayanDeOroCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Cagayan de Oro City is the gateway to Northern Mindanao.</p>\r\n            <p>It is geographically nestled between the central coastline of Macajalar Bay to the North and the naturally-rich plateaus and mountains of Bukidnon and Lanao del Norte to the South. It is the largest city in Northern Mindanao.</p>\r\n            <p>The City’s history dates back many centuries before the Span- iards came to Cagayan when the territory was called Kalam- bagohan. Its main settlement site, Himologan, was a hill-top fortress situated some kilometers south of the present Poblacion.</p>\r\n            <p>When the first Spanish missionaries came in 1622, the people of Cagayan had tributary relation to Kudarat, the Muslim Sultan of Maguindanao empire in Cotabato. However, the people had not embraced Islam and instead, many became Christians. Because of this, Muslim warriors began to attack the settlement. As a de- fense strategy, the priests persuaded the people to transfer from the hilltop to a better location which is the present site of the Saint Augustine Cathedral. The Cagayanons were able to defend themselves from Muslim harassment for almost 250 years.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1738, Spanish dominance was felt in Cagayan. When Misamis gained status of province in 1818, one of its four districts was the Partidos de Cagayan.</p>\r\n            <p>In 1871, the “Partidos” became a town and was made perma- nent capital of Misamis. In 1883, the town became the seat of the Spanish government in Mindanao for the provinces of Misa- mis Oriental, Misamis Occidental, Bukidnon, Lanao del Norte.</p>\r\n            <p>The war years in Cagayan were prompted by the presence of the Americans in 1898. After the troubled years, peace finally brought back the economic activities to normal under the guid- ance of Americans. St. Augustine School, the forerunner of the present Xavier University and of Lourdes College, was inaugu- rated in 1928.</p>\r\n            <p>On June 15, 1950, President Elpidio Quirino signed Republic Act No. 521, which granted the status of a chartered city to the municipality of Cagayan de Misamis.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. The Kagay-an Festival (August) in honor of its patron Saint Augustine. Several activities are lined-up for the celebration.</li>\r\n                <li>2. White Water Rafting Adventure and Adventure Parks like zipline, zorbs and rapelling</li>\r\n                <li>3. City Museums (City Museum, Xavier University, Capitol Uni- versity and Liceo de Cagayan University)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cagayanDeOroCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Cagayan De Oro City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit some of the nature-based adventure sites like the Mapawa Nature Park. It is a vast property abundant with mag- nificent waterfalls, imposing views, and exciting activities nestled in the forest park in Cugman.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Explore the Monigue Cave. It has a small yet passable opening with six-inch airspace between ceiling and water thus, requiring one to submerge to enter or take a steel staircase from a small opening at the side of the cave.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Embrace century old trees and view the spectacular Macahambus Gorge below. Rappel down to the gorge or try our 120 meter zip line or slide for life.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Take a dip and marvel the sight of the F.S. Catanico Falls (Felix Solidad). The falls drop into natural swimming pool where bathers could dive from where the water descends. It has huge boulders that are covered with fern and moss.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Visit the Douglas Mc Arthur Marker. It is located at the side of the PPA building at the Port Area, Macabalan, Cagayan de Oro City.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Cagayan De Oro City</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Cagayan de Oro City is accessible by air for 1.5 hours serviced by Philippine Airlines, AirPhilippines, Cebu Pacific Air, SEAIR and Asian Spirit.</p>\r\n            <p>By sea with a travel time of one night and two days through Super Ferry, Trans Asia, Sulpicio Lines, Inc., Cebu Ferries, Negros Navigation and Gothong Southern.</p>\r\n            <p>By land through Rural Transit of Mindanao Inc., PHILTRAN- CO, Super 5 Transit and Tomawis Metro Shuttle.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit:</h4>\r\n            <p>Summer months (March to May)</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism and Cultural Affairs Office, Ground Floor, Tourism Hall, at telephone nos. (088) 857- 3164, (088) 857-5057 local 608.</p>\r\n','Cagayan de Oro City is the gateway to Northern Mindanao.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/cagayan-de-oro',NULL,0,19,20,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:07:09','2012-09-12 06:03:00'),(48,NULL,1,'Calamba City','calamba','             <h3>The Premiere City of Growth, of Leisure and of National Pride</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/calambaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>In Calamba, there is the Rizal Shrine, the ancestral home of the country’s national hero and the city’s greatest son, Dr. Jose Rizal. It serves as a museum of the family memorabilias. Adja- cent to it are the famous big earthen jar or banga symbolizing the origin of the town’s name and the equally historic St. John the Baptist Church where Rizal was baptized.</p>\r\n            <p>Just recently, Calamba is also home of the tallest Rizal Monu- ment in the world in honor of Rizal’s sesquicentennial birth anniversary.</p>\r\n            <p>Calamba is also dubbed as the Hot Spring Capital of the Philip- pines with 123 registered private pools and eight public resorts that provide recreation, stress relief and rejuvenation to both local and foreign tourists. It also hosts world-class golf courses for sports enthusiasts like the Canlubang Golf and Country Club and Ayala Greenfield Golf and Leisure Club.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is one of the gateways to Makiling Forest Reserve, a popular spot for hiking, bird watching, nature trekking, climbing and camping.</p>\r\n            <p>Aside from Rizal, Calamba produced four more national heroes: Rizal’s brother, Brig. Gen. Paciano Rizal and his mother Dona Teodora Alonzo; Gen. Vicente Lim, first Filipino to graduate from United States Military Academy at Westpoint; and Lt. Geronimo Aclan, an ace pilot who served with Col. Jesus Villamor in WWII.</p>\r\n            <p>It is also home to international sports champions like Ronnie Alcano in World Pool and Dottie Ardina in golf.</p>\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <p>Anytime of the year with the presence of hot and cold spring resorts and pools coupled with the rich history of the City.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destination and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Dr. Jose Rizal Shrine, St. John the Baptist Church and the giant clay pot (Banga) at Poblacion area and the Tall- est Rizal Monument at The Plaza in front of the City Hall Complex.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Hot spring public resorts and private pools which are located at barangays Bucal, Pansol, Bagong Kalsada, and Masile.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Baywalk and Wonder Island Resort located at an islet in the center of Laguna de Bay.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Cultural festivities include April 21 (Cityhood Anniver- sary), June 19 (Rizal’s Birth Anniversary), June 24 (Basaan Festival during St. John the Baptist), Feast Day (August 28, Foundation Day of Calamba), December 1-23 (Christmas Celebration with the Lighting of Giant Christmas Trees), and December 30 (Rizal’s Death Anniversary).</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/calambaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Calamba City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Tour the City’s historical sites like Dr. Jose Rizal Shrine and learn more about the country’s national hero.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Swim in any of the hot spring resorts and taste local foods like sinigang na kanduli sa miso, okoy and bulalo for a double treat.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Row your boat from Baywalk to Wonder Island Resort.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Play golf at the famous Canlubang Golf and Country Club and Greenfield Golf and Leisure Club located in Barangays Canlubang and Maunong respectively.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Visit to several garden stalls for different varieties of ornamental plants and to pasalubong centers that sell espasol and buko pie, the City’s most famous pasalubong treats.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Calamba</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 360,281</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>The City is 54 kilometers away from Manila. It can be reached via South Luzon Expressway approximately in an hour drive. It serves as the gateway to the provinces of Batangas, Quezon and the Bicol region. The City is serviced by various bus lines 24 hours a day. Modes of transporta- tion include jeepneys and tricycle plying route within the City and to and from nearby municipalities.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For more travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Cultural Affairs, Tourism and Sports Development Department, 3F Right Wing, City Hall Bldg., City of Calamba with telephone nos. (049) 545-6789 loc. 8221 or 8222.</p>\r\n','In Calamba, there is the Rizal Shrine, the ancestral home of the country’s national hero and the city’s greatest son, Dr. Jose Rizal.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/calamba',NULL,0,21,22,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:06:35','2012-09-12 06:04:00'),(49,NULL,1,'Cauayan City','cauayan','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Mushroom Basket of the North</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cauayanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Cauayan City has a lot to offer: good roads, abundant raw materials, skilled workers and above all, a business-friendly environment. The City is focused on the vision to become the Agro-Industrial Zone of the Region II. Improvements are con- tinuing. Infrastructures are being built for businesses to flourish. Being united in this purpose, The City is confident that the local economy will achieve its rapid growth.</p>\r\n            <p>The City has also one of the best equipped police force. The City has a best equipped 922 Rescue Team. The Police Office con- tinues to connect itself with the community. Public safety is a team effort that requires an open dialogue between the commu- nity and those who enforce the law.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Gawagaway-yan Festival - March 30 to April 13</li>\r\n                <li>2. Mushroom Center and Isabela Green Valley Orchidarium – Year-round</li>\r\n                <li>3. Lindon Fruit Farm- April to May</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cauayanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Cauayan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n\r\n            <li>1. Visit to Our Lady of the Pillars Church in Cauayan City and be awed by its modern interiors and preserved brick exteri- ors.</li>\r\n            <li>2. Prepare for a day of sightseeing, food trip and shopping starting at the mushrooms center in Barangay Tagaran where mushrooms can be bought straight from mushroom farms. Learn about its scientific production and the various by-prod- ucts produced from mushrooms.</li>\r\n            <li>3. Pick and pay your way at the Cortez and Lindon Fruit Farm for rambutan, mangoes, papaya, bananas and duhat and enjoy an al fresco lunch of freshly caught tilapia from Cortez fishpond and eat-all-you-can fresh fruits.</li>\r\n            <li>4. Visit the Dacuycuy Farms where imported ornamental plants and fruits abound and bring home aromatic and green dwarf Philippine coconut tree seedling. Learn the basics of giant freshwater prawn production at the region’s first prawn hatchery farm.</li>\r\n            <li>5. Celebrate with Cauayanos in the City’s Gawagaway-yan Festival, a celebration of the City’s bountiful harvest and merriment for the city’s ethno-linguistic groups from March 30 to April 13. The City produced the longest cassava roll measuring 1.250 kilometers last 2005. In time for the festive mood, stay either at the Hotel Andrea and Restaurant, Am- ity Hotel or Queen Jennifer Hotel and dine at Kusina Kawayan, Kubo Kubo sa Kawayan and Otso Rios Restaurant which are all located at the City proper.</li>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Cauayan</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, the City is 375 kilometers northeast with ap- proximately eight hours travel time by land and 45 minutes travel by plane.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            March 30 to April 13 for the Gawagaway-yan Festival.\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Contact the Office of the City Mayor Tourism Division at telephone nos. (078) 652-2017 or email at cityofcauayani- sabela@yahoo.com+</p>\r\n','Cauayan City has a lot to offer: good roads, abundant raw materials, skilled workers and above all, a business-friendly environment.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/cauayan',NULL,0,25,26,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:14:03','2012-09-12 06:13:00'),(50,NULL,1,'Cavite City','cavite','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Historic and Cultural City By The Bay</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/caviteCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Cavite City today is a melting pot of various cultures, a City that has evolved its own distinct brand of culture showing the resilience and adaptability of its inhabitants. It is a City with a rich heritage.</p>\r\n            <p>Because of its strategic location for trade and military opera- tions, Cavite City has always felt foreign influences throughout the centuries. For one, inevitability the influence of Spain is deeply embedded in the City’s language – The Chabacano, a mixture of Spanish and Tagalog words, with its own syntactic structure.</p>\r\n            <p>Caviteños of the present generation visualize the city as the New Gateway for Trade, Commerce, and Industry, imbued with God-loving, culturally-oriented and responsible people, living in a highly developed community with a balanced ecology geared towards a more vibrant economy governed by a strong and transparent leadership.</p>\r\n            <p>Cavite City is a hook-shaped peninsula bounded by three bays - Manila Bay, Cañacao Bay, and Bacoor Bay located at the Northern tip of Cavite province. It is approximately 34 kilome- ters southwest of Manila.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Corregidor island (anytime of the year) – Corregidor has always been associated with bravery, gallantry and heroism. And it seems so appropriate that it is part of Cavite City, known for its gallant and brave heroes. The whole island is declared a Na- tional Shrine. There are several memorials in the island. There is\r\n                    a museum at the Pacific War Memorial Complex and an inspiring Eternal Flame of Freedom Sculpture. The highlight of a Corregi- dor tour is the light and sound show at the Malinta Tunnel.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Fort San Felipe (anytime of the year) – Located at the compound of the Philippine Navy, this 16th century fort is dedicated to San Felipe Neri. This is the place where the Cavite Mutiny 1872 occurred when Filipino workers were implicated in the armed uprising against the Spaniards. This is also the place where the 13 Martyrs of Cavite were executed.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Regada Festival (June 22-24 ) - Cavite City’s party-loving people have successfully combined their love for water and celebrations through the Regada, derived from the Spanish word “regar” which means to water, to sprinkle or to irrigate. Regada is held every year in June, a three-day long celebration of water sports, bays clean-up drive, among others to give importance as the City is endeared to water and the sea. A unique feature of the festival is the Paulan where the commercial area of the city is rigged with pipes to simulate rain.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Cavite City Fiesta (second or third week of November) - Caviteños by tradition are very religious people. A fiesta princi- pal is celebrated on the second Sunday of November for the de afuera (literally “outsiders”) or guests and on the third Sunday for families. The fiesta is being celebrated even by the Aglipayan religious sect, thus the icon of Our Lady of Solitude can be seen in the entire City’s Aglipayan Churches.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Navidad (December 16 to 25) – The City’s Christmas season is filled with fun and Spirit with weekly activities to feature.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/caviteCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Cavite City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <p>Take the Ciudad de Cavite tour package which explores the city’s most prized histo-cultural heritages like</p>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Fort San Felipe</li>\r\n                <li>2. 15th Strike Wing Aircraft Display</li>\r\n                <li>3. Cavite City Zoological & Botanical Park</li>\r\n                <li>4. Samala Pasalubong</li>\r\n                <li>5. Chefoo Restaurant/ Asiong Carinderia/ Asao (Filipino Chinese Cuisine)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Cavite</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 108, 715</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Cavite City is accessible with only an estimated one hour travel time.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <p>June, November, and December. Most of the major cul- tural activities of the city are within these months.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Mayor’s Office, Cavite City Hall, Samonte Park, Cavite City at telephone nos. (046) 431-0462 or (046) 431-1655 or the Cavite City Tourism Office, Samonte Park, Cavite City at (046) 431-8514 .</p>\r\n','Cavite City today is a melting pot of various cultures, a City that has evolved its own distinct brand of culture showing the resilience and adaptability of its inhabitants.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/cavite',NULL,0,27,28,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:15:04','2012-09-12 06:14:00'),(51,NULL,1,'Dagupan City','dagupan','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Bangus Capital of the Philippines</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/dagupanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>After years of aggressive self-advertisement that has billed Dagupan as the emerging metropolis and center of trade and commerce of the North, it turns out that Dagupeños are actually a bit shy about characterizing their city.</p>\r\n            <p>In less than four centuries, the City has grown from an obscure river delta and fishing village - where the great Pangasinan rebel chieftain Andres Malong assembled his forces for a last stand against the Spanish troops in this place also referred as ‘Nanda- ragupan’ which means “meeting place” or “rallying point”- to a bustling city of about 150,000 inhabitants, ballooning to some half a million during regular days, bolstered by transients do- ing business here, and students who commute daily from their respective towns and other cities.</p>\r\n            <p>If Northern Luzon were a nation, Dagupan would be its capital. Some residents claim it as a quintessential Pangasinan – the epitome of industry and hard-driving determination.</p>\r\n            <p>Dagupan City has a total land area of 44.47 square kilometers, politically subdivided into 31 barangays. About one-fourth of this area consists of bodies of water, such as rivers, lakes, creeks, and fishponds. It lies at the middle of the northern coastline of Pangasinan province overlooking the Gulf of Lingayen.</p>\r\n            <p>Amidst the destructive effects of the 1990 earthquake, Dagupan City managed to developed a booming economy</p>\r\n            <p>In addition to being a major trading and commercial center, the City has an ample concentration of banking and financing in- stitutions and substantial number of good schools, colleges and universities, hospitals, clinics, and other health centers, many of them are equipped with the latest state-of-the-art instruments and gadgets.</p>\r\n            <p>The city officials and department heads have envisioned Da- gupan City as the premiere center of the North for education, information technology, health, commerce and trade, and aqua- culture, with God loving, well-informed, healthy, self-reliant, em- powered and vigilant citizenry who live in a balanced, planned, attractive and safe environment and a globally-competitive, di- versified and environment-friendly economy under a firm, decent and progressive leadership.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1.Bangus Festival (April 15-May 1)</li>\r\n                <li>2.Dawel River Cruise</li>\r\n                <li>3.Bonuan Tondaligan Blue Beach</li>\r\n                <li>4.Magsaysay Fish Market</li>\r\n                <li>5.Museum</li>\r\n                <li>6.Gabaldon Building</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/dagupanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Dagupan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. River Cruise</li>\r\n                <li>2. Museo ng Dagupan/ Dagupan City Plaza</li>\r\n                <li>3. St. John Cathedral</li>\r\n                <li>4. Tondaligan Beach Park</li>\r\n                <li>5. Matutina’s Restaurant</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Dagupan City</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 158,334</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>The City is about 212 kilometers away north of Manila. Travel time is four to five hours by land.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>April 15 - May 1 for the Bangus Festival. It is the time where Dagupeños showcase the city’s culture, arts and heritage.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact Dagupan City Tourism Office with telephone nos. (075) 515-6196 or visit the City’s website at <a href=\"www.dagupan.gov.ph\">www.dagupan.gov.ph</a>.</p>\r\n','After years of aggressive self-advertisement that has billed Dagupan as the emerging metropolis and center of trade and commerce',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/dagupan',NULL,0,29,30,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:16:11','2012-09-12 06:15:00'),(52,NULL,1,'Davao City','davao','\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/davaoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Davao City is among the largest cities in the world with a sprawl- ing land area of 244,000 hectares. It is situated at the southern part of the country.</p>\r\n            <p>Davao City aims to become a major growth pole in the inter- national market by engaging the empowered and participative citizenry in resource-based and market-driven economic activi- ties within the context of balanced ecology, sustainable growth and equity-led development.</p>\r\n            <p>Davao City also aims to be the growth center in Mindanao. Davao City shall be developed as the service, financial, tour-\r\n                ism destination, and education center in Mindanao. The City is envisioned as the Premier Socio-economic and Tourism Center in Mindanao, East Asean Growth Area (EAGA) and the Asia-Pacific Region</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Davao</p>\r\n            <p>City Population: 1,464,301 (as of 2010)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Davao City offers a wide bus network to major cities and prov- inces, not only in Mindanao but even as far as Manila and Pasay City in Luzon. Davao City is connected to Manila by a series of roll on roll off or inter-island ferry connection.</p>\r\n            <p>Davao City is accessible by bus to and from points in Mindanao. The city is also served by domestic passenger ferries at Sasa Port and Sta. Ana Wharf.</p>\r\n            <p>Access to Davao City is never a problem with its almost 20 daily flights to the nation’s capital of Manila.</p>\r\n            <p>Davao City has direct flights to major cities in the Philippines and some Asian Cities. The Francisco Bangoy International Airport (Davao International Airport) is currently being served by the following airline carriers: Airphil Express that flies to Manila and Cebu three times daily, Iloilo once daily and Cagayan de Oro, once daily; Cebu Pacific with four flights weekly to Cagayan de Oro, 24 weekly flights to Cebu City, once daily flight to Iloilo City, 45 weekly flights to Manila, and once daily flight to Zam- boanga City; Philippine Airlines with four daily flights to Manila; SilkAir with five flights weekly to Singapore. Zest Airways two daily flights to Manila; Tiger Airways will launch a three times weekly flight to Singapore</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/davaoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Davao City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the Philippine Eagle Center, home of the Philippine Eagle (one of the largest eagles in the world). The nature center is primarily a breeding facility for the eagles and habitat to different animals endemic to the region.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Journey into the Eden Nature Park, the heart of tribal Mindanao. Due to its elevation, the climate in the Park is compa- rable to cooler cities like Baguio and Tagaytay. Visitors can look forward to a healthy array of dishes such as salads and organic vegetables.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Pick an orchid at the Malagos Garden, home to diverse varieties of ornamental flora and orchids, like the famed Wal- ing- waling. Visit the Crocodile Park, the home of the largest crocodile in the country. At the Crocodile Park, one may as well try crocodile sisig and crocodile ice cream</li>\r\n                <li>4. Play in world-class golf courses like the Apo Golf and Country Club, Davao City Golf Club, or Rancho Palos Verdes. Or try the Deca Wakeboard Park Facility, the first cable wakeboarding in Mindanao</li>\r\n                <li>5. Tour the City proper and make stopovers at the Museo Dabawenyo (Pichon St.), the People’s Park (Camus St.), San Pedro Cathedral, City Hall and City Council (San Pedro St.), Magsaysay Park (Magsaysay Avenue), T’Boli Weaving Center (Lanang), Davao Museum (Insular Village) and Bankerohan Public Market (Bankerohan). Sip Durian coffee (Blugre Café and Yellow Fin) and munch durian sweets (Lola Abon’s Durian Delicacies) in between.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. The third week of August because of the Kadayawan Fes- tival. The Kadayawan is the City’s annual festival in celebra- tion of the City’s bountiful harvest and in recognition of the ten tribes of Davao City.</li>\r\n                <li>2. May - For the Davao Summerfest</li>\r\n                <li>3. December – For the Pasko Fiesta. It is celebrated during the entire month of December. The City pulsates with excit- ing sights and sounds, barraged with mall sales, bazaars, food festivals, and night markets filled with wholesome entertainment day and night.</li>\r\n                <li>4. March 16 – For the Araw ng Dabaw, a celebration of the Dabawenyos’ oneness.</li>\r\n                <li>5. February – For the Davao Chinese New Year Festival. It celebrates the harmonious relations of the locals with the City’s Chinese community as it promotes the development of Chinatown as one of the major historical, economic and cultural centers of the City.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Operations Office, Davao City, Door 8, Magsaysay Park Complex, R. Magsaysay Avenue, Davao City with telephone nos. (082) 222-1956 to 57. Email them at info@davaotourism.com. Visit website at <a href=\"www.davaotourism.com\">www.davaotourism.com</a>, <a ref=\"www.davaocity.gov.ph\">www.davaocity.gov.ph</a>.</p>\r\n','Davao City is among the largest cities in the world with a sprawl- ing land area of 244,000 hectares. It is situated at the southern',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/davao',NULL,0,31,32,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:17:03','2012-09-12 06:16:00'),(53,NULL,1,'Digos City','digos','\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/digosCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>In the early days, Digos was a watercourse that served as a meeting place of the inhabitants belonging to the Indonesian Malay tribes who settled along the southern foothills of Mt. Apo. During the Spanish era, a group of natives carrying bows and ar- rows were approached by Spaniards traversing the fertile tracks of land in Davao and inquired about the name of the place. Believing that the Spaniards were asking where they were bound to, the natives answered, padigos which means to take a bath. Since then, the place was identified as Digos.</p>\r\n            <p>For many years, Digos has been the center of trade, commerce and education owing to its strategic location at the crossroad of two provincial thoroughfares in the South of Mindanao.</p>\r\n            <p>The Vision of Digos City is to be a socially and economically developed City, responsive to differentiated gender roles and needs of women and men, characterized by political maturity and social harmony in a healthy and sustainable environment and gender fair society and with an overall Mission that is to promote the welfare and interest of the people of Digos and to ensure that everyone shares the benefits of development.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Mt. Apo Summer Climb. City government employees spear- head this activity.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Pista Kadig’garan, a Bagobo term which means the Feast of Goodness. It is a festival celebrating the bountiful harvest and good weather. It is being celebrated during the Araw ng Digos (September 08).</li>\r\n                <li>3. Dorong Festival – It is a thanksgiving feast for the Bagobos being celebrated every June 14-19 at Barangay Kapatagan.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/digosCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Digos City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Conquer Mt. Apo, the country’s highest peak, by using the Digos Kapatagan Trail. It is an experience which an adven- turous individual must do when in Digos City.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Experience extreme adventure when one visits Camp Sabros at Sitio Baras in Barangay Kapatagan. The camp provides one of the longest zipline in the country traversing along top of pine trees with the majestic Mt. Apo looming on site.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit the Agong House. A remarkable work of art designed by renowned sculptor, art photographer, painter and perfor- mance artist Kublai Millan. Located in Sitio Baras, Kapatagan, the place is surrounded with gigantic sculptors which will amaze guests from different parts of the country.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Taste the Mers Bibingka, which has been featured in one of the country’s leading newspaper as one of the best bib`ingka in the country. You may also dine and try other delicacies at Mers Kichenette in Barangay Badiang.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Witness traditional pottery at work in Barangay Matti which has been known for its terracotta products.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Digos</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 145,514 (2007 census)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, the Davao City International Airport and the Sasa Port in Davao City serve as the nearest entry point to Digos City. From Davao City, Digos is 56 kilometers. It can be reached by land within one to two hours.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>September 08 – For the annual celebration of Araw ng Digos</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office, Rizal Park, Digos City at (082)-272-12-82.</p>\r\n','In the early days, Digos was a watercourse that served as a meeting place of the inhabitants belonging to the Indonesian Malay tribes',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/digos',NULL,0,33,34,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:18:07','2012-09-12 06:17:00'),(54,NULL,1,'Dipolog City','dipolog','\r\n            <h3>Gateway to Western Mindanao</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/dipologCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Dipolog City is the Capital City of Zamboanga del Norte and the center of trade in the peninsula. It has gained worldwide prominence through its bottled sardines which has become one of the major industries City’s major industries.\r\n                A popular eco-tourism destination, Dipolog’s main attractions are the Cogon Eco-Park, a 350-hectare forest, which is 30 minutes away from the City center, the Sungkilaw Falls, and the Linabo peak which commands a breathtaking view of the Dapitan and Dipolog Cities. Sports fishing and scuba diving are also fast becoming the popular reason to visit Dipolog.</p>\r\n\r\n            <p>Meanwhile, the City’s rich history and culture trace its roots to the Subanen and later the influx of migrants from Spain, China, Bohol, Cebu and other Mindanao provinces giving inspiration to the P’gsalabuk Festival, Dipolog’s most colorful annual festival.\r\n                The progress of Dipolog has accelerated in recent years giving way to newly opened roads and modern buildings, more commercial banks and business establishments including hotels and restaurants. The blueprint for the city’s development plan has been laid out after a series of participatory planning workshops. Dipolog is visioning itself as A God-centered, Peaceful and Self- Reliant Supercity by the year 2030.\r\n                Best time to visit</p>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. All year round. Since Dipolog is not within the typhoon belt, it is best to visit the place anytime of the year. However, from June to October, tropical fruits like durian, lanzones, marang, rambu- tan, and mangoes are abundant.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Summertime (March to June) is the best time to enjoy the beaches and the mountain resorts. Dipolog also celebrates its fiesta every last Saturday of May and on October 7.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Major destination and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Cogon Eco-Park and Sungkilaw Falls</li>\r\n                <li>2. Linabo Peak and 3,003 Steps</li>\r\n                <li>3. Dipolog City Boulevard</li>\r\n                <li>4. Sports Fishing and Scuba Diving</li>\r\n                <li>5. P’gsalabuk Festival (April up to 3rd Saturday of May)</li>\r\n                <li>6. Dahunog Festival (September- October 7)</li>\r\n                <li>7. Pasko sa Dipolog (November – January 02)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/dipologCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Dipolog City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Go jogging and walking at the break of dawn or sunset time in the Boulevard</li>\r\n                <li>2. Eat at the Food Court in the Boulevard or fresh seafoods available daily at the fish port and the public mar- ket. Go sports fishing and feast on your fresh catch.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Buy souvenir items like the bottled sardines, nito hand woven products and fruits from the different pasalu- bong centers in the city.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Visit the Cathedral, the P’gsalabuk circle, Sports Complex, City hall and other places that eloquently speak of the city’s rich historical and cultural heritage. Take time to join the river cruise along the scenic Dipolog river and savor the excellent buffet.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Get yourself invited to one of the meetings of the Multi-sectoral Governance Coalition (MSGC) and experience a vibrant and active partnership between the local governments and the private sector in crafting the City’s plans and programs.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Dipolog City Population: 110,000</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Dipolog City is in northern Mindanao. It is accessible by land, sea, and air from any point in the Philippines. It is barely an hour and fifteen minutes by plane from Manila and 30 minutes by plane from Cebu. There are daily flights from Dipolog to Manila and thrice weekly to Cebu.\r\n                There are several trips by boat every day to Dumaguete, Cebu and Bohol. Rural Transit travels to Zamboanga City and other cities in Mindanao every hour daily.</p>\r\n            <h4>For more travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office, Second Floor, City Hall, Dipolog City with telephone nos. (065) 212-2485.</p>\r\n','Dipolog City is the Capital City of Zamboanga del Norte and the center of trade in the peninsula. It has gained worldwide',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/dipolog',NULL,0,35,36,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:19:03','2012-09-12 06:18:00'),(55,NULL,1,'Gapan City','gapan','\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/gapanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Gapan City is a fourth class component city in the southern part of Nueva Ecija province. It became a city through Republic Act 9022 which was approved in a plebiscite on August 25, 2001.</p>\r\n            <p>Gapan City is the oldest town in Nueva Ecija and one of the oldest in the country. It was founded in 1595 as a pueblo by three Spanish friars.\r\n                Aside from a dynamic agricultural sector, the local footwear industry is a major economic driver for the City. Gapan has been dubbed as the “Footwear Capital of the North” because of the numerous footwear producers operating in the villages of San Lorenzo and Mangino. There are also a number of footwear sup- pliers operating along Tinio Street. Both the footwear producers and suppliers provide employment to hundreds of city residents.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>1. May 1 is the best time to go to Gapan City. It is the Feast of La Virgen Divina Pastora. Residents and visitors go to Gapan City to pray to the La Virgen Divina Pastora at the Three Kings Parish Church. A parade or “paseo” is also held yearly on April 30, known as the bisperas.</p>\r\n            <p>A colorful fireworks are also displayed in the early evening of April 30. Another big event is the City’s Agri-Trade Fair which is slated one week before Feast.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/gapanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h3>Gapan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the Three Kings Parish Church and offer a prayer to La Virgen Divina Pastora.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Buy Gapan-made footwear products, meat products, fruits and vegetables (mango, watermelon, and egg- plant among others) during the agri-trade fair or at the public market.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Dine at Luz Kitchenette, Patio de Lis or Bayanihan Resto Grill which offer native dishes.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Buy delicacies like pastillas which are located along the Maharlika highway or palutik (pork skin) at the public market.</li>\r\n                <li>5. If one wants to shop and eat fast, Walter Mart along the Maharlika highway can easily be reached.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Gapan City Population: 98,795 (2007)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, one can just ride a bus (like Baliwag, Five Star or ES) which will pass through Bulacan. Right after the town of San Miguel, Bulacan is Gapan City.</p>\r\n            <p>From those coming from Pampanga, Bataan, and Zambales provinces, one can travel via Gapan-Olongapo road and can arrive in the City after passing the town of San Isidro, Nueva Ecija. Visitors coming from Cabanatuan and from the northern part may use the Maharlika highway and will reach Gapan after passing the town of San Leonardo, Nueva Ecija.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Contact the City Administrator’s Office at telephone nos. (044) 486-5502.</p>\r\n','Gapan City is a fourth class component city in the southern part of Nueva Ecija province. It became a city through Republic Act 9022',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/gapan',NULL,0,37,38,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:19:51','2012-09-12 06:19:00'),(56,NULL,1,'Iligan City','iligan','\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of Majestic Waterfalls</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/iliganCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Chroniclers say that centuries ago, before Legaspi’s expedition reached the Philippines in 1565, the Tala-andigs and the Banwahons, two peace-loving Higa-onon tribes of Mindanao, had to build an ilihan or iliyan, meaning a “fortress of defense” on the coastal plain to secure them from the frequent attacks of pirates and savage tribes. Hence, the place came to be called as Iligan.</p>\r\n            <p>Iligan City is bounded by the provinces of Bukidnon, Misamis Oriental, and the two provinces of Lanao. It has a total land area of 81,337 hectares with 44 barangays with a projected population of 308,046. Its climate is characterized by short, dry season for one to three months. Rainfalls are evenly distributed throughout the year. It is located outside the typhoon belt. Iligan was chartered as a City upon the approval and signing of Republic Act No. 525 “Charter of the New City of Iligan” on June 16, 1950.</p>\r\n            <p>Iligan is the City of Majestic Waterfalls. As of the latest count, it boasts of 23 waterfalls dispersed in the City’s 44 barangays. The most famous is the Maria Cristina Falls which is also being har- nessed by the National Power Corporation – Mindanao Generation. The Maria Christina Falls provides electricity to the City and the rest of Mindanao.</p>\r\n            <p>Not only known for its rich natural resources, but the City is also home for nationally acclaimed artists, poets, film makers, cultural workers and writers. Geographically, The City is a cultural blend of the Maranaos of Lanao del Sur, Higa-onons of Bukid- non, and the Christian settlers and migrants from Luzon, Visayas and other places of Mindanao.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. May 28 (during the National Flag Day), June 12 (for the In- dependence Day) and June 16 for the Charter Day Celebration. This is also known as the City’s Grand Triple Day Celebrations.</li>\r\n                <li>2. September first week until the 29th is the City’s Diyandi Festival Sa Iligan. It is being celebrated as a folklore depicting the City’s patron saint, St. Michael, as the protector of peace.</li>\r\n                <li>3. December – During Christmas Season, the City is bustling with many activities.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/iliganCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Iligan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit Maria Cristina Falls, Mimbalot Falls, and Tinago Falls. Drop by the Macaraeg-Macapagal Ancestral House. </li>\r\n                <li>2. Swim at Timoga Swimming Pool.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Eat a City’s variant of Lechon and Buy Cheding’s Peanuts and Suka Pinakurat.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Visit the Iligan City Hall and the Anahaw Amphitheater.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Climb Mt. Agad-agad for a grand view of the city especially at night.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Iligan Population: 308,046</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, the fastest and most convenient to Iligan City is to take a flight to Cagayan de Oro City, approximately one hour and 20 minutes travel time. From Cebu City, also take a flight to Cagayan De Oro City, approximately for 20 minutes travel time.</p>\r\n            <p>From Cagayan de Oro, take either bus, a taxi or rent a car and travel 89 kilometers to Iligan City. Meanwhile, the City’s public seaport serves passenger ships taking the Iligan-Cebu and Iligan-Manila routes.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact Iligan City Tourism Office with telephone nos. (063) 221-3426 c/o Bahay Salakot, Buhanginan Hill, Brgy. Pala, Iligan City. Visit the City website at <a href=\"http://www.iligan.gov.ph\" >www.iligan.gov.ph</a> or at <a href=\"http://iligancitytourism.yolasite.com\">http://iligancitytourism.yolasite.com.</a> Email queries at iligancitytourism@yahoo.com.</p>\r\n','Chroniclers say that centuries ago, before Legaspi’s expedition reached the Philippines in 1565, the Tala-andigs and the Banwahons',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/iligan',NULL,0,39,40,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:20:41','2012-09-12 06:20:00'),(57,NULL,1,'Iloilo City','iloilo','\r\n            <h3>City of Love, My City, My Pride</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/iloiloCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The name Iloilo was derived from the Hiligaynon word Ilong- Ilong meaning ‘noselike’ that specifically referred to an islet in the Batiano River.\r\n                Iloilio has an old city charm. It became a city in 1893 under the Spanish Law, then reverted to municipality status in 1898 under the American Regime and became a chartered city again in 1937. It was declared a Highly Urbanized City in 1981.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is presently inhabited with an estimated half a million residents living in its six major districts - the City Proper, Jaro, Molo, Mandurriao, Arevalo, and La Paz. Among the City’s festivals, the grandest celebration ans the most famous is the Dinagyang, which falls every 4th Sunday of January. It is the celebration commemorating the arrival of the image of the Child Jesus as welcomed by the Aetas hundreds of years ago.</p>\r\n            <p>In terms of tourism, Iloilo City is developing the culinary attractions of the six districts: La Paz Batchoy has already gained a national fame. Pancit Molo is also known around the country as a variant of a noodle soup; Jaro is proud of its delicacies like the biscocho, butterscotch, banana pinasugbo; Mandurriao would underscore the unique taste of its Cansi; Arevalo’s seafood is sumptuous with Tatoy’s and Breakthrough as the popular food trip destination; the City, of course is proud to promote grilled chicken. Foods take the stomach as a way to win the hearts and minds of those who come to visit Iloilo. Iloilo foods taste better because ultimately, Ilonggos are hospitable warm good-natured people</p>\r\n            <p>The investment potentials of the city are in agribusiness: agri- based and aqua-based food processing; delicacies-making, furniture, gifts, toys and house wares and garments. In the area of trade and services: IT and IT enabled services, retail and wholesale trading, restaurants and eateries; in tourism-related investments; culinary attractions and themed tourism facilities and amenities. There is room for convention center, IT parks and buildings and housing subdivision projects.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is also known for its competitiveness - high profitability of business, low labor cost, high growth of registered businesses, availability of good information technology training, presence of private and public sector organized training programs, good administration of justice, transparent local government, effective leadership of the local chief executive, and appropriate security environment for businesses.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/iloiloCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Iloilo City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Explore the City’s culture and heritage through a half- or one-day city tour. This includes the Museo Iloilo, Fort San Pedro, antique hunting, campus tours, and pasalubong shopping</li>\r\n                <li>2. Visit La Paz district for a taste of authentic La Paz Batchoy or Molo district for the original Pancit Molo. Seafood cuisine is also famous in the Arevalo Beach area where one can dine by the shore</li>\r\n                <li>3. Also in the Arevalo district, See how women weavers daintily operate Spanish era looms to make delicate jusi, piňa, and hablon fabrics of delicate designs. Buy finished products at Sinamay Dealer near Arevalo Plaza</li>\r\n                <li>4. Capture the aura of the old Iloilo through its opulent churches like in Molo (St. Anne’s Parish) and Jaro (St. Elizabeth Metropolitan Cathedral)</li>\r\n                <li>5. Participate in the City’s grand festivities like the Dinagyang Festival, Paraw Regatta Festival, which is the Asia’s oldest native boat sailing event, the Chinese New Year, and the Feast of our Lady of the Candles, which is the grandest religious festival in the Western Visayas.</li></ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Iloilo</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 420,002 (2007 NSO Census)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>By Sea: Ship – 18 hours.</p>\r\n            <p>By Air: Airplane via Iloilo Airport – 50 minutes. From airport (Santa Barbara or Cabatuan) to Iloilo City: 20 minutes</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major cultural and tourism destinations</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Dinagyang Festival – every fourth Sunday of January</li>\r\n                <li>2. Paraw Regatta Festival – every third weekend of February</li>\r\n                <li>3. City Charter Anniversary Celebration – from 16th July to 25th August every year</li>\r\n                <li>4. Iloilo Churches- St. Elizabeth Cathedral (Jaro) and St. Anne Church (Molo)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Iloilo City Tourism and Development Office</p>\r\n            <p>Iloilo Freedom Grandstand, JM Basa St., Iloilo City with telephone nos. (033) 336-3439 and/ or (033) 337-2172</p>\r\n            <p>Western Visayas (Region VI), 283 statute miles from Manila From Manila: By Land: Roll-On, Roll-Off – 16 hours.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <p>November to May</p>\r\n','The name Iloilo was derived from the Hiligaynon word Ilong- Ilong meaning ‘noselike’ that specifically referred to an islet in the Batiano River.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/iloilo',NULL,0,41,42,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:21:27','2012-09-12 06:20:00'),(58,NULL,1,'Iriga City','iriga','\r\n            <h3>City of Crystal Clear Springs</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/irigaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Iriga City is the economic, educational and cultural center of the 5th District of Camarines Sur. Its most prominent natural landmark, Mt. Asog, with its volcanic soil, made it one of the biggest abaca producing areas in Bicol during the Spanish and American occupation. During pre-colonial times, the mountain was the center of a first-harvest offering ritual, celebrated today as the Tinagba festival.</p>\r\n            <p>Iriga is also the birthplace of the country’s first bus transporta- tion company, the ALATCO, which along with the three schools established in the post-war years, propelled the progress of the town. In 1968, Iriga was converted into a component city.</p>\r\n            <p>Iriga City is a dynamic and progressive city. It has posted an average of 11.3% annual growth over the last seven years. Its advocacy on good governance earned it the 2009 Excellence in Good Governance Award from the Department of Interior and Local Government - Region V and a citation as one of the Top 10 Performing local governments in the country in 2010.</p>\r\n            <p>Iriga City envisions a vibrant economy and a contented life for every Irigueno through a transparent local government unit, a strong agroecotourism backbone and a people with a deep sense of pride, identity, shared values and character.</p>\r\n            <p>The City is also called the City of Crystal Clear Springs, boasting with more than 30 natural springs that provide a rich source of drinking and irrigation waters. The City is located at the heart of Bicol Economic Growth Corridor. It is also known as the Character City with its warm and friendly, honest and industrious inhabitants.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. February 11 in time for the Tinagba Festival as it lures the visitor to a cultural experience which is the reenactment of an old pagan ritual of offering and thanksgiving. The whole day merrymaking includes a day parade of colored bull carts that are laden with the best products of the farm followed by revelers in colored costumes in a street dance around the city.</li>\r\n                <li>2. June 13 is the City Fiesta in honor of its patron, St. Anthony of Padua. It is highlighted with the coronation of Ms. Iriga, Ms. Rinconada and Ms. Bicol Tourism.</li>\r\n                <li>3. September 3 is the City’s foundation anniversary with a grand military parade whose participation and competition is open to all not limited only to the two big universities and col- leges and all other schools in the City but also to the neighbor- ing academic institutions in the neighboring municipalities. The Sumagang Awards, the highest civilian award is being conferred to outstanding Irigueños during the City’s foundation day.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/irigaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Iriga City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Climb any of the following: The over-100 step Grotto of Our Lady of Lourdes built atop the Calvario Hill that faces Mount Iriga offering a bird’s eye view of the City’s central business district; Mount Iriga which rises some 4,823 feet above sea level. Its climb is challenging. Its cold surrounding makes a fitting habitat for wild berries and local specie of pine calleda agoho; and the Inorogan Shrine, on top of a hill at Barangay Sto. Domingo. The Pieta shrine was built to commemorate the miraculous escape from death and destruction of the inhabitants from the eruption of Mount Iriga in the 30s.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Taste Iriga’s delicacies. Gulay na katnga (laing), tinutktok, pili nut candies, santan, and the special Iriga Bicol express. These products are available at the Katnga Center located at the ground floor of the old City Hall. Native products and souvenir items are sold at the Pasalubong Center at the ground floor of the Iriga Public Market. Dine also at Mariolis, Desny Grill, Mayees All Chinese Restaurant. MCM Restaurant, Biggs Diner, and Crown Park Restaurant.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit the Gawad Kalinga Character Village located at Barangay Perpetual Help. Its 140 beautiful and multi-colored houses which make up a sustainable community development project of Iriga City government and the GK Community Development Foundation is a major tourist attraction.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Visit the Iriga Government Center, a modern edifice that is fully air-conditioned. Painted in Mediterranean-inspired col- ors, it brings together all the important offices in one central location to facilitate the processing of documents and other transactions. Visit also the New Iriga Public Library which is fully air conditioned and operates daily from 8:00 am to 8:00 pm except Sunday. A Nora Aunor corner is a major interest to many. Visit and shop at the Iriga Public Market, the cleanest in the region where you can find fast food chains, native products and food and just everything that suits your fancy.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Watch the Tinagba Festival on February 11 and enjoy the parade of bullcarts laden with fresh farm products and the streetdancing of revelers in their beautiful costumes. Watch the Coronation Night of Ms Iriga/Ms Rinconada/Ms Bicol Tourism. During your free time side – trip and enjoy a dip at Masuso, Crystal, Cascade and Fountain Spring Resorts.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Iriga City Population: 97,983 (NSO 2007)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Iriga is strategically located between Naga City in the north and Legazpi City in the south. From Manila to Naga Airport, it is a 55-minute travel and from Naga Airport to Iriga, it is a 30-minute ride by car. If you are landing at the Legazpi Airport which is an hour’s flight from Manila, Iriga is a 50-minute travel by car.</p>\r\n            <p>Major air-conditioned bus companies ply the Manila-Bicol Route via Maharlika Highway which is an eight-hour ride. Terminals are located at the Ali-Mall Cubao, Pasay City and Pedro Gil Street, Manila. The Philippine National Railways (PNR) now travels daily the Manila – Bicol route and vice – versa.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the New Government Center, Sta. Cruz Sur, Iriga City with telephone nos. (054) 299-1989 or (054) 299-1953 or email at mag-irigacity@yahoo.com and/or irigatourism@yahoo.com.ph. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"http://www.iriga.gov.ph\" >www.iriga.gov.ph</a> for more queries</p>\r\n','Iriga City is the economic, educational and cultural center of the 5th District of Camarines Sur. Its most prominent natural landmark',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/iriga',NULL,0,43,44,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:23:58','2012-09-12 06:23:00'),(59,NULL,1,'Isabela City','isabela','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Promising City of the South</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/isabelaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Isabela City is the commercial center and capital of the island province of Basilan. The City is located in the northern part of Basilan.</p>\r\n            <p>In the ancient times, Basilan island was called Taguima while Isabela was referred by its ethnic groups (the Yakans, Samal Bangingih, Badjaos, and Tausogs) as Pasangan which the names still hold among the natives. In 1844, the Spaniards occupied Pasangan and in July next year, it was named Isabela, in honor of Queen Isabel II of Spain.</p>\r\n            <p>During the Spanish regime and the American occupation, Basilan was part of a big Zamboanga province, which also included the provinces of Zamboanga del Sur and Zamboanga del Norte. In 1937, the City of Zamboanga brought into existence and made Basilan part of the newly created City.</p>\r\n            <p>On July 1, 1948 with Republic Act No. 288, Basilan island be- came a chartered city, separating it from City of Zamboanga, with three districts, namely – Isabela, Lamitan, and Maluso. Mayor Nicasio Valderoza was the first appointed city mayor who served until December 31, 1953.</p>\r\n            <p>On December 27, 1973, then President Ferdinand E. Marcos issued Presidential Decree No. 356 creating Basilan Province - Basilan as an island province with three municipalities: Lamitan, Maluso and Isabela, the latter being its capital.</p>\r\n            <p>On January 1, 1976, Ricardo G. Mon, then the top councilors of the defunct city of Basilan, officially assumed for mayoralty post as town mayor of Isabela.</p>\r\n            <p>On March 5, 2001 Republic Act No. 9023 converted Isabela into a component city. On April 25, 2001, the Isabeleños ratified the said conversion making Luis R. Biel II as its first local chief executive.</p>\r\n            <p>On August 2001 by virtue of Republic Act 9054 or the Expanded Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM), Basilan became an administrative part of the new region. In a historic move, the Isabeleños opted for No to inclusion in ARMM. The City of Isabela has remained to be part of Region IX (Zambo- anga Peninsula).</p>\r\n            <p>In June 30, 2007, Cherrylyn Santos – Akbar became the first lady mayor in the City. She is determined to make Isabela as the “Promising City of the South” introducing several commitments and reforms to create a promising habitat for the Isabeleños.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Feast of Sta. Isabel on July 8</li>\r\n                <li>2. City’s Founding Anniversary / Cocowayan Festival on April 25</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/isabelaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Isabela City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Revel in the Cocowayan Festival, a week-long celebration in line with the City’s founding anniversary marked with fes- tive street dancing, colorful parade, sports activities, fairs, cultural and variety shows and beauty pageant.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Discover and enjoy the scenery of the unspoiled beaches like the white sands of the Malamawi beach. Enjoy trekking on the nearby mountain trails and see the panoramic view of Isabela Channel once one gets to the top.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Shop and savor the cheap and freshest variety of seafood and fruits.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Enjoy the City’s fiesta on July 8 in honor of Sta. Isabel de Portugal. Experience Isabeleños charm and warm hospitality.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Tour around the City’s picturesque landscape and rubber plantation. Explore the forest grounds of the City at Maligue Nursery and enjoy the clean and fresh air brought about by the tall trees that gives the feeling of being one with Mother Nature.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Isabela City Population: 987,985</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Visiting Isabela City is made possible by sea travel via Zam- boanga City. There are five trips plying the Zamboanga-Isa- bela channel. It takes about 45 minutes via fast craft and an average of one hour and twenty minutes for regular ferries.</p>\r\n            <p>In the urban areas, constituents and transients ride motor- ized tricycles. In the mountainous barangays, public utility jeepneys convey passengers and goods going in and out of the City proper.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Tourism Office, City Hall, Isabela City with telephone nos. (0917) 6344989 or email at cpdo_isabelacity@yahoo.com or melvinmanapol@yahoo.com</p>\r\n','Isabela City is the commercial center and capital of the island province of Basilan. The City is located in the northern part of Basilan.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/isabela',NULL,0,45,46,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:24:45','2012-09-12 06:24:00'),(60,NULL,1,'Kabankalan City','kabankalan','\r\n\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/kabankalanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <p>Kabankalan City occupies the central portion of the Southern Negros Island. It is 92 kilometers away from Bacolod City, the provincial capital of Negros Occidental and 126 kilometers to Dumaguete City, the provincial capital of Negros Oriental.</p>\r\n            <p>Kabankalan City has an agricultural-based economy. Fifty five percent (55%) of the land area is devoted to agriculture. The City’s main product is sugar.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Third week of January – for the Sinulog Festival</li>\r\n                <li>2. August 2 – for the Charter Day Anniversary /Udyakan Festival.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities.</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Mag-aso Leisure Camp – Brgy. Oringao</li>\r\n                <li>2. Balicaocao Eco-Park – Brgy. Orong Sinulog</li>\r\n                <li>3. Kabankalan Festival – Third week of January</li>\r\n                <li>4. Charter Day / Udyakan sa Kabankalan – August 2</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/kabankalanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <h3>Kabankalan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Stay in the City’s best accommodations like Zaycoland Resort & Hotel, South Gate Inn, Monbela Tourist Inn, Justine’s Guest House.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Eat sumptuous meals at City’s recognized homegrown restaurants like Alton Bar & Restaurant, RK’s Kalan- an, Ting-Tings Native Foods, Emilio’s Bistro, Bro’s Dinner, Melting Pot, and Reegal’s Refreshment.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Get the best deal in souvenir shopping in the City Showroom and City Public Market.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official name: City of Kabankalan</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 166,970 (NSO 2007); 177,286 (Projection 2011)</p>\r\n            <h3>For more travel information</h3>\r\n            <p>Please contact Office of the City Mayor with telephone nos. (034) 471-2291. Visit website at <a href=\"http://www.kabankalancity.gov.ph\" >www.kabankalancity.gov.ph</a>. Email for more queries at citytourism@yahoo.com.</p>\r\n','Kabankalan City occupies the central portion of the Southern Negros Island. It is 92 kilometers away from Bacolod City, the provincial',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/kabankalan',NULL,0,47,48,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:26:35','2012-09-12 06:25:00'),(61,NULL,1,'Kidapawan City','kidapawan','\r\n\r\n            <h3>City of Fruits and Highland Springs</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/kidapawanCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n\r\n            <p>The name Kidapawan is derived from the Manobo words Tida (spring) and Pawan (highland), hence, A Spring in the Highland. Its first settlers were predominantly Manobos, the City’s early settlers. The influx of Christian settlers from Luzon and the Visayas has resulted in the evolution of the word Tidapawan to Kidapawan.</p>\r\n            <p>Originally a district of Pikit, it was declared as a separate municipality on August 18, 1947. On February 12, 1998, former President Fidel Ramos signed Republic Act No. 8500 declaring Kidapawan a component city of the Province of Cotabato which was finally ratified on March 25, 1998.</p>\r\n            <p>Kidapawan City plays a pivotal role in the economic develop- ment of the province and its adjacent areas. It is the commercial and trading hub of six neighboring towns, and is strategically surrounded by cities of Davao, Digos, Tacurong, and General Santos.</p>\r\n            <p>All development efforts are geared towards establishing Kidapawan City as the province’s major service center that is linked to increased agricultural productivity, food sufficiency and agri-based industrialization. Envisioned as a Fruit City, the City strives to be livable, providing sufficient economic opportunities in a sustainable environment propelled by a God-centered and empowered constituency under an effective, dynamic and gender-sensitive leadership.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/kidapawanCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Kidapawan City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Climb Mt. Apo. It is the City’s major tourist destination. It has two climbing season. January to June is highlighted with an organized climb during summer time specifically during Holy Week. October to December is being highlighted with an organized climb on October during semestral break when students are given the chance to enjoy the season.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Avail of package tours like visiting two falls with bat caves and trekking activity.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Tour fruit farms. It is usually done during peak season of ripening and harvest time of fruits.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Visit flower farms where ornamental plants, materials and plants used for landscaping and bonsai are all available.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Participate in various events and festivals for the whole year round like the City’s foundation anniversary, The Timpupu Fruit Festival, The Pangavukad Flower Festival, Kanyon Kawayan Festival, Festival of Lights, Children Festival, Culinary Festival and October Fest.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Kidapawan</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 119, 771</p>\r\n','The name Kidapawan is derived from the Manobo words Tida (spring) and Pawan (highland), hence, A Spring in the Highland. Its first',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/kidapawan',NULL,0,49,50,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:27:28','2012-09-12 06:26:00'),(62,NULL,1,'City of Koronadal','koronadal','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Kanami Koronadal!</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfKoronadal1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n            <p>The name Koronadal was derived from the two Maguindanaoan words koron or kolon meaning cogon grass and nadal or dalal meaning plain. In the past, the place was called Marbel which comes from a B’laan word meaning murky waters. Such name best described when the City was inhabited by the natives.</p>\r\n            <p>It started as Marbel Settlement District created under Common- wealth Act No. 141 on January 10, 1940 for landless farmers from both Luzon and Visayas. From a handful of settlers, their number grew including their families and dependents. They were responsible in the clearing of the area and the construction of roads and bunkhouses.</p>\r\n            <p>The rapid development of Koronadal came when it was created as one of the municipalities of the Province of South Cotabato by President Manuel Roxas on August 18, 1947. It became a component city on October 08, 2000.</p>\r\n            <p>The City also became the Regional Center and Seat of SOCCSKSARGEN Region that further boosted the development of the City. The development of the City of Koronadal may be best described by the awards it has reaped in the recent years. Some include the Most Competitive Small Sized Cities in the Philip- pines (2005) and Most Business Friendly City in Mindanao in 2005 and 2006.</p>\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/cityOfKoronadal2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Best time to visit</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. January 10 – Koronadal Hinugyaw Festival</li>\r\n                <li>2. October 08 – Charter Anniversary</li>\r\n                <li>3. December 16-25 – Hinugyaw sa Pascua</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Koronadal Population: 149,662</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Approximate travel time by land from General Santos City (one hour), Cotabato City (two hours and 30 minutes), Tacurong City (40 minutes) and Davao City (4 hours)</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City of Koronadal Investment and Pro- motions Center at telephone nos. (083) 228-1731 or email at lgu_kor@hotmail.gov.ph</p>\r\n','The name Koronadal was derived from the two Maguindanaoan words koron or kolon meaning cogon grass and nadal or dalal',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/koronadal',NULL,0,51,52,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:28:24','2012-09-12 06:27:00'),(63,NULL,1,'Laoag City','laoag','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Sunshine City</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/laoagCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Laoag City, the Northern Gateway to the Philippines, is located at the west-central side of Ilocos Norte in Northern Philippines. It is the capital of Ilocos Norte province.</p>\r\n            <p>A vibrant and dynamic growth center in the North, the City offers a unique experience to tourists such as the panoramic La Paz sand dunes, historical and heritage sites, lush vegetation, scenic beaches, and highland lures.</p>\r\n            <p>The City’s tourist and cultural destinations have been nationally recognized like the Grand National Champion in 2004, 2006, 2008 in the Aliwan Float Competition during the Aliwan Festivals. It was also awarded as Champion in the Best Booth Competition at the 18th Philippine Travel Mart in 2007 and awarded by the Department of Tourism and Association of Tourism Officers of the Philippines as first runner up, Best in Cultural Festival with Pamulinawen Festival as the city’s entry in 2009.</p>\r\n            <p>Laoag City is one of the most liveable city and was adjudged as the fifth Most Livable City in the Philippines in the Philippine Cities Competitiveness Ranking Project by the Asian Institute of Management Policy Center. In 2010, Laoag City received the biggest number of local and foreign tourists, students on their field trips, and employees and officials of local governments and nongovernment organizations on their Lakbay–Aral sessions.</p>\r\n            <p>For its part, the City government has invested heavily on health and environmental projects. The old City Hospital was trans- formed into a 120-bed secondary, ultra-modern Medical Center. The City’s sanitary landfill has been converted into Sunshine City Material Recovery Facility where most waste materials are processed into organic fertilizer and building materials such as pavers and hollow blocks. Eco-friendly E-taxi, electronic jeeps and Smart bikes are being used by the police and traffic enforcers in their daily patrols.</p>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/laoagCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Laoag City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the St. William Cathedral, one of the biggest churches of the country. This 400- year old structure showcases the Spanish era and its impact on the Ilocano architecture and culture. The church’s belfry, the Sinking Bell Tower, is one of the city’s top attractions. It is said that a rider atop his horse could enter this edifice but has now sunk considerably that one must stoop low to be able to view its magnificent threshold.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Get to learn more about the City’s past through the Tobacco Monopoly, an obelisk of clay brick. This monument is the Ilocano’s way of thanking King Alfonso XII of Spain for rescinding the Monopoly. It stands prominently at the Aurora Park located at the foot of the magnificent Gilbert Bridge.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Feel the sand dunes in La Paz, a rare geological monument. This vast sand dune formation (the only one in the Philip- pines) offers a fine vista of the West Philippine Sea (South China Sea). It is a continually shifting body of sand that is prone to erosion. It is a favorite destination of 4x4 off road enthusiasts.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Stay in The Fort Ilocandia Resort and Casino, a five-star hotel in Northern Luzon. The resort is complete with different amenities designed to provide absolute satisfaction for the tourist and traveler alike. Explore The Museo Ilocos Norte as it showcases the varied ethnicity and multi-faceted cultural heritage of a sturdy, hard-working people known for their industry, resourcefulness, and loyalty.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Fill in your taste buds with the best of Ilocano cuisine. Signature vegetable dish include Pinakbet, a mix of fresh veg- etables steamed in fish sauce, the Longaniza or garlic-flavored pork sausage, and Bagnet (pan-fried pork meat). There are also equally tasty snacks and desserts such as Chichacorn (corn bits), Empanada (Latin-inspired fried bread dough stuffed with grated papaya and whole egg), Bibingka (oven-baked sticky rice cake), Tupig (sticky rice with young coconut in banana leaves), and Artem (pickels in sukang iloko).</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Laoag City Population: 103, 353</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Laoag City has an International Airport, a nearby Seaport in Currimao town, and numerous bus lines where people and goods are transited daily.</p>\r\n            <p>From Manila, it is 45 minutes by plane and 80 minutes from Hongkong and Macau. By land, it is a 12-hour trip.</p>\r\n            <p>Laoag is an hour drive north of the World Heritage City of Vigan.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Whole month of February – In time for the City’s Pamulinawen Festival, a month-long festivity in commemoration of St. William the Hermit, the Patron Saint of Laoag City, which is celebrated on February 10.\r\n                    It is during this time when Ilocano migrants from abroad, especially from Hawaii and California, come home and get recognized through coronation pageants and balls.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Laoag City Tourism and Social Concerns Council at telephone nos. (077) 772-0001 local 204 and/or (077) 773-1676 or email at lctourismcouncil@yahoo.com or mvflaoag@hotmail.com. Visit the city’s website at <a href=\"http://www.laoagcity.gov.ph\" >www.laoagcity.gov.ph</a></p>\r\n','Laoag City, the Northern Gateway to the Philippines, is located at the west-central side of Ilocos Norte in Northern Philippines.',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/laoag',NULL,0,53,54,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:29:23','2012-09-12 06:28:00'),(64,NULL,1,'Ligao City','ligao','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Where Good Things Happen</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/ligaoCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>The City of Ligao, located at the heart of the third district of Albay just below the majestic Mayon Volcano, holds a great potential for tourism and investments. It is naturally gifted with caves, hills, lakes, and coastal areas perfect for nature lovers and trekking enthusiasts.</p>\r\n            <p>Ligao is a decade-old city, once dubbed as a richly-endowed developing town in Albay. It is now considered as the trade cen- ter for the nearby municipalities of Pioduran, Oas, Guinobatan, Polangui and Libon.</p>\r\n            <p>Legend tells that Ligao was coined with the corruption of the word ticau, once an abundant tree whose poisonous leaves were popularly used to catch fish in rivers or creeks. It was also believed that the name came from licau which means to take the long way around or to turn away from the ordinary or usual route. Lastly, most believed that it came from the Tagalog word ‘ligaw’ meaning to court or win a lady’s love. This idea was based on the common knowledge that the place was then known for its beautiful maidens.</p>\r\n            <p>The City envisions to be an internationally competitive trade and educational center of the third district of Albay by year 2018. Its mission is to “turn Ligao City into a community of love, peace, equality, and prosperity; anchored on the following core values: love of God, love of country, love of community, vision- driven, innovativeness, resilience, transparency, culture of excel- lence, and discipline.”</p>\r\n            <p>Aside from the panoramic view of Mayon Volcano, Ligao is gifted with various breathtaking sceneries. One is the becoming more popular Kawa-Kawa Hill Natural Park. It has become a famous ecotourism destination especially for devotees of the Divine Mercy. The Carmelite nuns of the Holy Trinity have put up a monastery and life-sized images of the Station of the Cross that are spread out upward towards the top of the Hill (“without a top”).</p>\r\n            <p>The Hill has become a favorite venue for religious activities during Lenten Season, Christmas, and Three Kings which have become annual traditions for the visitors of Kawa-Kawa. Ligao City is also a home to various spring resorts that offer continuous flowing spring water for a cool deep relaxation.</p>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Kawa-Kawa Natural Park</li>\r\n                <li>2. Conservation Farming Villages Projects</li>\r\n                <li>3. Coastal Resource Management- Coastal Barangays 4. Christmas Mainstreet Parade</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/ligaoCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Ligao City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1 .Trek on top of the Kawa-Kawa Hill and Natural Park and Visit the Divine Mercy Oratory and Monastery of the Carmel- ite Nuns of the Holy Trinity. The place is a reflection of the residents’ religiosity, with life-sized sculptures of the Stations of the Cross placed on the way to the top. Souvenir shops are also found at the foot of the Hill.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Taste Ligao’s distinct native delicacies. Among others, the City boasts of the rice puto con macapuno that is made up of two layers of puto — one colored purple, the other is white, with macapuno filling in the middle. This can be bought along the highway of Paulog, Ligao City and also at the City Market.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Buy pili nuts in Edsel Morato Pili Sweets that is located in McKinley Street, Dunao, Ligao City. It is said that pili nuts that are prepared in Ligao stand out as one of the best in the Bicol region.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Dance with Walt Disney characters in giant floats every December 25 during the Christmas Mainstreet Parade competition. It is one of the activities for the feast day of Ligao City’s Patron Saint, St. Stephen, the Protomartyr, which coincides with the Christmas Season.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Learn from Ligao City’s innovative and outstanding local governance practices, programs, and projects. The local government was awarded as the top performing city in the component city category for 2010, given by the Department of Interior and Local Government in their Local Governance Performance Management System (LGPMS) Report.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: Ligao City Population: 101,179 (August 2007)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Ligao City is located 525 kilometers, a 10-12 hour ride via bus. It is 27 kilometers from the provincial capitol of Albay and 30 kilometers from Legazpi City.</p>\r\n            <p>From Manila, it is a 45-minute ride by plane via Legazpi City and an hour-ride from Legazpi City.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. December is the best time to visit Ligao City because of (1) The Lighting of the giant Christmas tree on the first Sunday of December, (2) Patiribayan sa Ligao, a traditional amateur and dance contest every Friday night starting October, (3) Christmas Cheers, a nightly program starting December 16 (in time with the Start of the Misa de Gallo), the (4) Mainstreet Parade, a parade of Walt Disney characters depicted by groups of students, teachers and barangay officials and (5) the Fiesta Celebration on December 26.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Mayor’s Office at (052)-485-1385. Visit Ligao City website at <a href=\"http://www.ligaocity.org\" >www.ligaocity.org</a></p>\r\n','The City of Ligao, located at the heart of the third district of Albay just below the majestic Mayon Volcano, holds a great potential',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/ligao',NULL,0,55,56,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:30:03','2012-09-12 06:29:00'),(65,NULL,1,'Lipa City','lipa','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Little Rome of the Philippines</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/lipaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Lipa City is a pilgrim’s paradise and an ideal tourist destination. Many years back, the City has welcomed busloads of people who are mostly pilgrims. Almost always, they visit the Carmelite Monastery Chapel, the site of the 1948 apparition of Mary Mediatrix of All Grace.</p>\r\n            <p>Meanwhile, others visit the city government and its ongoing programs. There are regular tourists who simply come to the city. When they come, they learn about the city in its totality; its history, what it is today, and what it envisions for tomorrow.</p>\r\n            <p>But a story which the visitor should hear is the saga of Lipa’s dramatic past, when in the late 19th century, it was the world’s center of coffee trade, the richest in the country, the celebrated Lipa of the coffee days.</p>\r\n            <p>The vision for Lipa City is the revival of yesterday and infinitely much more. The people, therefore, look forward to a future where they live and work and enjoy everything in a progressive and God – loving City. The welfare of the people is in their own hands because they are part of the whole governance.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. January 20 – It is a week-long celebration of the City Fiesta culminating in the Feast of Saint Sebastian.</li>\r\n                <li>2. June 20 – It is the commemoration of the Cityhood of Lipa.</li>\r\n                <li>3. September 12 – It is the annual National Day of Prayer in remembrance of the phenomenal Apparition of the Virgin Mary. People from all over the Philippines gather at Carmelite grounds to pray for world peace and other intentions.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/lipaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Lipa City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Visit the City’s Churches - the San Sebastian Cathedral, the Carmelite Chapel, and the Divino Amor Chapel, Metropoli- tan Cathedral of San Sebastian, and the Carmelite Monastery Chapel.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Dine at Lipa Grille, Gotohan sa Barangay, Lomi King, and Lipa Panciteria for the best in the city’s culinary adventure.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit The Farm at San Benito, the Community Parks, Bluroze Farm, Agricultura Filipina, Mega Orchid Farms, Museo de Lipa and the Malarayat Golf & Country Club for wellness, educational, and leisure destination.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Explore the heritage houses like Casa de Segunda, the home of Segunda Solis Katigbak, the first love interest of the national hero, Dr. Jose Rizal; the house of Don Brigido Morada, a Filipino propagandist; and Museo de Lipa which houses artifacts and other memorabilia of the past.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Get the best souvenirs in Ala Eh! Shirt, Saplot Batangueño Shirt/ Souvenirs, Papelipa Arts and Crafts - Banay-Banay and religious articles in Lipa Carmel Monastery and Paulines.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Lipa Population: 260,568 (2007 Census)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, it is an 84 kilometers bus ride or a one and half hour drive from NAIA via the South Luzon Expressway (SLEX) and the Southern Tagalog Arterial Road (STAR) toll- way using Lipa Exit.</p>\r\n            <p>From the Batangas International Port, it is a 30-minute drive via STAR tollway Lipa Exit.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. October-February (coolest months in the city) For travel information\r\n                    Please contact the Lipa City Tourism & Museum Council, Plaza Independencia, Lipa City at telephone nos. (043) 784- 2537 and the City Planning and Development Office, City Hall Compound, Marawoy, Lipa City at telephone nos. (043) 784-2552 or 784-2512</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n','Lipa City is a pilgrim’s paradise and an ideal tourist destination. Many years back, the City has welcomed busloads of people who',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/lipa',NULL,0,57,58,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:30:46','2012-09-12 06:30:00'),(66,NULL,1,'Lucena City','lucena','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Gateway to the South / The Coco Palm City of the South</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/lucenaCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Lucena City is the capital of Quezon Province. Though compris- ing only one percen of the province’s big total area, Lucena is a bustling urbanized city that is wedged between the majestic and mystic Mt. Banahaw in the northwest and the placid waters of Tayabas Bay in the south. The City is a vibrant community with a mixed culture as large number of migrants comes and goes either to permanently settle or do business.</p>\r\n            <p>Early Spaniards called the present site of Lucena City Buenavista because of its breathtaking beauty. Lucena has grown from a small barrio of Tayabas (now Quezon) province to the bustling and vibrant metropolis it is today.</p>\r\n            <p>Visitors will appreciate the Lucenahin’s gentle nature and respect for tradition. They are known for their warm hospitality and friendly manner.</p>\r\n            <p>In terms of industries and livelihood, Lucena produces agro industrial-based products, dried and smoked fish, bamboo and rattan furniture, ornamental flowers and plants, vegetable and processed meat products.</p>\r\n            <p>There is also the litsunan in barangay Cotta; beaches and grilled fish in Dalahican; poultry in Ibabang Talim and Gulang-Gulang; tapahan and tikoy in Ibabang Dupay and Marketview; coconut and rice farming, including copra-making in the Mayao areas.</p>\r\n            <p>Lucena is positioning itself as the New Convention Destination of the Philippines. First rate hotels and convention facilities, as well as leisure and recreation venues are sprouting all over. Small and large gatherings will find all they need to relax, enjoy the sun and sand, sample the cuisine, and still do business.</p>\r\n            <p>With excellent yet reasonably priced accommodation and convention venues, the City boasts of its unique tradition and culture, friendly and hospitable people, highly-trained manpower, tourism development support facilities and infrastructures like well paved road network and transportation and common terminal facility and complete amenities for corporate and leisure activities.</p>\r\n            <h3>Major destinations and cultural festivities</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. St. Ferdinand Cathedral and Perez Park</li>\r\n                <li>2. Lucena Fish Port</li>\r\n                <li>3. Provincial Capitol Building and the City Hall (Main and An- nex Building)</li>\r\n                <li>4. Pasayahan sa Lucena (May 24-30) and Araw ng Lucena (August 20)</li>\r\n                <li>5. Panunuluyan / Lantern and Christmas Carol Competition (every 2nd week of December)</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/lucenaCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Lucena City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Try the City’s native products like the tinapa (smoked fish) and chami (a locally manufactured noodle).</li>\r\n                <li>2. Visit Lucena’s Fish Port in Barangay Dalahican and pick the freshest seafoods.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Visit Lucena’s historical landmarks like Manuel L. Quezon Heritage Site, Perez Park, St. Ferdinand Cathedral, Quezon Provincial Capitol Building, and the Lucena City Hall (Main Building).</li>\r\n                <li>4. Eat in the City’s best restaurants like Queen Margarette Court (Diversion Road, Brgy. Domoit); Grand Riviera Hotel (Diversion Road, Brgy. Ilayang Dupay); South Waters Marina and Country Club (Brgy. Ibabang Iyam); Ouans Worth Farm (Diversion Road, Brgy. Kanlurang Mayao); Lucena Fresh Air Hotel (Maharlika H-way, Brgy. Isabang); Restorante de Lucena (Quezon Avenue); Hacienda Inn (Quezon Avenue); Mug Café (Pacific Mall; JM Premiere Cuisine (Quezon Avenue); Buddy Pizza (Quezon Avenue); Plaza Food House (Profugo St.); and Koffee Klatch (Quezon Avenue)</li>\r\n                <li>5. Buy the latest souvenirs in La Moda Filipina (cor. Enverga and Merchan Sts.); Lucena Public Market. For sweets and pasalubong: Villamater (Quezon Avenue); Galeon Sweets and Pasalubong (Quezon Avenue); and Koffee Klatch (Quezon Avenue).</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Lucena</p>\r\n            <p>Population: 258,142 (population projection for 2010)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>From Manila, Lucena City lies approximately 137 kilometers southeast and can be reached by an approximately two to three-hour land trip via the Maharlika Highway.</p>\r\n            <p>Lucena also has a major domestic passenger seaport which serves as the gateway to Southern Tagalog with passengers coming from the island-provinces of Marinduque, Masbate, Palawan, and Romblon and Bicol Region.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. May - Summertime is Lucena’s best time with the Pasaya- han sa Lucena as the City’s main showcase.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the City Mayor, City Hall Main Building, M.L. Tagarao St., Lucena City, with telephone nos. 373-5931 to 34.</p>\r\n','Lucena City is the capital of Quezon Province. Though compris- ing only one percen of the province’s big total area, Lucena is a',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/lucena',NULL,0,59,60,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:31:31','2012-09-12 06:30:00'),(67,NULL,1,'Makati City','makati','\r\n\r\n            <h3>The Financial Center of the Philippines</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/makatiCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>Even before this once vast swampland was discovered and dismissed by Juan Miguel de Legazpi as ‘worthless’, Makati had been a part of the Kingdom of Namayan, a territory that stretched from Manila Bay to Laguna de Bay.</p>\r\n            <p>During the Spanish period, the area was colloquially known as Sampiro, a corruption of San Pedro de Makati, formerly the town’s official name. The friars established two churches in the area – the Nuestra Señora de Gracia in Guadalupe and the Church of Sts. Peter and Paul in Poblacion.</p>\r\n            <p>At the turn of the 20th century, Makati became a popular re- treat destination of Manila’s elite. Summer villas were construct- ed along the banks of Pasig River. In the 1930s, Nielson Airport, the country’s first airport, opened in what is now Ayala Triangle. Since the 1970s, Makati has been the undisputed financial capital of the country, transforming the once worthless swampland into a prime real property.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, one can marvel at the high-rise concrete jungle that is the Makati Central Business District, yet at the same time experience the local charm of City’s heritage district, Poblacion. The City continues to be a fusion of the new and the old, a bustling economic mecca with a warm soulful core.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. January – The Caracol Festival, a celebration of Mother Earth’s bounty while promoting environmental conservation. This is celebrated every last Sunday of the month.</li>\r\n                <li>2. March and April – The Barangay Poblacion is popular among pilgrims for its Lenten activities which include the kalbaryos, car- rozas, senakulo, and salubong.</li>\r\n                <li>3. May – Numerous events such as Flores de Mayo, Miss Makati, and the Grand Parade are held in the weeks leading to Araw ng Makati, which is on June 01.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/makatiCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Makati City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Pray. Get in touch with your spiritual side at Nuestra Señora de Gracia Church in Guadalupe and Sts. Peter and Paul Church in Poblacion.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Learn. Brush up on your local history and culture at the Ayala Museum, Filipinas Heritage Library, Yuchengco Museum, and Museo ng Makati.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Chill. Relax and destress at Greenbelt Park, Ayala Triangle, and Makati Park and Garden.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Hang out. Eat, drink, or party at the hottest spots in Ayala Center, Rockwell, Jupiter Street, and Makati Avenue. 5. Walk. Reconnect with the City’s past in Barangay Poblacion and awe with the present in Ayala Avenue.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Makati Population: 471,379 (2007 census);</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Located at the heart of Metro Manila, one can get to Makati through the following:</p>\r\n            <p>By land - The city has four MRT stations (Guadalupe, Buendia, Ayala, and Magallanes). Provincial and city buses ply through EDSA daily. Taxis and numerous jeepney routes also connect Makati to other Metro Manila cities.</p>\r\n            <p>By air - The city is just 15-30 minutes away from the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.</p>\r\n            <p>By sea -The city is 30-45 minutes away from the Port of Manila.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Makati City Tourism Office at 3F Old Makati City Hall at telephone nos. 899-8954 / 870-1424. Email at turismo@makati.gov.ph.</p>\r\n','Even before this once vast swampland was discovered and dismissed by Juan Miguel de Legazpi as ‘worthless’, Makati had been',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/makati',NULL,0,61,62,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:32:14','2012-09-12 06:31:00'),(68,NULL,1,'Malaybalay City','malaybalay','\r\n\r\n            <h3>Cool Place, Warm People</h3>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/malaybalayCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Third week of February – Kaamulan Festival. Celebrated from the third week of February until the second week of March, the famed yearly Kaamulan Festival records a growth of visitors at- tending this colorful and authentic cultural activity. Both foreign and local tourists are in total awe of the ethnic music, rituals and dances of the seven different tribes of Bukid- non. Meaning “gathering for a purpose” in the tribal language, Kaamulan is celebrated by the whole province as thanksgiving to the Magbabaya (God) for bountiful harvest and continuing prog- ress. Kaamulan is highlighted by a street dancing revelry.</li>\r\n                <li>2. May 15 – City Fiesta in honor of Patron San Isidro every May 15.</li>\r\n                <li>3. June 15 – Aldaw ta Malaybalay, the City’s Foundation Day.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/malaybalayCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Malaybalay City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Enjoy a healthy lifestyle by brisk walking and jogging at the Capitol Grounds on early mornings or late afternoon. The Provincial Capitol Grounds is perfect for sports and other activities for families and groups to bond and enjoy the refresh- ing site and cool air.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Play frisbee and soccer games during lazy afternoons and carefree weekends at the Capitol Grounds.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Commune with nature through rugged walking and running at the Kaamulan Tree Park. The Kaamulan Tree Park is a vast area of pine trees, creek, and natural garden that is located downside of the Provincial Capitol.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Experience a spiritual sanctuary of art and nature and partake a Breakfast with the Monks at the Monastery of Trans- figuration every second Sunday of the month. The Monastery of the Transfiguration, a religious site of the Benedictine Monks, is a famous destination for tourists, a favorite venue for weddings and home to the world renowned Monks Blend Coffee produced by the Monastery Farms.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Enjoy a variety of delectable delicacies and scrumptious recipes at Anton’s, Cuadra, Rey’s Grill, Benedict’s, Centro Chicken Neck, Bukidnon Brew Café, Mint Leaf Café and Le’ Café.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h3>Profile</h3>\r\n            <p>Official Name: City of Malaybalay Population: 148,347 (2009 MISS Survey)</p>\r\n            <h4>How to get there</h4>\r\n            <p>Daily flights to Cagayan de Oro from Manila, Cebu and Davao have made travel easier to reach Malaybalay City. Ships and ferries are also scheduled daily bounding to Cagayan de Oro City.</p>\r\n            <p>Just 91 kilometers from Cagayan de Oro City, Malaybalay City can be reached by bus which is available 24 hours. Buses from Davao and the southern provinces of Mindanao also ply the Bukidnon route with a convenient stop-over in Malaybalay. Air conditioned buses and vans are also avail- able for those who choose maximum travel comfort.</p>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact Malaybalay City Tourism Office, City Hall with telephone nos. (088)- 221-4143 local 104 or (0917) 4329900.</p>\r\n','Cool Place, Warm People',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/malaybalay',NULL,0,63,64,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:35:02','2012-09-12 06:32:00'),(69,NULL,1,'Mandaue City','mandaue','\r\n\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/mandaueCity1.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <p>One of only two highly urbanized cities in the Central Visayas Region, Mandaue City has a long history of commerce. During the time of Magellan, people were trading vigorousy their goods with the other villages. One Spanish ruler also mentioned in his communication to Spain that Mandawe, the old City’s name, was famous for its artistic carpentry and skilled carpenters.</p>\r\n            <p>As early as 1575, the Philippine pieces of furniture that were mostly hand carved in hardwood by Mandauehanons found their way into the households of prominent citizens in Spain. The Spaniards chose Saint Joseph as the patron saint of this town because they noted that the natives were very hard working.</p>\r\n            <p>Mandaue’s earlier lucrative industries were salt making and fishpond production, which provided income and employment to the people. It also developed its ceramics industries and bam- boo crafts. In the late 1800s and early 1900s, rice and sugar were extensively raised.</p>\r\n            <p>The industrialization of Mandaue progressed when it became a chartered city, from Mandawe to Mandaue, on August 30, 1969 upon the approval of the Republic Act No. 5519. The City has sustained growth and development that begun as early as 1960s when the City adopted measures to industrialize. Then Mayor Demetrio Cortes launched a massive campaign to lure business entrepreneurs to invest in Mandaue. Within ten years, the town which once relied heavily on agriculture developed into a major job opportunity basin and residential area and a minor port of trade and navigation.</p>\r\n            <p>As of 2001, the city has 391 export and import private manufacturing firms and has more than 8,000 major business establish- ments engaged in local and domestic trade, wholesale and retail merchandising and services.</p>\r\n            <p>Today, Mandaue is Cebu’s new economic driver with more than 10,000 business establishments. About 40 percent of Cebu’s export companies are found in Mandaue. The City also contributes at least 75 percent of the country’s total furniture export production. The City was also tagged by the Asian Institute of Management and the Department of Trade and Industry as the “little rich city”, notwithstanding its limited land area.</p>\r\n            <h4>Best time to visit</h4>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Comparsa sa Mandawe (last week of August) – Comparsa is a dance theatre competition among different youth groups that were used to be held in Mandaue in the late 50’s and 60’s. The Festival is akin to the traditional “comparsa” except that it ac- commodates all types of live instrumentation.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Sugat and Fluvial Parade of Sto. Nino (“The Traslacion”) – Third Friday and Saturday of January - Perhaps the most religious among Filipinos, Cebuanos come together to venerate the first religious relic brought by Magellan more than 480 years ago.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Mandaue City Fiesta (May 08) – Perhaps considered Mandaue’s biggest event, the Fiesta honors the City’s patron saint, St. Joseph. It is celebrated with the traditional blend of religious, sports, and other cultural activities.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n\r\n            <img src=\"/theme/weatherph/img/tourism/mandaueCity2.png\" alt=\"\">\r\n\r\n            <h3>Mandaue City’s Must Do List</h3>\r\n            <ol>\r\n                <li>1. Shop in Mandaue’s three existing big shopping destinations. Gaisano Super Metro is one of the oldest and is expand- ing to be one of the first class malls in Cebu. The stylish Parkmall features many first class restaurants. S&R is the latest addition to the emerging urban face of the City which is located in the reclamation area.</li>\r\n                <li>2. Eat Mandaue’s sumptuous native delicacy. Mandaue prides itself as the bibingka capital of the country. The City’s main delicacies are bibingka, tagaktak (made of grind rice and fried in hot oil) and the masareal (made from peanuts and milk). Foreign restaurants are to be found in the uptown area along A.S. Fortuna Street.</li>\r\n                <li>3. Organize a Convention. Hosting the 12th Association of Southeast Asian Nation (ASEAN) in 2006, Mandaue City and the Cebu provincial government have built the Cebu International Convention Center, a landmark that became one of its kind for convention in the southern Philippines.</li>\r\n                <li>4. Witness festival and other cultural activities. The City has a number of festivals celebrated every year. The Comparsa sa Mandawe is celebrated every charter day of Mandaue City in August. Also on the same month, the Pasigarbo sa Sugbo, which celebrates the founding anniversary of Cebu Province that is co-hosted by Mandaue City and the Cebu Provincial Government. All cities and municipalities of Cebu send their respective festivals for a showdown dubbed as the “Festival of Festivals” in Mandaue. Before Sinulog, the “Traslacion” arrives at the National Shrine of St. Joseph in Mandaue City in preparation for the Fluvial Procession.</li>\r\n                <li>5. Visit heritage sites: Mandaue has 12 heritage sites being one of the prime projects to develop and respect Mandaue’s past. Mandaue also joined the yearly celebrated Gabii sa Kabilin (Heritage Night) every May 27. The aim of the event is to allow more people to access all museums in Metro Cebu at a packaged discount price including transfers to and from destination points. Some of the heritages sites are the National Shrine of St. Joseph, Bantayan sa Hari, Mandaue Presidencia, Town Plaza, Rizal-Bonifacio Memorial Stage and Library, Mandaue City Central School , Angel Suico Ancestral House, Eversly Childs Sanitarium, Ernesto C. Ouano Ancestral House and the Mandaue Mactan Bridge.</li>\r\n            </ol>\r\n            <h4>For travel information</h4>\r\n            <p>Please contact the Mandaue City Tourism Office and Visitors Information Center, 2nd Floor, Land Bank Building Centro, Mandaue City at telephone nos. at (032) 343-9091 or tele- fax (032) 343-9092. Visit <a href=\"http://www.mandauecity.gov.ph\" >www.mandauecity.gov.ph</a>. Email at mandaue_tourism@yahoo.com.ph.</p>\r\n','One of only two highly urbanized cities in the Central Visayas Region, Mandaue City has a long history of commerce. During the time of',1,NULL,1,0,1,'/visit/mandaue',NULL,0,65,66,'','visit','2012-09-12 06:35:52','2012-09-12 06:35:00'),(70,NULL,1,'asdasd','asdasd','','',1,NULL,2,0,1,'/nodes/view/type:announcements/slug:asdasd',NULL,0,1,2,'','announcements','2012-09-24 06:59:49','2012-09-24 06:59:00'),(71,NULL,1,'Payong Panahon','payong-panahon','PAYONG PANAHONHONHONHON','',1,NULL,2,0,1,'/news/payong-panahon',NULL,0,1,2,'','news','2012-09-24 07:22:53','2012-09-24 07:21:00'),(72,NULL,1,'Stay Indoors','stay-indoors','dgjaklsdfhgasdi;fyhweklfad\r\nsgfasdfasd[fdkasdk\r\nasd\'f;asd\r\nfaskkls;dfkl;asfkas\r\ndafafa\r\nasdf\r\nkldfgkdf\r\nhgkjkmhgj\'lkghdfklhnufkguadfkljghjksdkjashgkjhasdkjghdakjhkadfjhgkjasdhgfkriryn nmgjkfmGb\r\n','When you eat chili. you\'re gonna have a baaaaad time~',1,NULL,2,0,1,'/news/stay-indoors',NULL,0,3,4,'','news','2012-09-24 07:24:33','2012-09-24 07:23:00');
